Withdrawal is perhaps twice as hard as Login, so we’ll say it’s a 6. Deposit is similar to Withdrawal but perhaps not quite as hard, so we’ll give it a 5. Finally, Transfer is about the same as Login, so we’ll give it a 3.

我们将这些数字写在我们估计的每张故事卡的一角。稍后我将详细讨论估算过程。现在，假设我们现在有一批故事卡片，其估计范围从 1 到 6。为什么是 1 到 6？为什么不？有许多分配成本的方案。越简单的通常越好。

We write these numbers up in one corner of each story card that we estimate. I’ll talk much more about the estimation process later. For now, let’s just say that we now have a batch of story cards with estimates on them that range from 1 to 6. Why 1 to 6? Why not? There are many schemes for assigning cost. The simpler ones are usually better.

此时，您可能想知道这些点真正测量的是什么。也许您认为它们是小时、天、周或其他时间单位。他们不是。相反，它们是估计工作量的单位，而不是实时的。它们甚至不是估计的时间——它们是估计的努力。

At this point, you may be wondering what these points are really measuring. Perhaps you think they are hours, days, weeks, or some other unit of time. They are not. Rather, they are a unit of estimated effort, not real time. They are not even estimated time—they are estimated effort.

故事点应该大致呈线性。一张 2 的牌需要的力应该是一张 4 的牌的一半。然而，线性度不一定是完美的。请记住，这些是估计值，因此有意将精度保持在较宽范围内。如果 Jim 没有被现场的 bug 分心，一个 3 的故事可能需要两天时间才能实现。或者，如果帕特在家工作，她可能只需要一天时间。这些数字是模糊的、模糊的、不精确的东西，与实时没有直接关系。

Story points should be roughly linear. A card with a 2 should require about half the effort of a card with a 4. However, the linearity doesn’t have to be perfect. Remember, these are estimates, so precision is kept intentionally wide. A story with a 3 might take Jim two days to implement if he doesn’t get distracted by a bug in the field. Or it might take Pat only one day if she works at home on it. These numbers are vague, fuzzy, imprecise things that do not relate directly to real time.

但是模糊和模糊的数字有一个美丽的地方。它被称为大数定律。4量入为出，浑然一体！我们稍后会利用它。

But there is a beautiful thing about vague and fuzzy numbers. It’s called the Law of Large Numbers.4 When taken in quantity, the fuzziness integrates out! We’re going to take advantage of that later.

4 . https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_of_large_numbers

4. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_of_large_numbers

计划迭代一

同时，是时候计划第一次迭代了。迭代从迭代计划会议(IPM) 开始。该会议应安排在迭代持续时间的二十分之一。两周迭代的 IPM 应该需要大约半天的时间。

Meanwhile, it’s time to plan the first iteration. The iteration begins with the Iteration Planning Meeting (IPM). This meeting should be scheduled to be one-twentieth the duration of the iteration. The IPM for a two-week iteration should require about a half a day.

整个团队都参加了 IPM。这包括利益相关者、程序员、测试人员和项目经理。涉众之前会阅读估计的故事，并按照商业价值的顺序对它们进行排序。一些团队实际上为该业务价值选择数字，类似于用于故事点的技术。其他团队只关注商业价值。

The whole team attends the IPM. This includes the stakeholders, the programmers, the testers, and the project manager. The stakeholders will have previously read the estimated stories and sorted them in the order of business value. Some teams actually choose numbers for that business value, similar to the technique used for the story points. Other teams just eyeball the business value.

IPM 的利益相关者的工作是选择将在迭代期间由程序员和测试人员实施的故事。为此，他们需要知道程序员认为他们可以完成多少个故事点。这个数字称为速度。当然，由于这是第一次迭代，所以没有人真正知道速度会是多少。所以团队做出了猜测。假设猜测是 30。

The job of the stakeholders at the IPM is to choose the stories that will be implemented by the programmers and testers during the iteration. To do this, they need to know how many story points the programmers think they can complete. This number is called the velocity. Of course, since this is the first iteration, no one has any real idea what the velocity is going to be. So the team makes a guess. Let’s say that guess is 30.

重要的是要认识到速度不是一种承诺。团队并没有承诺在迭代期间完成 30 分。他们甚至没有做出努力完成 30 分的承诺。这只不过是他们对迭代结束时将完成多少点的最佳猜测。这个猜测可能不是很准确。

It’s important to realize that velocity is not a commitment. The team is not making a promise to get 30 points done during the iteration. They aren’t even making the promise to try to get 30 points done. This is nothing more than their best guess as to how many points will be complete by the end of the iteration. That guess is probably not very accurate.

投资回报

现在利益相关者玩四象限游戏（图 3.2）。

Now the stakeholders play the four-quadrant game (Figure 3.2).

有价值但廉价的故事将立即完成。那些有价值但昂贵的将在以后完成。那些既不值钱也不贵的，说不定哪天就做完了。那些不值钱但很贵的永远不会做。

The stories that are valuable but cheap will be done right away. Those that are valuable but expensive will be done later. Those that are neither valuable nor expensive might get done one day. Those that are not valuable but are expensive will never be done.

这是投资回报率 (ROI) 计算。它不是正式制作的，也不需要数学。利益相关者只需查看卡片并根据其价值和估计成本做出判断。

This is a return on investment (ROI) calculation. It’s not made formally, and no math is necessary. The stakeholders simply look at the card and make a judgement based on its value and its estimated cost.

因此，例如：“登录非常重要；但它也很贵。我们等等吧。注销也很重要，而且很便宜。做吧！提款是昂贵的——真的很贵。但首先展示该功能也很重要。那就去做吧。”

So, for example: “Login is pretty important; but it’s also pretty expensive. Let’s wait. Logout is important too, and it’s quite cheap. Do it! Withdrawal is expensive—really expensive. But it’s also important to show that feature off first. So do it.”

这就是这个过程的工作原理。利益相关者扫描故事的甲板，寻找那些具有最高性价比和最高投资回报率的故事。当他们找到足够的分数加起来达到 30 分时，他们就会停止。这就是迭代的计划。

That’s how the process works. The stakeholders scan the deck of stories for those that have the highest bang for buck, the highest ROI. When they find enough to add up to 30 points, they stop. That’s the plan for the iteration.

中点检查

让我们开始工作吧。稍后我将详细解释开发故事所涉及的过程。现在，假设有一些程序可以将故事转化为工作代码。将其视为将故事卡片从计划堆移动到已完成堆。

Let’s get to work. I’ll explain the process involved in developing the stories in detail later. For now, just imagine that there is some procedure for turning stories into working code. Think of it as moving story cards from the planned pile to the done pile.

在迭代的中点，应该做很多故事。这些故事的总和应该是多少？没错，15。要做这个过程，你必须能除以二。

At the midpoint of the iteration, many stories should be done. What should the point total of those stories add up to? That’s right, 15. To do this process, you must be able to divide by two.

那么，让我们召开中期审查会议吧。现在是星期一早上，迭代第二周的第一天。团队与利益相关者会面，他们会查看进展情况。

So, let’s call the midpoint review meeting. It’s Monday morning, the first day of the second week of the iteration. The team gathers with the stakeholders, and they look at the progress.

呃哦，完成的故事加起来才10分。只剩下一周了，他们不太可能再完成 20 分。因此，利益相关者从计划中删除了足够多的故事，将剩余的点数减少到 10。

Uh oh, the completed stories only add up to 10 points. With only a week left, it’s not likely that they are going to get 20 more points done. So the stakeholders remove enough stories from the plan to reduce the remaining points to 10.

到周五下午，迭代以演示结束。结果只完成了18个点。这次迭代失败了吗？

By Friday afternoon, the iteration concludes with a demo. It turns out only 18 points were completed. Has this iteration failed?

不！迭代不会失败。迭代的目的是为管理者生成数据。如果迭代也生成工作代码就好了，但即使没有，它仍然会生成数据。

No! Iterations do not fail. The purpose of an iteration is to generate data for managers. It would be nice if the iteration also generated working code, but even when it doesn’t it has still generated data.

昨天的天气

现在我们知道我们一周可以做多少点：大约 18 个。下周一开始下一次迭代时，利益相关者应该计划多少点？当然是十八岁。这叫做昨天的天气。今天天气最好的预报器是昨天的天气。迭代进度的最佳预测器是前一次迭代。

Now we know how many points we can do in a week: about 18. On Monday, when the next iteration begins, how many points should the stakeholders plan for? Eighteen, of course. This is called yesterday’s weather. The best predictor of today’s weather is yesterday’s weather. The best predictor of the progress of an iteration is the previous iteration.

因此，在 IPM 上，利益相关者选择了加起来为 18 分的故事。但这一次，在中点复习的时候，却发生了奇怪的事情。完成了12个点。我们应该告诉他们吗？

So at the IPM, the stakeholders select stories that add up to 18 points. But this time, at the midpoint review, something strange has happened. There are 12 points done. Should we tell them?

我们不必。他们可以亲眼看到。因此，利益相关者向计划中添加了 6 个要点，计划总数为 24 个。

We don’t have to. They can see it for themselves. So the stakeholders add six more points to the plan, for a planned total of 24.

当然，团队实际上只完成了 22 个。因此下一次迭代将选择 22 个。

Of course, the team really only completes 22. So 22 will be chosen for the next iteration.

项目结束

它是这样的。随着每次迭代的完成。完成的速度被添加到速度图表中，这样每个人都可以看到团队的速度。

And on it goes like this. As each iteration completes. the completed velocity is added to the velocity chart, so that everyone can see how fast the team is going.

现在想象这个过程继续进行，迭代后迭代，月复一月。那副故事卡发生了什么事？将迭代周期想象成一个从甲板上抽出投资回报率的泵。将对需求的不断探索视为将 ROI 泵回甲板的泵。只要传入的 ROI 超过传出的 ROI，项目就会继续。

Now imagine that this process continues, iteration after iteration, month after month. What is happening to that deck of story cards? Think of the iteration cycle as a pump that pumps the ROI out of that deck. Think of the continuous exploration of the requirements as a pump that pumps ROI back into the deck. As long as incoming ROI outpaces the outgoing ROI, the project will continue.

但是，可能会出现探索中发现的新特征数量逐渐下降为零的情况。当这种情况发生时，甲板上剩余的 ROI 将在再进行几次迭代后耗尽。总有一天，在 IPM 上，利益相关者会扫视一切，寻找值得做的事情，但一无所获。项目结束了。

However, it may happen that the number of new features discovered in exploration gradually sinks to zero. When that happens, the remaining ROI in the deck will be exhausted after just a few more iterations. The day will come when, at the IPM, the stakeholders scan the deck for something worth doing and find nothing. The project is over.

当所有的故事都被实施时，项目还没有结束。当甲板上没有更多值得实施的故事时，项目就结束了。

The project is not over when all the stories are implemented. The project is over when there are no more stories in the deck worth implementing.

项目结束后，甲板上剩下的东西有时令人惊讶。我曾经参与过一个为期一年的项目，其中写的第一个故事，也就是给项目命名的故事，从未被选中实施。这个故事在当时很重要，但还有许多更紧迫的故事需要实施。当所有这些紧急故事都得到解决时，原始故事的重要性已经消失。

It is sometimes amazing what is left in the deck after the project is over. I once worked on a year-long project where the very first story written, the story that gave the project its name, was never chosen for implementation. That story was important at the time, but there were many more urgent stories to implement. By the time all those urgent stories were resolved, the importance of the original story had evaporated.

故事

Stories

用户故事是我们用作功能提醒的简单陈述。我们在编写故事时尽量不记录太多细节，因为我们知道这些细节可能会发生变化。详细信息稍后记录，但作为验收测试，我们将在稍后讨论。

User stories are simple statements that we use as reminders of features. We try not to record too much detail when we write the story because we know that those details will likely change. The details are recorded later, but as acceptance tests, which we’ll discuss later.

故事遵循一套简单的指导方针，我们用首字母缩略词INVEST记住这些指导方针。

Stories follow a simple set of guidelines that we remember with the acronym INVEST.

  • 我：独立。用户故事是相互独立的。这意味着它们不需要以任何特定顺序实施。Login不需要在Logout之前实现。

  • I: Independent. User stories are independent of each other. This means that they do not need to be implemented in any particular order. Login does not need to be implemented before Logout.

这是一个软性要求，因为很可能有些故事依赖于首先实施的其他故事。例如，如果我们定义没有任何忘记密码恢复的登录，那么显然密码恢复在某种程度上取决于登录。尽管如此，我们仍尝试将故事分开，以尽可能减少依赖性。这使我们能够按照业务价值的顺序实施故事。

This is a soft requirement because there may well be stories that depend on other stories being implemented first. For example, if we define Login without any forgotten password recovery, then clearly Password Recovery depends, to some extent, upon Login. Still, we try to separate the stories so that there is as little dependence as possible. This allows us to implement the stories in the order of business value.

  • N：面议。这是我们不写下所有细节的另一个原因。我们希望这些细节可以在开发人员和企业之间协商。

  • N: Negotiable. This is another reason why we don’t write down all the details. We want those details to be negotiable between the developers and the business.

例如，企业可能要求为某些功能提供一个奇特的拖放界面。开发人员可以通过说开发成本低得多来推荐更简单的复选框样式。像这样的谈判很重要，因为它是企业深入了解管理软件开发成本的方式的少数几种方式之一。

For example, the business might ask for a fancy drag-and-drop interface to some feature. The developers could recommend a simpler checkbox style by saying that it would be much less expensive to develop. Negotiations like that are important because it is one of the few ways that the business gains insight into ways of managing the cost of developing software.

  • 五：有价值。故事必须对业务具有清晰且可量化的价值。

  • V: Valuable. The story must have clear and quantifiable value to the business.

重构从来都不是故事。建筑从来都不是故事。代码清理从来都不是故事。故事始终是企业重视的东西。别担心，我们会处理重构、架构和清理——但不会处理故事。

Refactoring is never a story. Architecture is never a story. Code cleanup is never a story. A story is always something that the business values. Don’t worry, we will deal with refactoring, architecture, and cleanup—but not with stories.

这通常意味着故事将贯穿系统的所有层。它可能涉及一些 GUI、一些中间件、一些数据库工作等。将故事想象成穿过系统水平层的薄薄的垂直切片。

This usually means that a story will cut through all the layers of a system. It may involve a little GUI, a little middleware, some database work, etc. Think of a story as a thin vertical slice through the horizontal layers of the system.

量化商业价值可以是非正式的。一些团队可能简单地使用高/中/低作为他们的业务价值尺度；其他人可能会尝试使用十分制。只要您可以区分价值显着不同的故事，使用什么规模并不重要。

Quantifying the business value can be informal. Some teams might simply use high/medium/low as their business value scale; others might try to use a ten-point scale. It doesn’t matter what scale you use as long as you can differentiate between stories that differ significantly in value.

  • E：估计。用户故事必须足够具体，以便开发人员能够对其进行估算。

  • E: Estimable. A user story must be concrete enough to allow the developers to estimate it.

像系统必须快这样的故事是不可估量的，因为它没有关闭；这是所有故事都必须实现的背景要求。

A story such as The System Must Be Fast is not estimable because it is not closed; it’s a background requirement that all stories must implement.

  • 问：小。用户故事不应超过一两个开发人员在单次迭代中可以实施的内容。

  • S: Small. A user story should not be larger than one or two developers can implement in a single iteration.

我们不希望一个故事在整个迭代中支配整个团队。一个迭代应该包含与团队中的开发人员数量大致相同的故事。如果团队有 8 个开发人员，那么每个迭代应该包含大约 6 到 12 个故事。但是，您不想太在意这一点；它更像是一个指南而不是规则。

We don’t want a single story to dominate the whole team for an entire iteration. An iteration should contain about the same number of stories as there are developers on the team. If the team has 8 developers, then each iteration should contain about 6 to 12 stories. You don’t want to get too hung up on this point, however; it’s more a guideline than a rule.

  • T：可测试。企业应该能够清楚地表达将证明故事已经完成的测试。

  • T: Testable. The business should be able to articulate tests that will prove that the story has been completed.

通常，这些测试将由 QA 编写，将自动执行，并将用于确定故事是否完整。稍后我们将对此进行更多讨论。现在，请记住，故事必须足够具体才能通过测试进行说明。

Typically, those tests will be written by QA, will be automated, and will be used to determine whether a story is complete. We’ll have much more to say about this later. For now, just remember that a story has to be concrete enough to specify with tests.

这似乎与上面的N矛盾。它不会，因为我们在编写故事时不必知道测试。我们只需要知道可以在适当的时候编写测试即可。因此，例如，即使我不知道登录故事的所有细节，我也知道它是可测试的，因为登录是一个具体的操作。另一方面，像Usable这样的故事是不可测试的。也是不可估量的。事实上，E和T非常接近。

This may seem to contradict N above. It doesn’t, because we don’t have to know the test at the time we write the story. All we need to know is that a test can be written at the appropriate time. So for example, even though I don’t know all the details of the Login story, I know that it is testable because Login is a concrete operation. On the other hand, a story like Usable is not testable. It’s also not estimable. Indeed, the E and T go together pretty closely.

故事估计

Story Estimation

有许多估算故事的方案。其中大部分是旧的 Wideband Delphi 5方法的变体。

There are a number of schemes for estimating stories. Most of them are variations on the old Wideband Delphi5 approach.

5 . https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wideband_delphi

5. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wideband_delphi

最简单的一种称为Flying Fingers。开发人员围坐在一张桌子旁，阅读一个故事，并在必要时与利益相关者进行讨论。然后开发人员将一只手放在背后，远离视线，并举起与他们认为故事应得的分数相对应的手指数量。然后有人数一……二……三……然后所有的手指立刻飞了出去。

One of the simplest is called Flying Fingers. Developers sit around a table, read a story, and discuss it with stakeholders if necessary. Then the developers put one hand behind their back, out of sight, and hold up the number of fingers that corresponds to the number of points they think the story deserves. Then someone counts one…two…three… and then all the fingers come flying out at once.

如果每个人都握着相同数量的手指，或者如果偏差很小并且有明显的均值，那么这个数字就会写在故事卡上，然后团队继续下一个故事。但是，如果手指之间存在重大分歧，则开发人员讨论原因，然后重复该过程，直到达成一致。

If everyone is holding the same number of fingers, or if the deviation is small and has an obvious mean, then that number is written on the story card, and the team moves on to the next story. If, however, there is substantial disagreement between the fingers, then the developers discuss the reasons why, and then repeat the process until agreement is reached.

故事的合理范围是衬衫尺码：小号、中号和大号。如果您想使用所有五个手指，请继续。另一方面，不止几个排名几乎肯定是荒谬的。请记住，我们想要准确，但不要比必要的更精确。

A reasonable range for stories is Shirt Sizes: small, medium, and large. If you want to use all five fingers, go ahead. On the other hand, more than a handful of rankings is almost certainly absurd. Remember, we want to be accurate, but no more precise than necessary.

Planning Poker 6是一种类似的技术，但它涉及纸牌。那里有许多流行的 Planning Poker 牌组。大多数使用某种斐波那契数列。一副流行的牌组包含以下牌：?、0、½、1、2、3、5、8、13、20、40、100 和 ∞。如果你使用这样的牌组，我的建议是移除大部分牌。

Planning Poker6 is a similar technique, but it involves cards. There are many popular Planning Poker card decks out there. Most use some kind of Fibonacci series. One popular deck contains the cards: ?, 0, ½, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, 20, 40, 100, and ∞. If you use such a deck, my advice to you would be to remove most of those cards.

6 . Grenning, JW 2002。规划扑克或如何在发布规划时避免分析瘫痪。访问https://wingman-sw.com/articles/planning-poker。

6. Grenning, J. W. 2002. Planning Poker or how to avoid analysis paralysis while release planning. Accessed at https://wingman-sw.com/articles/planning-poker.

斐波那契数列的一个好处是它允许团队估计更大的故事。例如，您可以选择 1、2、3、5 和 8，这将为您提供 8X 的大小范围。

A benefit of the Fibonacci series is that it allows the team to estimate larger stories. For example, you could choose 1, 2, 3, 5, and 8, which gives you an 8X range in size.

您可能还希望包括 0、∞ 和 ?。在Flying Fingers 中，您可以使用拇指向下、拇指向上和张开的手来表示这些符号。零意味着“太微不足道了，无法估计”。小心那些！您可能希望将其中一些合并成一个更大的故事。无穷大（∞）代表太大而无法估计，因此故事应该被拆分。而 (?) 意味着您根本不知道，这意味着您需要一个spike。

You may also wish to include 0, ∞, and ?. In Flying Fingers, you can use thumbs down, thumbs up, and an open hand for these symbols. Zero means, “Too trivial to estimate.” Be careful with those! You may wish to merge a few of them into a bigger story. Infinity (∞) represents too big to estimate, and therefore the story should be split. And (?) means you simply don’t know, meaning that you’ll need a spike.

拆分、合并和尖峰

合并故事很简单。您可以将卡片夹在一起并将合并的故事视为一个故事。把所有的点加起来就可以了。如果有零分，请使用您的最佳判断来总结它们。毕竟，五个零加起来可能不为零。

Merging stories is simple. You can clip the cards together and treat the merged stories as one. Just add up all the points. If any have zero points, use your best judgment in summing them. After all, fives zeros probably does not add up to zero.

拆分故事会更有趣一些，因为您需要保持 INVEST。作为拆分故事的一个简单示例，请考虑登录。如果我们想将它分成更小的故事，我们可以创建无密码登录、单次密码尝试登录、允许多次密码尝试和忘记密码。

Splitting stories is a bit more interesting because you need to maintain INVEST. As a simple example of splitting a story, consider Login. If we wanted to split it into smaller stories, we could create Login with No Password, Login with Single Password Attempt, Allow Multiple Password Attempts, and Forgot Password.

很难找到一个不能分割的故事。对于那些大到需要分裂的人来说尤其如此。请记住，将故事一直分解成单独的代码行是程序员的工作。所以分裂几乎总是可能的。挑战在于保持投资。

It is rare to find a story that cannot be split. This is especially true of those that are big enough to need splitting. Remember, it is the job of a programmer to split stories all the way down into individual lines of code. So splitting is almost always possible. The challenge is maintaining INVEST.

尖峰是一个元故事，或者更确切地说，是一个用于估计故事的故事。之所以称为尖峰，是因为它通常需要我们在系统的所有层中开发一个长而非常薄的切片。

A spike is a meta-story, or rather, a story for estimating a story. It is called a spike because it often requires us to develop a long but very thin slice through all the layers of the system.

假设有一个你无法估计的故事。我们称它为Print PDF。你怎么不知道怎么估价？因为您以前从未使用过 PDF 库，并且不确定它是如何工作的。因此，您编写了一个名为Estimate Print PDF 的新故事。现在你估计那个故事，这更容易估计。

Let’s say there’s a story that you cannot estimate. Let’s call it Print PDF. Why don’t you know how to estimate it? Because you’ve never used the PDF library before and you aren’t sure how it works. So you write a new story called Estimate Print PDF. Now you estimate that story, which is easier to estimate.

毕竟，您知道必须做什么才能了解​​ PDF 库的工作原理。这两个故事都在甲板上。

After all, you know what you’ll have to do to figure out how the PDF library works. Both stories go in the deck.

在未来的 IPM 中，利益相关者可能会决定打打印 PDF卡片，但由于尖峰，他们不能。相反，他们必须打秒牌。这将允许开发人员做必要的工作来估计原始故事，这可以在未来的迭代中实现。

In a future IPM, the stakeholders may decide to play the Print PDF card, but they can’t because of the spike. They have to play the spike card instead. That will allow the developers to do the work necessary to estimate the original story, which can be implemented in a future iteration.

管理迭代

Managing the Iteration

每次迭代的目标都是通过完成故事来产生数据。团队应该关注故事而不是故事中的任务。完成 80% 的故事远比完成每个故事 80% 要好得多。专注于推动故事完成。

The goal of each iteration is to produce data by getting stories done. The team should focus on stories rather than tasks within stories. It is far better to get 80% of the stories done than it is to get each story 80% done. Focus on driving the stories to completion.

计划会议一结束，程序员就应该选择他们各自负责的故事。一些团队选择第一个故事，然后将其余的故事堆成一堆，等故事完成后再选择。无论哪种方式，故事都是由个体程序员选择的，并且属于个体程序员。

As soon as the planning meeting ends, the programmers should choose the stories for which they will each individually be responsible. Some teams choose the first stories and leave the rest in a pile to be chosen later as stories are completed. Either way, stories are chosen by, and belong to, individual programmers.

经理和领导会忍不住将故事分配给程序员。应该避免这种情况。让程序员自己协商要好得多。

Managers and leads will be tempted to assign stories to programmers. This should be avoided. It is far better to let the programmers negotiate amongst themselves.

例如：

For example:

Jerry（熟练工）：如果没人介意的话，我会选择登录和注销。将它们一起做是有意义的。

Jerry (Journeyman): If nobody minds, I’ll take Login and Logout. It makes sense to do them together.

Jasmine（熟练工）：我对此没有意见，但你为什么不在数据库部分与 Alphonse 配对。他一直在询问我们的事件溯源风格，登录将是一个温和的介绍。阿尔方斯？

Jasmine (Journeyman): I don’t have a problem with that, but why don’t you pair with Alphonse on the database part. He’s been asking about our event-sourcing style, and Login would be a gentle introduction. Alphonse?

Alphonse（学徒）：这对我来说听起来很棒。一旦我看到我应该能够在Withdraw 上工作。

Alphonse (Apprentice): That sounds great to me. Once I’ve seen that I should be able to work on Withdraw.

Alexis（首席程序员）： Alphonse ，我为什么不选择Withdraw你也可以和我配对。然后你可以采取转移。

Alexis (Lead programmer): Why don’t I take Withdraw, Alphonse. You can pair with me on that, too. Then you can take Transfer.

阿尔方斯：噢，好的。这可能更有意义。小步骤，对吧？

Alphonse: Aw, OK. That probably makes more sense. Small steps, right?

茉莉花：对，艾尔。这就剩下存款了。我会拿那个。亚历克西斯，你和我应该在用户界面上齐心协力，因为它们可能很相似。我们也许可以共享一些代码。

Jasmine: Right, Al. And that leaves Deposit. I’ll take that one. Alexis, you and I should put our heads together on the UIs because they’re likely similar. We might be able to share some code.

在此示例中，您可以看到首席程序员如何引导雄心勃勃的新学徒避免贪多嚼不烂，以及团队通常如何协作选择故事。

In this example, you can see how the lead programmer guides the new, ambitious apprentice away from biting off more than he can chew, and how the team generally collaborates on choosing the stories.

质量保证和验收测试

如果 QA 还没有开始编写自动验收测试，他们应该在 IPM 结束后立即开始。计划提前完成的故事的测试应该尽早完成。我们不希望完成的故事等待编写验收测试。

If QA has not already begun to write the automated acceptance tests, they should start as soon as the IPM ends. The tests for stories that are scheduled for early completion should be done early. We don’t want completed stories waiting for acceptance tests to be written.

验收测试写作应该很快。我们希望它们都在迭代的中点之前编写。如果到中点还没有准备好所有的验收测试，那么一些开发人员应该停止编写故事并开始进行验收测试。

Acceptance test writing should go quickly. We expect them to all be written before the midpoint of the iteration. If not all the acceptance tests are ready by the midpoint, then some of the developers should stop working on stories and start working on acceptance tests.

这可能意味着并非所有故事都将在此迭代中完成，但无论如何，如果没有验收测试，故事就无法完成。只需确保编写故事的程序员不会同时为该故事编写验收测试。如果 QA 继续错过中点截止日期，一个又一个迭代，那么 QA 工程师与开发人员的比例可能是错误的。

This will likely mean that not all the stories will be completed in this iteration, but a story cannot be completed without the acceptance tests anyway. Just be sure that the programmers working on a story are not also writing the acceptance tests for that story. If QA continues to miss the midpoint deadline, one iteration after another, then the ratio of QA engineers to developers is likely wrong.

在中点之后，如果所有验收测试都已完成，QA 应该为下一次迭代进行测试。这有点推测，因为 IPM 尚未发生，但利益相关者可以提供有关最有可能选择的故事的指导。

After the midpoint, if all the acceptance tests are done, QA should be working on the tests for the next iteration. This is a bit speculative since the IPM hasn’t happened yet, but the stakeholders can offer guidance about the stories most likely to be chosen.

开发人员和 QA 应该就这些测试进行密切沟通。我们不希望 QA 简单地将测试“扔过墙”给开发人员。相反，他们应该协商测试的结构并合作编写测试，甚至在编写测试时结对。

Developers and QA should be communicating intensely about these tests. We don’t want QA to simply “throw the tests over the wall” to the developers. Rather, they should be negotiating how the tests are structured and collaborating on writing them, even to the point of pairing together on the writing of them.

随着迭代的中点临近，团队应该尝试为中点审查完成故事。随着迭代接近尾声，开发人员应该尝试让剩余的故事通过各自的验收测试。

As the midpoint of the iteration approaches, the team should be trying to get stories done for the midpoint review. As the end of the iteration approaches, developers should be trying to get the remaining stories to pass their respective acceptance tests.

“完成”的定义是：验收测试通过。

The definition of “done” is this: acceptance tests pass.

在迭代的最后一天，可能需要做出艰难的选择，决定哪些故事要完成，哪些故事必须放弃。我们这样做是为了重新分配精力以完成尽可能多的故事。同样，我们不想以两个半完成的故事结束迭代，因为我们本可以牺牲一个故事来完成另一个故事。

On the last day of the iteration, tough choices may be required regarding which stories will be completed and which will have to be abandoned. We do this so that we can reallocate effort to get as many stories done as possible. Again, we don’t want to end the iteration with two half-done stories when we could have sacrificed one story in order to get the other one done.

这不是要快。这是关于取得具体的、可衡量的进展。这是关于可靠的数据。当一个故事的验收测试通过时，那个故事就完成了。然而，当一个程序员说一个故事已经完成了 90% 时，我们真的不知道它离完成有多近。因此，我们唯一想在速度图表上报告的是已经通过验收测试的故事。

This is not about going fast. This is about making concrete, measurable progress. This is about reliable data. When the acceptance tests for a story pass, that story is done. However, when a programmer says that a story is 90% done, we really don’t know how close to done it is. So, the only thing we ever want to report on our velocity chart is stories that have passed their acceptance tests.

演示

The Demo

迭代以向利益相关者简要演示新故事结束。这次会议不超过一两个小时，取决于迭代大小。演示应该包括显示所有验收测试运行——包括所有以前的验收测试——和所有单元测试。它还应该展示新添加的功能。最好是利益相关者自己操作系统，这样开发人员就不会试图隐藏不起作用的东西。

The iteration ends with a brief demonstration of the new stories to the stakeholders. This meeting need be no more than an hour or two long, depending on the iteration size. The demo should include showing that all the acceptance tests run—including all previous acceptance tests—and all unit tests. It should also show off the newly added features. It is best if the stakeholders themselves operate the system so that the developers aren’t tempted to hide things that don’t work.

速度

Velocity

迭代的最后一步是更新速度图和燃尽图。只有通过验收测试的故事的分数才会记录在这些图表上。多次迭代后，这两个图表将开始显示斜率。燃尽斜率预测下一个重要里程碑的日期。速度斜率告诉我们团队的管理情况。

The last act of the iteration is to update the velocity and burn-down charts. Only the points for stories that have passed their acceptance tests are recorded on these charts. After several iterations, both of these charts will begin to show a slope. The burn-down slope predicts the date for the next major milestone. The velocity slope tells us how well the team is being managed.

速度斜率会非常嘈杂，尤其是在早期迭代期间，因为团队仍在弄清楚项目的基础知识。但在最初的几次迭代之后，噪声应该降低到允许平均速度变得明显的水平。

The velocity slope will be pretty noisy, especially during early iterations, as the team is still figuring out the basics of the project. But after the first few iterations, the noise should reduce to a level that allows an average velocity to become apparent.

我们希望在前几次迭代后，斜率将为零——即水平。我们不希望团队在很长一段时间内加速或减速。

We expect that after the first few iterations, the slope will be zero—that is, horizontal. We don’t expect the team to be speeding up or slowing down over long periods.

上升速度

如果我们看到正斜率，这可能并不意味着团队实际上走得更快。相反，这可能意味着项目经理正在向团队施加压力以加快速度。随着压力的增加，团队会不自觉地改变他们的估计值，使他们看起来进展得更快。

If we see a positive slope, it likely does not mean that the team is actually going faster. Rather, it probably means that the project manager is putting pressure on the team to go faster. As that pressure builds, the team will unconsciously shift the value of their estimates to make it appear that they are going faster.

这是简单的通货膨胀。积分是一种货币，球队在外部压力下贬值。明年回到那个团队，他们将在每次迭代中完成数百万点。这里的教训是，速度是一种衡量标准，而不是一个目标。这是控制理论 101：不要对你正在测量的东西施加压力。

This is simple inflation. The points are a currency, and the team is devaluing them under external pressure. Come back to that team next year, and they’ll be getting millions of points done per iteration. The lesson here is that velocity is a measurement not an objective. It’s control theory 101: don’t put pressure on the thing you are measuring.

在 IPM 期间估算迭代的目的很简单，就是让利益相关者知道可以完成多少故事。这有助于利益相关者选择故事并帮助他们进行计划。但这个估计并不是一个承诺，如果实际速度较低，团队就没有失败。

The purpose of estimating the iteration during the IPM is simply so that the stakeholders know how many stories might get done. This helps the stakeholders choose the stories and helps them to plan. But that estimate is not a promise, and the team has not failed if the actual velocity is lower.

请记住，唯一失败的迭代是未能生成数据的迭代。

Remember, the only failing iteration is an iteration that fails to produce data.

下落速度

如果速度图表显示一致的负斜率，则最可能的原因是代码质量。该团队可能没有进行足够的重构，他们可能会允许代码腐烂。团队未能充分重构的原因之一是他们没有编写足够的单元测试，因此他们担心重构会破坏曾经有效的东西。管理这种对变化的恐惧是团队管理的主要目标，而这一切都归结为测试纪律。稍后我们将对此进行更多讨论。

If the velocity chart shows a consistent negative slope, then the most likely cause is the quality of the code. The team is likely not refactoring enough and they are probably allowing the code to rot. One reason that teams fail to refactor enough is that they don’t write enough unit tests, so they fear that refactoring will break something that used to work. Managing this fear of change is a major goal of team management, and it all comes down to the testing discipline. We’ll have much more to say about that later.

随着速度下降，团队压力增加。这会导致点膨胀。通货膨胀可以掩盖下降速度。

As velocity falls, pressure on the team builds. This causes the points to inflate. That inflation can hide the falling velocity.

黄金故事

避免通货膨胀的一种方法是不断将故事估计与原始黄金故事进行比较，这是衡量其他故事的标准。请记住，Login是我们最初的Golden Story，它被估计为 3。如果一个新故事（例如Fix Spelling Error in Menu Item）的估计值为 10，您就知道某种通货膨胀的力量在起作用。

One way to avoid inflation is to constantly compare story estimates back to the original Golden Story, the standard against which other stories will be measured. Remember that Login was our original Golden Story, and it was estimated as 3. If a new story such as Fix Spelling Error in Menu Item has an estimate of 10, you know that some inflationary force is at work.

小版本

Small Releases

Small Releases的实践表明开发团队应该尽可能频繁地发布他们的软件。回到 20 世纪 90 年代后期，在敏捷的早期，我们认为这意味着每“一两个月”发布一次。然而，如今，我们已经将目标定得非常非常短。的确，我们已经让它无限短了。新目标当然是持续交付：在每次更改后将代码发布到生产环境的做法。

The practice of Small Releases suggests that a development team should release their software as often as possible. Back in the late ’90s, in the early days of Agile, we thought that this meant a release every “month or two.” Nowadays, however, we’ve set the goal to be much, much, shorter. Indeed, we’ve made it infinitely shorter. The new goal, of course, is Continuous Delivery: the practice of releasing the code to production after every change.

这种描述可能会产生误导，因为持续交付这个术语让人觉得我们想要缩短的周期似乎只是交付周期。实际上，我们想缩短每个周期。

This description could be misleading because the term Continuous Delivery makes it seem like the cycle that we want to shorten is only the delivery cycle. Actually, we want to shorten every cycle.

不幸的是，缩短周期存在很大的历史惯性。这种惰性与我们过去管理源代码的方式有关。

Unfortunately, there is a significant historical inertia to shortening cycles. That inertia has to do with the way we managed our source code back in the olden days.

源代码控制简史

A Brief History of Source Code Control

源代码控制的故事就是周期及其大小的故事。它始于 1950 年代和 60 年代，当时源代码保存在用纸片打的孔中（图 3.3）。

The story of source code control is the story of cycles and their sizes. It begins in the 1950s and ’60s when source code was kept in the holes punched in bits of paper (Figure 3.3).

那时我们很多人都使用穿孔卡片。一张卡片包含 80 个字符，代表一行程序。程序本身就是一副这样的卡片，通常用橡皮筋绑在一起并保存在一个盒子里

（图 3.4）。

Many of us used punched cards in those days. A card held 80 characters and represented one line of a program. The program itself was a deck of such cards, typically held together with a rubber band and kept in a box

(Figure 3.4).

该程序的所有者将甲板放在抽屉或橱柜中。如果有人想查看源代码，他会在所有者的许可下从抽屉或柜子中直接查看源代码。

The owner of that program kept the deck in a drawer or a cabinet. If someone wanted to check out the source code, he literally checked out the source code from the drawer or cabinet, with the permission of the owner.

如果您检查了源代码，那么您是唯一可以更改该源代码的人，因为您实际拥有它。没有其他人可以触摸它。完成后，您将甲板还给所有者，所有者将其放回抽屉或橱柜中。

If you had the source code checked out, you were the only one who could change that source code because you had physical possession of it. Nobody else could touch it. When you were done, you gave the deck back to the owner, who put it back in the drawer or cabinet.

该程序的周期时间是程序员保留它的时间量。那个时间可能是几天、几周或几个月。

The cycle time for that program was the amount of time that a programmer kept possession of it. That time could be days, weeks, or months.

磁带

Tapes

在 1970 年代，我们逐渐过渡到将我们的源代码保存在存储在磁带上的卡片图像中。磁带可以保存大量的源代码模块，而且很容易复制。编辑模块的过程如下。

In the 1970s, we gradually transitioned to keeping our source code in card images stored on magnetic tape. Magnetic tapes could hold a large number of source code modules, and they were easy to duplicate. The procedure for editing a module was as follows.

  1. 从母带架上获取母带。

  2. Get the master tape from the master rack.

  3. 将要编辑的模块从主磁带复制到工作磁带。

  4. Copy the modules you want to edit from the master tape to a work tape.

  5. 将母带放回去，以便其他人可以访问其他模块。

  6. Put the master tape back so other people could access other modules.

  7. 在您要编辑的模块名称旁边的检查板上放置一个彩色图钉。（我是蓝色的，我的老板是红色的，我团队中的另一个程序员是黄色的。是的，最终我们用完了颜色。）

  8. Put a colored pin in the checkout board next to the name of the modules you want to edit. (I was blue, my boss was red, and the other programmer on my team was yellow. Yes, eventually we ran out of colors.)

  9. 使用工作磁带进行编辑、编译和测试。

  10. Edit, compile, and test using the work tape.

  11. 再次获取母带。

  12. Get the master tape again.

  13. 将更改的模块从工作磁带复制到主磁带的新副本。

  14. Copy the changed modules from the work tape to a new copy of the master tape.

  15. 把新的主人放在机架上。

  16. Put the new master in the rack.

  17. 从板上取下你的别针。

  18. Remove your pin from the board.

再一次，周期时间是你的引脚出现在电路板上的时间。这可能是数小时、数天甚至数周。只要您的图钉在结帐板上，其他人就不应触碰您已固定的模块。

Once again, the cycle time was the time your pin was present on the board. This could be hours, days, or even weeks. So long as your pins were in the checkout board, nobody else was supposed to touch the modules you had pinned.

当然，那些模块仍然在母带上，在紧要关头，其他人可能会违反规则并编辑这些模块。所以别针是一种约定，而不是物理障碍。

Of course, those modules were still on the master tape, and in a pinch, someone else could violate the rules and edit the modules. So the pins were a convention, not a physical barrier.

磁盘和 SCCS

Disks and SCCS

在 80 年代，我们将源代码移至磁盘。起初，我们继续使用结帐板上的图钉；然后，一些真正的源代码控制工具开始出现。我记得的第一个是源代码控制系统 (SCCS)。SCCS 的行为就像收银台一样。你锁定了一个模块磁盘，防止其他人编辑它。这种锁称为悲观锁。同样，循环时间是锁的长度。可能是数小时、数天或数月。

In the ’80s, we moved our source code to disk. At first, we continued to use the pins in the checkout board; then, some real source code control tools started to appear. The first I remember was Source Code Control System (SCCS). SCCS behaved just like the checkout board. You locked a module on disk, preventing anyone else from editing it. This kind of lock is called a pessimistic lock. Again, the cycle time was the length of the lock. It could be hours, days, or months.

SCCS 让位于版本控制系统 (RCS)，后者让位于并发版本系统 (CVS)，所有这些系统都使用一种或另一种形式的悲观锁。因此，周期时间仍然很长。但是，磁盘是一种比磁带方便得多的存储介质。将模块从主磁带复制到工作磁带的过程诱使我们保持这些模块很大。另一方面，磁盘允许我们大幅缩小模块的大小。拥有许多小模块而不是几个大模块根本不会受到惩罚。这有效地缩短了周期时间，因为检查小模块的时间相对较少。

SCCS gave way to Revision Control System (RCS), which gave way to Concurrent Versions System (CVS), all of which used one form or another of pessimistic lock. So the cycle time remained long. However, disks are a much more convenient medium of storage than tapes. The process of copying modules from master to work tapes tempted us to keep those modules large. Disks, on the other hand, allowed us to shrink the size of our modules drastically. There simply was no penalty for having many small modules as opposed to a few large ones. This effectively shortened the cycle time simply because the amount of time you would keep a small module checked out was relatively small.

问题是对系统的更改通常需要更改许多模块。由于系统深度耦合，有效结帐时间仍然很长。我们中的一些人学会了解耦我们的模块以缩短结帐时间。然而，大多数人没有。

The problem was that changes to a system usually required changes to many modules. To the extent that the system was deeply coupled, the effective checkout time was still long. Some of us learned to decouple our modules to shorten that checkout time. Most, however, did not.

颠覆

Subversion

然后是 Subversion（SVN）。这个工具提供乐观锁。乐观锁根本不是真正的锁。一个开发人员可以在另一个开发人员签出模块的同时签出模块。该工具会跟踪这一点并自动将更改合并到模块中。如果该工具检测到冲突（即，两个开发人员更改了相同的代码行），它会强制程序员在允许签入之前解决冲突。

Then came Subversion (SVN). This tool offered optimistic locks. An optimistic lock is not really a lock at all. One developer could check out a module at the same time that another had it checked out. The tool kept track of this and automatically merged changes into the modules. If the tool detected a conflict (i.e., the two developers changed the same lines of code) it forced the programmer to resolve the conflict before allowing the checkin.

这大大缩短了编辑、编译和测试一系列小更改所需的周期时间。耦合仍然是一个问题。紧密耦合的系统保持较长的周期时间，因为许多模块必须一致更改。但是松散耦合的系统可以更快地循环。结帐时间不再是限制因素。

This drastically shortened the cycle time to the time required to edit, compile, and test a series of small changes. Coupling was still an issue. A tightly coupled system maintained long cycle times because many modules had to be changed in unison. But a loosely coupled system could be cycled much more quickly. Checkout time was no longer the limiting factor.

Git 和测试

Git and Tests

现在我们使用 Git。使用 Git 的结帐时间已缩减为零。这个概念不存在。相反，可以随时提交对模块的任何更改。这些提交之间的冲突在程序员需要时得到解决。微小的解耦模块和快速的提交频率导致周期时间可以短至几分钟。加上创建一个全面的、快速运行的测试套件的能力，测试几乎所有的东西，你就具备了持续交付的能力。

Nowadays we use Git. Checkout time using Git has shrunk to zero. The concept doesn’t exist. Rather, any alteration to a module can be committed at any time. Conflicts among these commits are resolved as and when the programmers desire. Tiny decoupled modules and rapid commit frequency result in cycle times that can be as small as minutes. Add to this the ability to create a comprehensive, fast-running test suite that tests almost everything, and you have the makings of Continuous Delivery.

历史惯性

不幸的是，组织很难摆脱过去的行为。几天、几周和几个月的周期时间在许多团队的文化中根深蒂固，并且已经传播到 QA、管理和利益相关者的期望中。从这种文化的角度来看，持续交付的概念似乎很可笑。

Unfortunately, it is difficult for organizations to shake off the behaviors of the past. The cycle time of days, weeks, and months is deeply ingrained in the culture of many teams and has spread to QA, to management, and to the expectations of the stakeholders. From the vantage of such a culture, the notion of Continuous Delivery can seem ludicrous.

小版本

敏捷试图通过推动团队缩短发布周期来打破这种历史惯性。如果您每六个月发布一次，则每三个月尝试一次，然后每月尝试一次，然后每周尝试一次。以渐进接近零的方式不断缩短发布周期。

Agile attempts to break that historical inertia by driving the team to shorter and shorter release cycles. If you are releasing every six months, try every three months, then try every month, then try every week. Keep shortening the release cycle in an asymptotic approach to zero.

为此，组织需要打破发布和部署之间的耦合。术语“发布”表示软件在技术上已准备好部署。部署决定完全是一个业务决策。

To do this, the organization will need to break the coupling between release and deployment. The term “release” means that the software is technically ready to be deployed. The decision to deploy becomes solely a business decision.

您可能已经注意到，这与我们用来描述迭代的语言相同。迭代在技术上是可部署的。如果我们的迭代周期为两周，但我们想要更频繁地发布，那么我们将不得不缩短迭代周期。

You may have noticed that this is the same language we used to describe iterations. Iterations are technically deployable. If our iterations are two weeks long, but we want to release more often than that, we’ll have to shorten our iterations.

迭代可以逐渐缩短为零吗？是的他们可以。但这是另一节的主题。

Can iterations be shortened asymptotically toward zero? Yes, they can. But that’s a topic for another section.

验收测试

Acceptance Tests

验收测试实践是所有敏捷实践中了解最少、使用最少和最混乱的实践之一。这很奇怪，因为基本思想非常简单：需求应该由业务指定。

The practice of Acceptance Tests is one of the least understood, least used, and most confused of all the Agile practices. This is strange because the underlying idea is remarkably simple: Requirements should be specified by the business.

问题当然是这个词的意思：指定。许多企业希望这个词意味着他们可以在空中挥舞双手，并用模糊不清的术语描述所需的行为。他们希望开发人员弄清楚所有的小细节。许多程序员希望企业能够精确定义系统应该做什么，精确到每个像素的坐标和值。

The problem, of course, is the meaning of the word: specify. Many businesses would like that word to mean that they can wave their hands around in the air and describe the desired behavior in vague and fluffy terms. They want the developers to figure out all the little details. Many programmers would like the business to define precisely what the system should do, right down to the coordinates and values of each individual pixel.

介于这两个极端之间的东西是必要的。

Something in the middle of these two extremes is necessary.

那么什么是规范呢？就其本质而言，规范是一种测试。例如：

So what is a specification? A specification is, by its very nature, a test. For example:

当用户输入有效的用户名和密码，然后点击“登录”，系统会出现“欢迎”页面。

When the user enters a valid username and password, and then clicks “login,” the system will present the “Welcome” page.

这显然是一个规范。这显然也是一种考验。

This is obviously a specification. It is also obviously a test.

同样显而易见的是，该测试可以自动化。计算机没有理由无法验证是否满足规范。

It should also be obvious that this test could be automated. There is no reason that a computer could not verify that the specification has been met.

这是验收测试的做法。实践中说，在切实可行的范围内，系统的需求应该写成自动化测试。

This is the practice of Acceptance Tests. The practice says that, to the degree practicable, the requirements of the system should be written as automated tests.

可是等等！谁编写这些自动化测试？本节的第一段回答了这个问题：需求应该由企业指定。所以业务应该编写自动化测试。正确的？

But wait! Who writes these automated tests? The first paragraph in this section answers that question: Requirements should be specified by the business. So the business should write the automated tests. Right?

可是等等！自动化测试必须以某种正式的可执行语言编写。这听起来像是程序员的工作。所以程序员应该编写自动化测试，对吧？

But wait! Automated tests have to be written in some kind of formal executable language. That sounds like a job for programmers. So programmers should write the automated tests, right?

可是等等！如果程序员编写测试，他们将不会从业务的角度来编写。它们将是充满只有程序员才能理解的细节的技术测试。它们不会反映项目的商业价值。所以业务应该编写自动化测试。正确的？

But wait! If programmers write the tests, they won’t be written from the business’ point of view. They’ll be technical tests full of details that only programmers understand. They won’t reflect the item’s business value. So the business should write the automated tests. Right?

可是等等！如果企业编写自动化测试，那么它们的编写方式将与我们正在使用的技术不匹配。程序员只需要重写它们，对吧？

But wait! If the business writes the automated tests then they’ll be written in a way that doesn’t match the technology we’re using. The programmers will just have to rewrite them, right?

您会明白为什么这种做法让这么多人感到困惑。

You can see why this practice has been so confusing for so many people.

工具和方法

Tools and Methodologies

情况比这更糟，因为这种做法已经被工具和方法淹没了。

It’s worse than that because the practice has been inundated with tools and methodologies.

为了让业务人员更容易编写自动化测试，程序员编写了大量工具来“提供帮助”。这些工具包括 FitNesse、JBehave、SpecFlow 和 Cucumber。这些工具中的每一个都创建了一种形式主义，试图将自动化测试的技术和业务方面分开。工作假设是业务可以编写自动化测试的业务方面，而程序员可以编写将这些测试绑定到被测试系统的胶水代码。

In an attempt to make it easier for business people to write automated tests, programmers have written a plethora of tools to “help.” These tools include things like FitNesse, JBehave, SpecFlow, and Cucumber. Each of these tools creates a formalism that attempts to separate the technical and business sides of an automated test. The working hypothesis is that the business can write the business side of the automated tests, and the programmers can write the glue code that binds those tests to the system being tested.

这似乎是个好主意，而且这些工具在这种分离方面做得不错。然而，企业一直不愿参与。负责规范的业务人员对形式语言持谨慎态度。他们通常希望使用人类语言（例如英语）来编写规范。

This seems like a good idea, and the tools do a decent job of this separation. Yet businesses have been reluctant to engage. The businesspeople who are responsible for specification are wary of formal languages. They typically want to use a human language, like English, to write their specifications.

针对这种不情愿，程序员介入，给业务人员写了验收测试，希望业务人员至少看一下正式的文档。但这并没有解决所有问题好吧，因为商人不喜欢正式的语言。他们宁愿看到系统实际工作，或者更好的是，将验证工作委托给 QA。

In response to this reluctance, programmers have stepped in and written the acceptance tests for the businesspeople, in the hopes that the businesspeople will at least read the formal documents. But this hasn’t worked out all that well either, because the businesspeople don’t like the formal languages. They’d rather either see the system actually work, or better yet, delegate the job of verification to QA.

行为驱动的发展

Behavior-Driven Development

千禧年之后，Dan North 开始重新定义 TDD，他称之为行为驱动开发(BDD)。他的目标是从测试中去除技术行话，让测试看起来更像业务人员会喜欢的规范。

After the turn of the millennium, Dan North began working on a redefinition of TDD that he called Behavior-Driven Development (BDD). His goal was to remove the techie jargon from the tests and make the tests appear more like specifications that businesspeople would appreciate.

起初，这只是另一种形式化测试语言的尝试，在这种情况下使用了三个特殊的副词：Given、When和Then。创建或修改了几个工具来支持这种语言。其中包括 JBehave、Cucumber 和 FitNesse。但随着时间的推移，重点从工具和测试转变为需求和规范。

At first, this was just another attempt at formalizing the language of testing, in this case using three special adverbs: Given, When, and Then. Several tools were created or modified to support this language. Among them are JBehave, Cucumber, and FitNesse. But over time, the emphasis changed from tools and tests to requirements and specification.

BDD 的支持者建议，企业可以通过以正式的基于场景的语言（如 Given-When-Then）指定他们的系统来获得巨大的价值，而不管他们是否实际上将这些需求自动化为测试。

The proponents of BDD suggest that businesses can derive great value by specifying their systems in a formal scenario-based language like Given-When-Then, regardless of whether they actually automate those requirements as tests.

这使业务人员不必遵守编写真正可执行测试所涉及的技术要求，同时允许它们正式和精确。

This relieves the businesspeople from conforming to the technical requirements involved with writing truly executable tests, while at the same time allowing them to be formal and precise.

实践

The Practice

尽管存在上述所有争议和困惑，但验收测试的实践实际上非常简单。企业编写描述每个用户故事行为的正式测试，开发人员将这些测试自动化。

Despite all the controversy and confusion described above, the practice of Acceptance Testing is actually quite simple. The business writes formal tests describing the behavior of each user story, and developers automate those tests.

测试由业务分析师和 QA 在开发他们测试的故事的迭代的前半部分之前编写。开发商将这些测试集成到持续构建中。这些测试成为迭代中故事的完成定义。在编写验收测试之前，故事不会被指定。在验收测试通过之前，故事是不完整的。

The tests are written by business analysts and QA before the first half of the iteration in which the stories they test are to be developed. The developers integrate those tests into the continuous build. Those tests become the Definition of Done for the stories in the iteration. A story is not specified until its acceptance test is written. A story is not complete until its acceptance test passes.

业务分析师和 QA

验收测试是业务分析师、QA 和开发人员之间的协作工作。业务分析师指定快乐路径。那是因为他们在程序员和利益相关者之间的沟通角色中有足够的工作要做。

Acceptance tests are a collaborative effort between business analysts, QA, and the developers. Business analysts specify the happy paths. That’s because they have enough to do in their role of communicating between the programmers and the stakeholders.

QA 的作用是编写不愉快的路径。它们的数量比前者多得多。聘请质量检查人员是因为他们有能力弄清楚如何破坏系统。他们是深谙技术的人，可以预见用户将要对系统做的所有稀奇古怪的事情。他们也了解程序员的想法，知道如何探查他们所有的懒惰倾向。

QA’s role is to write the unhappy paths. There are a lot more of them than there are of the former. QA folks are hired for their ability to figure out how to break the system. They are deeply technical people who can foresee all the strange and bizarre things that users are going to do to the system. They also know the minds of programmers and understand how to probe all their lazy streaks.

当然，开发人员与 QA 和业务分析师合作，以确保测试从技术角度来看是有意义的。

And, of course, the developers work with QA and business analysts to ensure that the tests make sense from a technical point of view.

质量保证

当然，这完全改变了 QA 的角色。他们不再充当项目后端的测试人员，而是成为项目前端的指定者。他们没有提供有关错误和遗漏的延迟反馈，而是为开发团队提供早期输入以防止这些错误和遗漏。

This, of course, completely changes the role of QA. Rather than acting as testers on the back end of the project, they become specifiers operating at the front end of the project. Instead of supplying late feedback about errors and omissions, they are providing early input to the development team to prevent those errors and omissions.

这给 QA 带来了更大的负担。QA 现在必须通过将其注入每个迭代的开始来确保质量，而不是在结束时衡量是否缺乏合规性。但是，QA 的责任丝毫没有减少；他们确定系统是否可部署。

This puts a much greater burden upon QA. QA must now ensure quality by injecting it into the start of each iteration, rather than measuring lack of compliance at the end. However, the responsibility of QA is not diminished in any way; they determine whether the system is deployable.

最后失去测试

将 QA 移至开始并自动化测试解决了另一个大问题。当 QA 最后手动操作时，它们就是瓶颈。他们必须先完成工作，然后才能部署系统。不耐烦的经理和利益相关者依靠 QA 来完成，以便可以部署系统。

Moving QA to the beginning and automating the tests solves another huge problem. When QA operates manually at the end, they are the bottleneck. They must finish their work before the system can be deployed. Impatient managers and stakeholders lean on QA to finish up so that the system can be deployed.

当 QA 走到最后时，所有上游延迟都落在 QA 身上。如果开发人员延迟交付给 QA，交付日期是否会改变？交货日期通常是出于非常好的商业原因而选择的，延迟交货日期将代价高昂，甚至是灾难性的。QA 留下来拿着袋子。

When QA comes at the end, all upstream delays fall on QA. If the developers are late delivering to QA, does the delivery date change? Often the delivery date was chosen for very good business reasons, and delaying it would be costly, or even catastrophic. QA is left holding the bag.

当 QA 没有时间测试系统时，他们应该如何测试系统？QA 如何才能更快？这很简单：不要测试所有内容。只需测试发生变化的事情。根据新特性和变化特性做影响分析，只测试受影响的东西。不要浪费时间测试没有改变的东西。

How should QA test the system when they have no time left in the schedule to test it? How can QA go faster? That’s easy: don’t test everything. Just test the things that changed. Do an impact analysis based on new and changed features, and only test the impacted things. Don’t waste time testing things that haven’t changed.

所以你失去了测试。在压力下，QA 会简单地绕过所有回归测试。他们希望下次可以运行它们。通常，“下一次”永远不会到来。

So you lose the tests. Under pressure, QA simply bypasses all the regression tests. They hope that they can run them next time. Often, “next time” never comes.

质检病

然而，这还不是最严重的问题，因为 QA 处于流程的最后阶段。当 QA 结束时，组织如何知道他们的工作做得很好？当然是通过他们的缺陷数。如果 QA 发现了很多缺陷，那么他们显然做得很好。QA 经理可以吹捧发现的缺陷数量，作为他们正在履行职责的明确证据。

However, that’s not the worst problem that happens because QA is at the end of the process. When QA is at the end, how does the organization know they are doing their jobs well? By their defect count, of course. If QA is finding lots of defects, they are clearly doing their job well. QA managers can tout the number of defects found as clear evidence that they are performing their function.

因此，缺陷被认为是一件好事。

Thus, defects are considered a good thing.

还有谁可以从缺陷中获益？年长的程序员之间流传着这样一句话：“我可以在你为我设定的任何截止日期前完成任务，只要软件不必正常运行即可。” 那么还有谁能从缺陷中受益呢？需要在截止日期前完成任务的开发人员。

Who else can benefit from defects? There’s a saying among older programmers: “I can meet any deadline you set for me, as long as the software doesn’t have to work properly.” So who else benefits from defects? Developers who need to meet schedule deadlines.

无需多言。不需要写协议。但双方都明白他们从缺陷中获益。出现了缺陷的黑市经济。这种疾病渗透到许多组织中，如果不是绝症，那肯定会使人衰弱。

No word needs to be spoken. No agreement needs to be written. But both sides understand that they benefit from defects. A black market economy of defects emerges. This disease permeates many organizations, and if it’s not terminal, it’s certainly debilitating.

开发人员是测试人员

这些问题都可以通过验收测试的实践来解决。QA 在迭代中为故事编写验收测试。但 QA 不运行这些测试。验证系统是否通过测试不是 QA 的工作。这是谁的工作？当然是程序员的！

These problems are all cured by the practice of Acceptance Tests. QA writes the acceptance tests for the stories in an iteration. But QA does not run those tests. It’s not QA’s job to verify that the system passes the tests. Whose job is it? The programmers’, of course!

运行测试是程序员的工作。确保他们的代码通过所有测试是程序员的工作。所以当然，程序员必须运行这些测试。运行这些测试是程序员确定他们的故事是否完成的唯一方法。

It is the programmers’ job to run the tests. It is the programmers’ job to make sure that their code passes all the tests. So of course, the programmers must run those tests. Running those tests is the only way for programmers to determine whether their stories are done.

持续构建

实际上，程序员将通过设置持续构建服务器来自动化该过程7 。每当任何程序员签入模块时，该服务器将简单地运行系统中的所有测试，包括所有单元测试和所有验收测试。当我们谈论持续集成时，我们会有更多的话要说。

Indeed, the programmers will automate that process7 by setting up a Continuous Build server. This server will simply run all the tests in the system, including all unit tests and all acceptance tests, every time any programmer checks in a module. We’ll have more to say about that when we talk about Continuous Integration.

7 . 因为自动化是程序员的工作！

7. Because automating things is what programmers do!

整队

Whole Team

Whole Team的做法最初被称为On-Site Customer。这个想法是用户和程序员之间的距离越近，沟通越好，开发越快、越准确。客户是理解用户需求并与开发团队共处一地的某个人或某个群体的隐喻。理想情况下，客户与团队坐在同一个房间。

The practice of Whole Team was initially called On-Site Customer. The idea was that the shorter the distance between the users and the programmers, the better the communication, and the faster and more accurate the development. The customer was a metaphor for someone, or some group, who understood the needs of the users, and who was co-located with the development team. Ideally, the customer sat in the same room with the team.

在 Scrum 中，客户被称为产品负责人。这是选择故事、设置优先级并提供即时反馈的人（或小组）。

In Scrum, the customer is called the Product Owner. This is the person (or group) who chooses stories, sets priorities, and provides immediate feedback.

该实践被重新命名为Whole Team以明确开发团队不仅仅是客户/程序员二人组。相反，一个开发团队由许多角色组成，包括经理、测试人员、技术编写人员等。这种做法的目标是尽量减少这些角色之间的物理距离。理想情况下，团队的所有成员都坐在同一个房间里。

The practice was renamed Whole Team in order to make it clear that a development team was not simply a customer/programmer dyad. Instead, a development team is composed of many roles including managers, testers, technical writers, etc. The goal of the practice is to minimize the physical distance between these roles. Ideally, all members of the team sit together in the same room.

毫无疑问，将整个团队放在一个房间里可以最大限度地提高该团队的效率。个人可以快速沟通，并以最少的形式进行。可以在几秒钟内提出和回答问题。知道答案的专家总是在附近。

There can be little doubt that putting the entire team into a single room maximizes the efficiency of that team. The individuals can communicate rapidly and with a minimum of formality. Questions can be asked and answered within seconds. The experts who know the answers are always near.

此外，还有一个巨大的偶然机会。现场客户可能会查看并在程序员或测试人员的屏幕上看到一些看起来不正确的东西。测试人员可能无意中听到一对编程人员在谈论需求，并意识到他们得出了错误的结论。这种意外的协同作用不应被低估。当整个团队坐在同一个空间时，奇迹就会发生。

Moreover, there is a huge opportunity for serendipity. An on-site customer may look over and see something on a programmer’s or tester’s screen that doesn’t look right. A tester may overhear a programming pair talking about a requirement and realize that they’ve come to the wrong conclusion. This kind of accidental synergy should not be undervalued. When the Whole Team sits together in the same space, magic can happen.

请注意，此实践算作业务实践，而不是团队实践。那是因为整体团队实践的主要优势会累积到业务中。

Notice that this practice is counted as a business practice, and not a team practice. That’s because the primary advantages of the Whole Team practice accrue to the business.

当团队位于同一地点时，业务运行得更加顺畅。

When teams are co-located, the business runs much more smoothly.

同地办公

Co-Location

在 2000 年代初，我帮助了几个组织采用敏捷方法。在我们的初步访问中，在主动指导开始之前，我们要求我们的客户设置团队房间并将团队放在一起。不止一次，客户报告说团队的效率仅仅因为同地办公就大大提高了。

In the early 2000s, I helped several organizations adopt Agile methods. In our preliminary visits, before the active coaching began, we asked our customers to set up team rooms and co-locate the teams. More than once, the customer reported that the efficiency of the teams increased dramatically simply because of the co-location.

主机代管备选方案

在 1990 年代，互联网使得在劳动力成本非常低的国家利用大量编程劳动力成为可能。使用这种劳动力的诱惑是压倒性的。会计师计算了一下，他们的眼睛闪闪发光，因为他们相信自己可以实现节省。

In the 1990s, the internet made it feasible to take advantage of vast pools of programming labor in countries where the cost of that labor was very low. The temptation to use this labor was overwhelming. Accountants did the math, and their eyes sparkled with the savings they believed they could achieve.

这个梦想并没有像大家希望的那样顺利。事实证明，向世界各地发送兆位源代码的能力与拥有一个位于同一地点的客户和程序员团队并不完全相同。英里、时区、语言和文化方面的距离仍然很大。沟通不畅很猖獗。质量受到严重限制。返工飙升。8个

This dream didn’t work out quite as well as everyone hoped. It turns out that the ability to send megabits of source code around the world is not quite the same as having a team of co-located customers and programmers. The distances in terms of miles, time zones, language, and culture were still huge. Miscommunication was rampant. Quality was severely limited. Rework soared.8

8 . 这些是我自己的印象，基于与直接经历过这些问题的人交谈。我没有实际数据可以展示。买者自负。

8. These are my own impressions based upon talking with folks who experienced the issues directly. I have no actual data to present. Caveat emptor.

从那以后的几年里，这项技术有所改进。数据吞吐率现在允许定期视频聊天和屏幕共享会话。位于世界两端的两个开发人员现在可以配对使用相同的代码，就好像他们坐在一起一样——几乎。当然，这些进步并没有解决时区、语言和文化问题；但是面对面的电子编码肯定比来回通过电子邮件发送源代码更可取。

In the years since, the technology has improved somewhat. Data throughput rates now allow regular video chat and screen-sharing sessions. Two developers located on opposite sides of the world can now pair on the same code almost as though they were sitting next to each other—almost. Of course, these advances don’t solve the time-zone, language, and culture issues; but electronic face-to-face coding is certainly preferable to emailing source code back and forth.

敏捷团队可以这样工作吗？我听说这是可能的。我从未见过它成功完成。也许你有。

Can an Agile team work this way? I’ve heard that it is possible. I’ve never seen it done successfully. Perhaps you have.

在家远程工作

互联网带宽的改善也让人们更容易在家工作。在这种情况下，语言、时区和文化都不是重要问题。更重要的是，没有跨洋通信滞后。团队会议几乎可以在同一地点举行，并且与每个人的昼夜节律同步。

The improvement in internet bandwidth has also made it much easier for people to work from home. In this case, the language, time zone, and culture aren’t significant issues. What’s more, there is no trans-ocean communications lag. Team meetings can occur almost as if co-located and in sync with everyone’s circadian rhythms.

不要误会我的意思。当团队成员在家工作时，非语言交流仍然存在很大损失。偶然的谈话要少得多。无论团队之间的电子连接多么紧密，他们仍然不在同一个空间中。这使在家工作的人处于明显的劣势。他们总是错过对话和临时会议。尽管他们可能享有巨大的数据带宽，但与同处一地的人相比，他们仍然通过窥视孔进行通信。

Don’t get me wrong. When team members work from home, there is still a significant loss of nonverbal communication. Serendipitous conversations are much rarer. No matter how electronically connected the team is, they are still not together in the same space. This puts the people working from home at a distinct disadvantage. There are always conversations and impromptu meetings that they miss. Despite the vast data bandwidth they may enjoy, they are still communicating through a peephole compared to those who are co-located.

一个大部分时间都在同一地点但有一两个成员每周在家工作一两天的团队可能不会注意到任何重大障碍，特别是如果他们已经投资了一些好的、高带宽的远程通信工具。

A team that is mostly co-located but has a member or two who work from home one or two days per week will likely not notice any significant impediment, especially if they have invested in some good, high-bandwidth remote-communication tools.

另一方面，一个由几乎完全在家工作的人组成的团队永远不会像在同一地点工作的团队那样工作。

On the other hand, a team composed of people who work almost entirely from home will never work as well as a team that is co-located.

不要误会我的意思。在 20 世纪 90 年代初期，我和我的搭档 Jim Newkirk 成功地管理了一个完全没有同地办公的团队。每个人都完全在家工作。我们每年最多见两次面，我们中的一些人生活在不同的时区。另一方面，我们都说同一种语言，共享同一种文化，而且我们的时区相隔从不超过两个小时。我们成功了。我们让它工作得很好。但如果我们在同一个房间里，效果会更好。

Don’t get me wrong. In the early ’90s, my partner Jim Newkirk and I successfully managed a team that had no co-location at all. Everyone worked entirely from home. We met in person twice per year at most, and some of us lived in different time zones. On the other hand, we all spoke the same language, shared the same culture, and our time zones were never more than two hours apart. We made it work. We made it work very well. But it would have worked even better if we’d been together in the same room.

结论

Conclusion

在 2000 年的 Snowbird 会议上，Kent Beck 说我们的目标之一是弥合业务与开发之间的鸿沟。面向业务的实践在实现该目标方面发挥着重要作用。通过遵循这些实践，业务和开发人员可以通过一种简单而明确的方式进行沟通。这种交流滋生了信任。

At the Snowbird meeting in 2000, Kent Beck said that one of our goals was to heal the divide between business and development. The business-facing practices play a big role in satisfying that goal. By following these practices, business and development have a simple and unambiguous way to communicate. That communication breeds trust.

4.团队实践

4. Team Practices

Ron Jeffries 的生命圈中的中间带由敏捷的团队实践组成。这些实践管理团队成员之间的关系以及他们与他们正在创建的产品之间的关系。我们将讨论的实践是隐喻、可持续步伐、集体所有权和持续集成。

The middle band within Ron Jeffries’ Circle of Life consists of the Team Practices of Agile. These practices govern the relationship of the team members with one another and with the product they are creating. The practices we will discuss are Metaphor, Sustainable Pace, Collective Ownership, and Continuous Integration.

然后我们将简要讨论所谓的站立会议。

Then we’ll talk briefly about so-called Standup Meetings.

隐喻

Metaphor

在敏捷宣言签署前后的几年里，隐喻实践对我们来说是一种尴尬，因为我们无法描述它。我们知道这很重要，我们可以举出一些成功的例子。但是我们无法有效地表达我们的意思。在我们的几次谈话、讲座或课程中，我们只是逃避并说“当你看到它时你就会知道”之类的话。

In the years just before and after the signing of the Agile Manifesto, the Metaphor practice was something of an embarrassment for us because we couldn’t describe it. We knew it was important, and we could point to some successful examples. But we were unable to effectively articulate what we meant. In several of our talks, lectures, or classes, we simply bailed out and said things like, “You’ll know it when you see it.”

这个想法是为了让团队有效地沟通，他们需要一个受约束和有纪律的术语和概念词汇表。Kent Beck 将此称为隐喻，因为它将他的项目与团队拥有共同知识的其他事物相关联。

The idea is that in order for the team to communicate effectively, they require a constrained and disciplined vocabulary of terms and concepts. Kent Beck called this a Metaphor because it related his projects to something else about which the teams had common knowledge.

Beck 的主要示例是克莱斯勒薪资项目使用的 Metaphor。1他将薪水的生产与流水线联系起来。薪水会从一个站点转移到另一个站点，并添加“零件”。空白支票可能会移至 ID 站以添加员工的身份证明。然后它可能会移动到支付站以获得添加的总工资。接下来它可能会转移到联邦税务站，然后是 FICA 站，然后是 Medicare 站……你明白了。

Beck’s primary example was the Metaphor used by the Chrysler payroll project.1 He related the production of a paycheck to an assembly line. The paychecks would move from station to station getting “parts” added to them. A blank check might move to the ID station to get the employee’s identification added. Then it might move to the pay station to get the gross pay added. Next it might move to the federal tax station, and then the FICA station, and then the Medicare station… You get the idea.

1 . https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chrysler_Comprehensive_Compensation_System

1. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chrysler_Comprehensive_Compensation_System

程序员和客户可以很容易地将这个比喻应用到建立薪水支票的过程中。它为他们提供了谈论系统时使用的词汇。

The programmers and customers could pretty easily apply this metaphor to the process of building a paycheck. It gave them a vocabulary to use when talking about the system.

但是隐喻经常出错。

But metaphors often go wrong.

例如，在 80 年代后期，我参与了一个测量 T1 通信网络质量的项目。我们从每条 T1 线路的端点下载错误计数。这些错误计数被收集到 30 分钟的时间片中。我们认为这些切片是需要处理的原始数据。什么煮切片？烤面包机。面包的隐喻由此开始。我们有切片、面包、面包屑等。

For example, in the late ’80s, I worked on a project that measured the quality of T1 communication networks. We downloaded error counts from the endpoints of each T1 line. Those error counts were collected into 30-minute time slices. We considered those slices to be raw data that needed to be cooked. What cooks slices? A toaster. And thus began the bread metaphor. We had slices, loaves, crumbs, etc.

这个词汇表对程序员很有效。我们可以互相谈论生的和烤的切片、面包等。另一方面，无意中听到我们的经理和顾客会摇着头走出房间。在他们看来，我们似乎在胡说八道。

This vocabulary worked well for the programmers. We were able to talk with each other about raw and toasted slices, loaves, etc. On the other hand, the managers and customers who overheard us would walk out of the room shaking their heads. To them we appeared to be talking nonsense.

举一个更糟糕的例子，在 70 年代初期，我从事一个分时系统的工作，该系统在有限的内存空间中交换应用程序。在应用程序占用内存期间，它会加载要发送到慢速电传打字机的文本缓冲区。当该缓冲区已满时，应用程序将进入休眠状态并换出到磁盘，同时缓冲区会慢慢清空。我们称这些缓冲区为垃圾车，在垃圾生产者和垃圾场之间来回奔跑。

As a much worse example, in the early ’70s I worked on a time-sharing system that swapped applications in and out of limited memory space. During the time that an application occupied memory, it would load up a buffer of text to be sent out to a slow teletype. When that buffer was full, the application would be put to sleep and swapped out to disk while the buffers slowly emptied. We called those buffers garbage trucks, running back and forth between the producer of the garbage and the dump.

我们认为这很聪明。我们使用垃圾作为比喻，让我们咯咯地笑。实际上，我们是在说我们的客户是垃圾商。尽管这个比喻对我们的交流很有效，但它对那些付钱给我们的人是不尊重的。我们从未与他们分享过。

We thought this was clever. Our use of garbage, as a metaphor, made us giggle. In effect, we were saying that our customers were garbage merchants. As effective as the metaphor was for our communication, it was disrespectful to those who were paying us. We never shared it with them.

这些例子显示了隐喻思想的优点和缺点。隐喻可以提供让团队有效沟通的词汇。另一方面，一些隐喻愚蠢到冒犯客户的地步。

These examples show both the advantages and disadvantages of the Metaphor idea. A metaphor can provide a vocabulary that allows the team to communicate efficiently. On the other hand, some metaphors are silly to the point of being offensive to the customer.

领域驱动设计

Domain-Driven Design

2 Eric Evans在他开创性的著作《领域驱动设计》中解决了隐喻问题，并最终消除了我们的尴尬。在那本书中，他创造了Ubiquitous Language 这个词，这个名字应该有被赋予隐喻实践。团队需要的是问题领域的模型，它由每个人都同意的词汇表描述。我的意思是每个人——程序员、QA、经理、客户、用户……每个人。

In his groundbreaking book Domain-Driven Design,2 Eric Evans solved the metaphor problem and finally erased our embarrassment. In that book, he coined the term Ubiquitous Language, which is the name that should have been given to the Metaphor practice. What the team needs is a model of the problem domain, which is described by a vocabulary that everyone agrees on. And I mean everyone—the programmers, QA, managers, customers, users…everyone.

2 . Evans, E. 2003。领域驱动设计：应对软件核心的复杂性。马萨诸塞州波士顿：Addison-Wesley。

2. Evans, E. 2003. Domain-Driven Design: Tackling Complexity in the Heart of Software. Boston, MA: Addison-Wesley.

在 1970 年代，Tom DeMarco 将此类模型称为数据字典。3它们是应用程序操作的数据以及操作该数据的进程的简单表示。Evans 将这个简单的想法极大地扩展为领域建模的学科。DeMarco 和 Evans 都使用这些模型作为与所有利益相关者沟通的工具。

In the 1970s, Tom DeMarco called such models Data Dictionaries.3 They were simple representations of the data manipulated by the application and the processes that manipulated that data. Evans greatly amplified that simple idea into a discipline of modeling the domain. Both DeMarco and Evans use those models as vehicles to communicate with all of the stakeholders.

3 . DeMarco, T. 1979。结构化分析和系统规范。新泽西州上马鞍河：尤登出版社。

3. DeMarco, T. 1979. Structured Analysis and System Specification. Upper Saddle River, NJ: Yourdon Press.

举个简单的例子，我最近写了一个名为 SpaceWar 的视频游戏。数据元素是 Ship、Klingon、Romulan、Shot、Hit、Explosion、Base、Transport 等。我小心翼翼地将这些概念中的每一个隔离到它们自己的模块中，并在整个应用程序中专门使用这些名称。这些名字是我的通用语言。

As a simple example, I recently wrote a video game called SpaceWar. The data elements were things like Ship, Klingon, Romulan, Shot, Hit, Explosion, Base, Transport, etc. I was careful to isolate each of these concepts into their own modules and to use those names exclusively throughout the application. Those names were my Ubiquitous Language.

项目的所有部分都使用无处不在的语言。企业使用它。开发人员使用它。质量检查使用它。Ops/Devops 使用它。甚至客户也使用它的那些合适的部分。它支持业务案例、需求、设计、架构和验收测试。它是一个一致性线程，在其生命周期的每个阶段将整个项目互连起来。4个

The Ubiquitous Language is used in all parts of the project. The business uses it. The developers use it. QA uses it. Ops/Devops use it. Even the customers use those parts of it that are appropriate. It supports the business case, the requirements, the design, the architecture, and the acceptance tests. It is a thread of consistency that interconnects the entire project during every phase of its lifecycle.4

4 . “这是一个由所有生物创造的能量场。它围绕着我们，渗透着我们。它把银河连在一起。” Lucas, G. 1979。星球大战：第四集——新希望。卢卡斯影业。

4. “It’s an energy field created by all living things. It surrounds us and penetrates us. It binds the galaxy together.” Lucas, G. 1979. Star Wars: Episode IV—A New Hope. Lucasfilm.

可持续步伐

Sustainable Pace

“比赛不是为了快……”

“The race is not to the swift…”

— 传道书 9:11

— Ecclesiastes 9:11

“……但忍耐到底的，必然得救。”

“…But he who endures to the end will be saved.”

- 马太福音 24:13

— Matthew 24:13

第七天，上帝安息了。上帝后来将第七日安息定为诫命。显然，即使是上帝也需要以可持续的步伐奔跑。

On the seventh day, God rested. God later made it a commandment to rest on the seventh day. Apparently even God needs to run at a Sustainable Pace.

70 年代初，在我 18 岁那年，我和我的高中伙伴被聘为新程序员，从事一个至关重要的项目。我们的经理设定了最后期限。那些最后期限是绝对的。我们的努力很重要！我们是组织机构中的关键齿轮。我们很重要！

In the early ’70s, at the tender age of 18, my high school buddies and I were hired as new programmers working on a critically important project. Our managers had set deadlines. Those deadlines were absolute. Our efforts were important! We were critical cogs in the machinery of the organization. We were important!

18岁很好，不是吗？

It’s good to be 18, isn’t it?

我们这些刚从高中毕业的年轻人使出浑身解数。我们工作了好几个小时，几个月又几个月。我们每周的平均工作时间超过 60 小时。有几周达到 80 小时以上的峰值。我们拉了几十个通宵达旦的人！

We, young men right out of high school, pulled out all the stops. We worked hours and hours and hours, for months and months and months. Our weekly average was over 60 hours. There were weeks that peaked above 80 hours. We pulled dozens of all-nighters!

我们为所有的加班感到自豪。我们是真正的程序员。我们很敬业。我们很有价值。因为我们单枪匹马地挽救了一个重要的项目。我们。是。程序员。

And we prided ourselves on all that overtime. We were real programmers. We were dedicated. We were valuable. Because we were single-handedly saving a project that was important. We. Were. Programmers.

然后我们筋疲力尽——非常严重。如此努力以至于我们集体退出。我们冲出了那里，留下公司拥有一个几乎无法运行的分时系统，没有任何称职的程序员来支持它。那会给他们看的！

And then we burned out—hard. So hard that we quit en masse. We stormed out of there, leaving the company holding a barely functioning time-share system without any competent programmers to support it. That’ll show ’em!

18 岁生气就好，不是吗？

It’s good to be 18 and angry, isn’t it?

别着急，公司蒙混过关。事实证明，我们并不是那里唯一有能力的程序员。那里有人每周认真工作 40 小时。在我们的私人深夜节目狂欢中，我们曾贬低为不敬业和懒惰的人。那些人悄悄地拿起了缰绳，把系统维护得很好。而且，我敢说，他们很高兴摆脱了我们这些生气、吵闹的孩子。

Don’t worry, the company muddled through. It turned out that we were not the only competent programmers there. There were folks there who had carefully worked 40 hours per week. Folks whom we had disparaged as undedicated and lazy in our private late-night programming orgies. Those folks quietly picked up the reins and maintained the system just fine. And, I daresay, they were happy to be rid of us angry, noisy kids.

随着时间的推移

Overtime

你会认为我会从那次经历中吸取教训。但是，当然，我没有。在接下来的 20 年里，我继续为我的雇主长时间工作。我继续爱上重要的项目模因。哦，我没有像 18 岁时那样疯狂工作。我的平均每周工作时间下降到 50 小时左右。通宵工作变得非常罕见——但是，正如我们将要看到的，并非完全没有。

You’d think that I would have learned my lesson from that experience. But, of course, I did not. Over the next 20 years, I continued to work long hours for my employers. I continued to fall for the important project meme. Oh, I didn’t work the crazy hours I worked when I was 18. My average weekly hours dropped to more like 50. All-nighters became pretty rare—but, as we shall see, not entirely absent.

随着我的成熟，我意识到我最严重的技术错误是在那些狂热的深夜能量时期犯下的。我意识到这些错误是我在真正清醒的时候必须不断解决的巨大障碍。

As I matured, I realized that my worst technical mistakes were made during those periods of frenetic late-night energy. I realized that those mistakes were huge impediments that I had to constantly work around during my truly wakeful hours.

然后发生了让我重新考虑我的方式的事件。我未来的商业伙伴吉姆·纽柯克 (Jim Newkirk) 和我通宵达旦。凌晨 2 点左右的某个时候，我们试图弄清楚如何将一段数据从我们系统的低级别部分获取到执行链上更高级别的另一个部分。将此数据返回堆栈不是一种选择。

Then came the event that made me reconsider my ways. My future business partner, Jim Newkirk, and I were pulling an all-nighter. Sometime around 2 a.m., we were trying to figure out how to get a piece of data from a low-level part of our system to another part that was much higher up the execution chain. Returning this data up the stack was not an option.

我们在我们的产品中构建了一个“邮件”传输系统。我们用它来在进程之间发送信息。凌晨 2 点，我们突然意识到，随着咖啡因在我们的血管中咆哮，我们所有的机能都以最高效率运转，我们可以让流程的低级部分将那条数据邮寄给自己，而高级部分可以从中获取数据它。

We had built a “mail” transport system within our product. We used it to send information between processes. We suddenly realized, at 2 a.m., with caffeine roaring through our veins and all our faculties operating at peak efficiency, that we could have the low-level part of the process mail that piece of data to itself where the high-level part could fetch it.

即使在 30 多年后的今天，每当吉姆和我想描述别人的不幸决定时，我们都会说：“呃-哦。他们只是把它邮寄给自己。”

Even today, more than three decades later, whenever Jim and I want to describe someone else’s unfortunate decision, we say: “Uh-oh. They just mailed it to themselves.”

我不会用所有关于为什么这个决定如此糟糕的可怕细节来烦你。可以这么说，它花费了我们许多倍于我们认为可以节省的努力。当然，这个解决方案变得根深蒂固，无法逆转，所以我们只能坚持下去。5个

I won’t bore you with all the horrible, nitty-gritty details about why that decision was so awful. Suffice it to say, it cost us many times the effort that we thought we were saving. And of course, the solution became too entrenched to reverse, so we were stuck with it.5

5 . 这是我了解 TDD 之前的十年。如果 Jim 和我当时一直在实践 TDD，我们本可以轻松地取消该更改。

5. This was a decade before I would learn about TDD. Had Jim and I been practicing TDD back then, we could have easily backed out that change.

马拉松

Marathon

就在那一刻，我了解到软件项目是一场马拉松，而不是冲刺，也不是一系列冲刺。为了获胜，您必须调整自己的节奏。如果你跳出障碍物并全速奔跑，那么在你越过终点线之前你就会耗尽能量。

That was the moment that I learned that a software project is a marathon, not a sprint, nor a sequence of sprints. In order to win, you must pace yourself. If you leap out of the blocks and run at full speed, you’ll run out of energy long before you cross the finish line.

因此，您必须以可以长期维持的配速跑步。您必须以可持续的配速跑步。如果你试图跑得比你能维持的配速快，你将不得不在到达终点线之前放慢速度并休息，你的平均速度将低于可持续配速。快到终点的时候，如果还有点余力，可以冲刺。但是你不能在那之前冲刺。

Thus, you must run at a pace that you can sustain over the long haul. You must run at a Sustainable Pace. If you try to run faster than the pace you can sustain, you will have to slow down and rest before you reach the finish line, and your average speed will be slower than the Sustainable Pace. When you are close to the finish line, if you have a bit of spare energy, you can sprint. But you must not sprint before that.

经理可能会要求你跑得比你应该跑的快。你不能遵守。节约资源以确保坚持到底是你的工作。

Managers may ask you to run faster than you should. You must not comply. It is your job to husband your resources to ensure that you endure to the end.

奉献精神

Dedication

加班并不是向雇主表示奉献的一种方式。它表明你是一个糟糕的计划者，你同意了你不应该同意的最后期限，你做出了你不应该做出的承诺，你是一个可以操纵的劳动者而不是专业人士。

Working overtime is not a way to show your dedication to your employer. What it shows is that you are a bad planner, that you agree to deadlines to which you shouldn’t agree, that you make promises you shouldn’t make, that you are a manipulable laborer and not a professional.

这并不是说所有的加班都是不好的，也不是说你永远不应该加班。在情有可原的情况下，唯一的选择就是加班。但它们应该是极其罕见的。你必须非常清楚，加班的成本可能会比你在日程表上节省的时间还要多。

This is not to say that all overtime is bad, nor that you should never work overtime. There are extenuating circumstances for which the only option is to work overtime. But they should be extremely rare. And you must be very aware that the cost of that overtime will likely be greater than the time you save on the schedule.

几十年前我和吉姆一起熬夜的那次通宵并不是我最后一次熬夜——它是倒数第二个。我拉的最后一个通宵是我无法控制的情有可原的情况之一。

That all-nighter that I pulled with Jim all those decades ago was not the last all-nighter I was to pull—it was the second to last. The last all-nighter I pulled was one of those extenuating circumstances over which I had no control.

那是 1995 年。我的第一本书预定在第二天付印，而我却忙于提供校样。当时是下午 6 点，我让他们都准备好了。我需要做的就是将它们通过 FTP 传送到我的出版商。

The year was 1995. My first book was scheduled to go to press the next day, and I was on the hook to deliver page proofs. It was 6 p.m. and I had them all ready to go. All I needed to do was to FTP them to my publisher.

但后来，纯属偶然，我偶然发现了一种方法，可以将那本书中数百张图表的分辨率提高一倍。Jim 和 Jennifer 正在帮助我准备好页面校样，当我向他们展示改进分辨率的示例时，我们正要执行 FTP。

But then, by sheer accident, I stumbled across a way to double the resolution of the hundreds of diagrams in that book. Jim and Jennifer were helping me get the page proofs ready, and we were just about to execute the FTP when I showed an example of the improved resolution to them.

我们互相看着对方，深深地叹了口气，吉姆说：“我们必须全部重做。” 这不是问题。这是事实陈述。我们三个人互相看了看，看看时钟，又互相看了看，然后我们就开始工作了。

We all looked at each other, heaved a great sigh, and Jim said, “We have to redo them all.” It wasn’t a question. It was a statement of fact. The three of us looked at each other, at the clock, back at each other, and then we buckled down and got to work.

但是当我们熬完那个通宵，我们就完了。书寄来了。我们睡了。

But when we were done with that all-nighter, we were done. The book shipped. And we slept.

睡觉

Sleep

程序员生命中最宝贵的成分就是充足的睡眠。我在七小时内做得很好。我可以忍受六个小时中的一两天。再少一点，我的工作效率就会直线下降。确保你知道你的身体需要多少小时的睡眠，然后优先考虑这些时间。那些时间将不仅仅是回报自己。我的经验法则是，第一个小时的睡眠不足会让我在白天工作两个小时。第二个小时的睡眠不足让我又损失了四个小时的生产性工作。而且，当然，如果我晚睡三个小时，就根本没有任何生产性工作。

The most precious ingredient in the life of a programmer is sufficient sleep. I do well on seven hours. I can tolerate a day or two of six hours. Anything less, and my productivity plummets. Make sure you know how many hours of sleep your body needs, and then prioritize those hours. Those hours will more than pay themselves back. My rule of thumb is that the first hour of insufficient sleep costs me two hours of daytime work. The second hour of insufficient sleep costs me another four hours of productive work. And, of course, there’s no productive work at all if I’m three hours behind on my sleep.

集体所有制

Collective Ownership

没有人拥有敏捷项目中的代码。代码归团队所有。团队中的任何成员都可以随时检查和改进项目中的任何模块。团队集体拥有代码。

No one owns the code in an Agile project. The code is owned by the team as a whole. Any member of the team can check out and improve any module in the project at any time. The team owns the code collectively.

在泰瑞达工作期间，我在职业生涯的早期就学会了集体所有权。我们在一个大型系统上工作，该系统由分成数百个模块的五万行代码组成。然而，团队中没有人拥有这些模块中的任何一个。我们都努力学习和改进所有这些模块。哦，我们中的一些人比其他人更熟悉代码的某些部分，但我们试图传播而不是集中这种经验。

I learned Collective Ownership early in my career while working at Teradyne. We worked on a large system composed of fifty thousand lines of code partitioned into several hundred modules. Yet no one on the team owned any of those modules. We all strove to learn and improve all of those modules. Oh, some of us were more familiar with certain parts of the code than others, but we sought to spread rather than concentrate that experience.

该系统是早期的分布式网络。有一台中央计算机与分布在全国各地的几十台卫星计算机进行通信。这些计算机通过 300 波特调制解调器线路进行通信。在中央计算机和卫星计算机上工作的程序员之间没有区别。我们都为他们俩开发了软件。

That system was an early distributed network. There was a central computer that communicated with several dozen satellite computers that were distributed across the country. These computers communicated over 300-baud modem lines. There was no division between the programmers who worked on the central computer and the satellite computers. We all worked on the software for both of them.

这两台计算机的架构截然不同。一个类似于 PDP-8，只是它有一个 18 位字。它有 256K 的 RAM，是从磁带盒中加载的。另一个是带有 32K RAM 和 32K ROM 的 8085 8 位微处理器。

These two computers had very different architectures. One was similar to a PDP-8 except that it had an 18-bit word. It had 256K of RAM and was loaded from magnetic tape cartridges. The other was a 8085 8-bit microprocessor with 32K of RAM and 32K of ROM.

我们在汇编器中对这些进行了编程。两台机器的汇编语言和开发环境截然不同。我们都以同样的舒适度与他们一起工作。

We programmed these in assembler. The two machines had very different assembly languages and very different development environments. We all worked with both with equal comfort.

集体所有权并不意味着你不能专业化。随着系统变得越来越复杂，专业化成为绝对必要的。有些系统根本无法全面和详细地理解。然而，即使你专攻，你也必须概括。将您的工作分配给您的专业和代码的其他领域。保持你在专业之外工作的能力。

Collective Ownership does not mean that you cannot specialize. As systems grow in complexity, specialization becomes an absolute necessity. There are systems that simply cannot be understood in both entirety and detail. However, even as you specialize, you must also generalize. Divide your work between your specialty and other areas of the code. Maintain your ability to work outside of your specialty.

当一个团队实行集体所有权时，知识就会在整个团队中传播。每个团队成员都能更好地了解模块之间的界限以及系统的整体工作方式。这极大地提高了团队沟通和决策的能力。
