When a team practices Collective Ownership, knowledge becomes distributed across the team. Each team member gains a better understanding of the boundaries between modules and of the overall way that the system works. This drastically improves the ability of the team to communicate and make decisions.

在我相当长的职业生涯中，我见过一些与集体所有制相反的公司。每个程序员都拥有自己的模块，其他人不得触摸它们。这些是严重功能失调的团队，他们经常参与相互指责和沟通不畅。当作者不在工作时，模块中的所有进度都会停止。没有其他人敢在别人拥有的东西上工作。

In my rather long career, I have seen a few companies that practiced the opposite of Collective Ownership. Each programmer owned their own modules, and no one else was allowed to touch them. These were grossly dysfunctional teams who were constantly involved in finger pointing and miscommunication. All progress in a module would stop when the author was not at work. No one else dared to work on something owned by someone else.

X档案

The X Files

一个特别糟糕的案例是制造高端打印机的 X 公司。在 1990 年代，该公司正在从主要的硬件重点过渡到集成的硬件和软件重点。他们意识到，如果他们使用软件来控制机器的内部操作，就可以显着降低制造成本。

One particularly maladroit case was the company X, which built high-end printers. In the 1990s, the company was transitioning from a predominant hardware focus to an integrated hardware and software focus. They realized that they could cut their manufacturing costs significantly if they used software to control the internal operation of their machines.

然而，硬件重点根深蒂固，因此软件组按照与硬件相同的路线划分。硬件团队是按设备组织的：进纸器、打印机、堆叠器、订书机等都有各自的硬件团队。软件是根据相同的设备组织的。一个团队为进纸器编写控制软件，另一个团队为订书机编写软件，等等。

However, the hardware focus was deeply ingrained, so the software groups were divided along the same lines as the hardware. The hardware teams were organized by device: there were respective hardware teams for the feeder, printer, stacker, stapler, etc. The software was organized according to the same devices. One team wrote the control software for the feeder, another team wrote the software for the stapler, and so forth.

在 X 中，您的政治影响力取决于您使用的设备。由于 X 是一家打印机公司，因此打印机设备是最负盛名的。在打印机上工作的硬件工程师必须通过排名才能到达那里。订书机的家伙是无名小卒。

In X, your political clout depended on the device you worked on. Since X was a printer company, the printer device was the most prestigious. The hardware engineers who worked on the printer had to come up through the ranks to get there. The stapler guys were nobodies.

奇怪的是，同样的政治排名系统也适用于软件团队。编写堆垛机代码的开发人员在政治上无能为力；但是如果打印机开发人员在会议上发言，其他人都会仔细聆听。由于这种政治分歧，没有人分享他们的代码。打印机团队的政治影响力的关键被锁在打印机代码中。所以打印机代码也保持锁定状态。该团队之外的任何人都看不到它。

Oddly, this same political ranking system applied to the software teams. The developers writing the stacker code were politically impotent; but if a printer developer spoke in a meeting, everyone else listened closely. Because of this political division, no one shared their code. The key to the printer team’s political clout was locked up in the printer code. So the printer code stayed locked up, too. Nobody outside that team could see it.

这引起的问题很多。当您无法检查正在使用的代码时，存在明显的沟通困难。还有不可避免的指责和背叛。

The problems this caused were legion. There are the obvious communication difficulties when you can’t inspect the code you are using. There is also the inevitable finger pointing and backstabbing.

但比这更糟糕的是纯粹的、荒谬的重复。事实证明，用于进纸器、打印机、堆叠器和订书机的控制软件并没有什么不同。他们都必须根据外部输入和内部传感器来控制电机、继电器、螺线管和离合器。这些模块的基本内部结构是相同的。然而，由于所有的政治保障，每个团队都必须独立发明自己的轮子。

But worse than that was the sheer, ridiculous duplication. It turns out that the control software for a feeder, printer, stacker, and stapler aren’t that different. They all had to control motors, relays, solenoids, and clutches based upon external inputs and internal sensors. The basic internal structure of these modules was the same. And yet, because of all the political safeguarding, each team had to invent their own wheels independently.

更重要的是，软件应该按照硬件划分的想法是荒谬的。软件系统不需要独立于打印机控制器的进纸器控制器。

Even more important, the very idea that the software should be divided along hardware lines was absurd. The software system did not need a feeder controller that was independent of the printer controller.

人力资源的浪费，更不用说情绪上的焦虑和敌对的姿态，导致了一个非常不舒服的环境。我相信这种环境至少在一定程度上促成了他们最终的垮台。

The waste of human resources, not to mention the emotional angst and adversarial posturing, led to a very uncomfortable environment. I believe that this environment was instrumental, at least in part, to their eventual downfall.

持续集成

Continuous Integration

在敏捷的早期，持续集成的实践意味着开发人员每隔“几个小时”检查一次他们的源代码更改并将它们与主线合并。6所有单元测试和验收测试保持通过。没有未集成的功能分支。部署时不应激活的任何更改都通过使用切换来处理。

In the early days of Agile, the practice of Continuous Integration meant that developers checked in their source code changes and merged them with the main line every “couple of hours.”6 All unit tests and acceptance tests kept passing. No feature branches remained unintegrated. Any changes that should not be active when deployed were dealt with by using toggles.

6 . Beck, K. 2000。极限编程解释：拥抱变化。马萨诸塞州波士顿：Addison-Wesley，p. 97.

6. Beck, K. 2000. Extreme Programming Explained: Embrace Change. Boston, MA: Addison-Wesley, p. 97.

2000 年，在我们的一门 XP Immersion 课程中，一名学生陷入了一个经典陷阱。这些沉浸式课程非常激烈。我们将周期缩短为单日迭代。持续集成周期缩短到 15 到 30 分钟。

In the year 2000, at one of our XP Immersion classes, a student got caught in a classic trap. These immersion classes were intense. We shortened the cycles down to single-day iterations. The Continuous Integration cycle was down to 15 to 30 minutes.

有问题的学生在一个由六名开发人员组成的团队中工作，其中五个人的签到频率比他高。（由于某种原因他没有配对——想想看。）不幸的是，这个学生在一个多小时的时间里一直没有集成他的代码。

The student in question was working in a team of six developers, five of whom were checking in more frequently than he was. (He was not pairing for some reason—go figure.) Unfortunately, this student had kept his code unintegrated for over an hour.

当他最终尝试签入并集成他的更改时，他发现已经积累了如此多的其他更改，以至于合并花了他很长时间才能开始工作。当他为合并而苦苦挣扎时，其他程序员继续进行 15 分钟的签到。当他终于让他的合并工作并试图检查他的代码时，他发现他还有另一个合并要做。

When he finally tried to check in and integrate his changes, he found that so many other changes had accumulated that the merge took him a long time to get working. While he was struggling with that merge, the other programmers continued to make 15-minute checkins. When he finally got his merge working and tried to check in his code, he found he had another merge to do.

他对此非常沮丧，以至于他站在课堂中间大声宣布：“XP 不起作用。” 然后他冲出教室，去了酒店的酒吧。

He was so frustrated by this that he stood up in the middle of class and loudly proclaimed, “XP doesn’t work.” Then he stormed out of the classroom and went to the hotel bar.

然后奇迹发生了。被他拒绝的那对搭档追上来劝他。另外两对重新确定了工作的优先级，完成了合并，并使项目重回正轨。三十分钟后，这名学生平静多了，回到房间，道了歉，然后继续他的工作——包括配对。随后，他成为敏捷开发的热情倡导者。

And then a miracle happened. The pair partner that he had rejected went after him to talk him down. The other two pairs reprioritized their work, finished the merge, and got the project back on track. Thirty minutes later the student, now much calmer, came back in the room, apologized, and resumed his work—including pairing. He subsequently became an enthusiastic advocate for Agile development.

关键是持续集成只有在持续集成时才有效。

The point is that Continuous Integration only works if you integrate continuously.

然后是持续构建

Then Came Continuous Build

2001 年，ThoughtWorks 显着改变了游戏规则。他们创建了CruiseControl，7第一个持续构建工具。我记得 Mike Two 8在 2001 XP Immersion 上就此进行了深夜演讲。没有那个演讲的录音，但故事是这样的：

In 2001, ThoughtWorks changed the game significantly. They created CruiseControl,7 the first continuous build tool. I remember Mike Two8 giving a late-night lecture about this at a 2001 XP Immersion. There’s no recording of that speech, but the story went something like this:

7 . https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CruiseControl

7. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CruiseControl

8 . http://wiki.c2.com/?MikeTwo

8. http://wiki.c2.com/?MikeTwo

CruiseControl 允许签到时间缩短到几分钟。即使是最微小的变化也会迅速集成到主线中。CruiseControl 监视源代码控制系统，并在每次签入任何更改时启动构建。作为构建的一部分，CruiseControl 为系统运行大部分自动化测试，然后将结果通过电子邮件发送给团队中的每个人。

CruiseControl allows the checkin time to shrink down to a few minutes. Even the most minor change is quickly integrated into the mainline. CruiseControl watches the source code control system and kicks off a build every time any change is checked in. As part of the build, CruiseControl runs the majority of the automated tests for the system and then sends email to everyone on the team with the results.

“鲍勃，破坏了构建。”

“Bob, broke the build.”

我们实施了一个关于破坏构建的简单规则。在你打破身材的那一天，你必须穿一件写着“我打破身材”的衬衫——而且从来没有人洗过那件衬衫。

We implemented a simple rule about breaking the build. On the day that you break the build, you have to wear a shirt that says, “I broke the build”—and no one ever washes that shirt.

从那时起，已经创建了许多其他持续构建工具。它们包括Jenkins（或者是Hudson？）、Bamboo和TeamCity等工具。这些工具可以将集成之间的时间缩短到最低限度。肯特原来的“couple of hours”被改为“a few minutes”。持续集成已成为持续检查。

Since those days, many other continuous build tools have been created. They include tools like Jenkins (or is it Hudson?), Bamboo, and TeamCity. These tools allow the time between integrations to shrink to a minimum. Kent’s original “couple of hours” has been replaced by “a few minutes.” Continuous Integration has become Continuous Checkin.

持续构建纪律

The Continuous Build Discipline

持续构建不应该中断。那是因为，为了避免穿 Mike Two 的脏衬衫，每个程序员在签入代码之前都运行所有验收测试和所有单元测试。（呃！）所以如果构建失败，就会发生一些非常奇怪的事情。

The continuous build should never break. That’s because, in order to avoid wearing Mike Two’s dirty shirt, each programmer runs all acceptance tests and all unit tests before they check in their code. (Duh!) So if the build breaks, something very strange has happened.

Mike Two 在他的演讲中也谈到了这个问题。他描述了他们放在团队房间墙上显眼位置的日历。这是一年中的每一天都有一个正方形的大海报之一。

Mike Two addressed this issue in his lecture, too. He described the calendar that they put in a prominent position on the wall of their team room. It was one of those large posters that had a square for every day of the year.

在构建失败的任何一天，即使有一次，他们也会放置一个红点。在构建从未失败的任何一天，他们都会放置一个绿点。只是那个简单的视觉效果就足以在一两个月内将以红点为主的日历转变为以绿点为主的日历。

In any day where the build failed, even once, they placed a red dot. In any day where the build never failed, they placed a green dot. Just that simple visual was enough to transform a calendar of mostly red dots into a calendar of mostly green dots within a month or two.

停止压力机

再次强调：持续构建永远不应该中断。损坏的构建是Stop the Presses事件。我希望警报响起。我希望首席执行官办公室里有一个大红灯在旋转。一个破损的构建是一个Big Effing Deal。我希望所有的程序员都停止他们正在做的事情并围绕构建集结起来以使其再次通过。团队的口头禅必须是The Build Never Breaks。

Again: The continuous build should never break. A broken build is a Stop the Presses event. I want sirens going off. I want a big red light spinning in the CEO’s office. A broken build is a Big Effing Deal. I want all the programmers to stop what they are doing and rally around the build to get it passing again. The mantra of the team must be The Build Never Breaks.

作弊的代价

有些团队迫于截止日期的压力，让持续构建一直处于失败状态。这是自杀行为。发生的情况是，每个人都厌倦了来自持续构建服务器的持续不断的失败电子邮件，因此他们删除了失败的测试，并承诺他们会“稍后”返回并修复它们。

There have been teams who, under the pressure of a deadline, have allowed the continuous build to remain in a failed state. This is a suicidal move. What happens is that everyone gets tired of the continuous barrage of failure emails from the continuous build server, so they remove the failing tests with the promise that they’ll go back and fix them “later.”

当然，这会导致持续构建服务器再次开始发送成功邮件。每个人都放松了。构建正在通过。每个人都忘记了他们留待“稍后”修复的一堆失败测试。因此部署了一个损坏的系统。

Of course, this causes the continuous build server to start sending success emails again. Everyone relaxes. The build is passing. And everyone forgets about the pile of failing tests that they set aside to be fixed “later.” And so a broken system gets deployed.

站立会议

Standup Meetings

多年来，人们对“每日 Scrum”或“站会”有很多困惑。现在让我理清所有这些困惑。

Over the years, there has been a great deal of confusion about “The Daily Scrum” or the “Standup Meeting.” Let me cut through all that confusion now.

以下是站立会议的真实情况：

The following are true of the Standup Meeting:

  • 这次会议是可选的。许多团队没有一个也能过得很好。

  • This meeting is optional. Many teams get by just fine without one.

  • 它可以比每天少。选择对您有意义的时间表。

  • It can be less often than daily. Pick the schedule that makes sense to you.

  • 它应该需要大约 10 分钟，即使对于大型团队也是如此。

  • It should take ∼10 minutes, even for large teams.

  • 这次会议遵循一个简单的公式。

  • This meeting follows a simple formula.

基本思路是团队成员9人站成一圈，回答三个问题：

The basic idea is that the team members stand9 in a circle and answer three questions:

9 . 这就是它被称为“站会”的原因。

9. This is why it’s called a “standup” meeting.

  1. 上次会议后我做了什么？

  2. What did I do since the last meeting?

  3. 在下次会议之前我要做什么？

  4. What will I do until the next meeting?

  5. 有什么妨碍我的？

  6. What is in my way?

就这样。没有讨论。没有装腔作势。没有深入的解释。没有寒冷的房子，也没有黑暗的想法。没有关于 Jean 和 Joan 以及谁知道谁的抱怨。每个人都有 30 秒左右的时间来回答这三个问题。然后会议结束，大家回到工作岗位。完毕。完成。狂欢？

That’s all. No discussion. No posturing. No deep explanations. No cold houses nor dark thoughts. No complaints about Jean and Joan and who knows who. Everybody gets 30 seconds or so to answer those three questions. Then the meeting is over and everyone returns to work. Done. Finito. Capisce?

也许对站立会议的最好描述在 Ward 的 wiki 上：http ://wiki.c2.com/?StandUpMeeting 。

Perhaps the best description of the standup meeting is on Ward’s wiki: http://wiki.c2.com/?StandUpMeeting.

猪和鸡？

Pigs and Chickens?

我不会在这里重复火腿和鸡蛋的故事。有兴趣的可以在脚注10中查找。要点是只有开发人员才能在站会上发言。经理和其他人可以旁听，但不应插话。

I won’t repeat the ham-and-eggs story here. You can look it up in the footnote10 if you are interested. The gist is that only developers should speak at the standup. Managers and other folks may listen in but should not interject.

10。https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Chicken_and_the_Pig

10. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Chicken_and_the_Pig

在我看来，我不在乎谁发言，只要每个人都遵循相同的三个问题的格式并且会议时间控制在 10 分钟左右即可。

From my point of view, I don’t care who speaks so long as everyone follows the same three-question format and the meeting is kept to about 10 minutes.

喊出来

Shout-out

我喜欢的一个修改是添加可选的第四个问题：

One modification that I have enjoyed is to add an optional fourth question:

  • 你想感谢谁？

  • Whom do you want to thank?

这只是对帮助过你的人或做了你认为值得表扬的事情的人的快速致谢。

This is just a quick acknowledgment of someone who helped you or who did something you believe deserves recognition.

结论

Conclusion

敏捷是一组原则、实践和准则，可帮助小型团队构建小型软件项目。本章描述的实践是帮助那些小团队表现得像真正的团队的实践。他们帮助团队设定他们用来交流的语言，以及对团队成员如何对待彼此以及他们正在构建的项目的期望。

Agile is a set of principles, practices, and disciplines that help small teams build small software projects. The practices described in this chapter are those that help those small teams behave like true teams. They help the teams set the language they use to communicate, as well as the expectations for how the team members will behave toward each other and toward the project they are building.

5.技术实践

5. Technical Practices

本章中的实践描述了与大多数程序员在过去 70 年中的行为方式的彻底相背。他们强制执行一套深刻的每分钟和每秒的仪式行为，大多数程序员最初认为这些行为是荒谬的。因此，许多程序员试图在没有这些实践的情况下进行敏捷开发。然而，它们失败了，因为这些实践是敏捷的核心。没有 TDD、重构、简单设计，是的，甚至没有结对编程，敏捷就变成了一个无效的软壳，无法实现它的预期。

The practices in this chapter describe a radical departure from the way most programmers have behaved during the last 70 years. They enforce a profound minute-by-minute and second-by-second set of ritualistic behaviors that most programmers initially consider absurd. Many programmers have therefore attempted to do Agile without these practices. They fail, however, because these practices are the very core of Agile. Without TDD, Refactoring, Simple Design, and yes, even Pair Programming, Agile becomes an ineffective flaccid shell of what it was intended to be.

测试驱动开发

Test-Driven Development

测试驱动开发是一个丰富而复杂的主题，需要整本书才能完全涵盖。本章只是一个概述，更多地关注理由和动机，而不是实践的更深层次的技术方面。特别是，本章不会显示任何代码。

Test-Driven Development is a rich and complex topic that will require an entire book to cover properly. This chapter is merely an overview that focuses more on justification and motivation than on the deeper technical aspects of the practice. In particular, this chapter will not show any code.

程序员从事的是一种独特的职业。我们制作了大量包含深奥技术和神秘符号的文档。写入这些文件的每个符号都必须正确；否则，真正可怕的事情就会发生。一个错误的符号可能会导致财富和生命的损失。还有哪个职业是这样的？

Programmers are engaged in a unique profession. We produce huge documents of deeply technical and arcane symbology. Every symbol written into these documents must be correct; otherwise, truly terrible things can happen. One wrong symbol can result in the loss of fortunes and lives. What other profession is like that?

会计。会计师制作了大量的技术文档和神秘的符号系统。写入他们文件的每个符号都必须正确，以免失去财富，甚至可能失去生命。会计师如何确保每个符号都是正确的？

Accounting. Accountants produce huge documents of deeply technical and arcane symbology. Every symbol written into their documents must be correct lest fortunes, and possibly even lives, be lost. How do accountants ensure that every symbol is correct?

复式簿记

Double-Entry Bookkeeping

会计师有一门 1000 年前发明的学科。这叫做复式簿记。1他们记入账簿的每笔交易都被输入了两次：一次作为一组账户中的贷方，另一次作为另一组账户中的补充借方。这些账户最终流入一个称为资产负债表的单一文件，该文件从资产总和中减去负债和权益总和。该差异必须为零。如果它不为零，则说明已发生错误。2个

Accountants have a discipline that was invented 1000 years ago. It’s called double-entry bookkeeping.1 Every transaction they enter into their books is entered twice: once as a credit in one set of accounts, and again as a complementary debit in another set of accounts. These accounts eventually flow into a single document called the balance sheet, which subtracts the sum of liabilities and equities from the sum of assets. That difference must be zero. If it is not zero, then an error has been made.2

1 . https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Double-entry_bookkeeping_system

1. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Double-entry_bookkeeping_system

2 . 如果你学过会计，你的头发现在很可能着火了。是的，这是一个粗略的简化。另一方面，如果我在一个段落中描述 TDD，所有的程序员都会着火。

2. If you have studied accounting, your hair is likely now on fire. Yes, this was a gross simplification. On the other hand, had I described TDD in a single paragraph, all the programmers would set their hair on fire.

会计师在他们上学的早期就被教导一次输入一项交易并每次计算余额。这使他们能够快速捕获错误。他们被教导要避免在余额检查之间输入一批交易，因为这样很难发现错误。这种做法对于正确的货币核算非常重要，以至于它几乎已成为世界所有地区的法律。

Accountants are taught, in the early days of their schooling, to enter the transactions one at a time and compute the balance each time. This allows them to catch errors quickly. They are taught to avoid entering a batch of transactions between balance checks, since then errors would be hard to find. This practice is so essential to the proper accounting of monies that it has become law in virtually all parts of the world.

测试驱动开发是程序员相应的实践。每个必需的行为都输入两次：一次作为测试，然后再次作为使测试通过的产品代码。这两个条目是互补的，就像资产与负债和权益是互补的一样。当一起执行时，这两个条目产生零结果：无测试失败。

Test-Driven Development is the corresponding practice for programmers. Every required behavior is entered twice: once as a test, and then again as production code that makes the test pass. The two entries are complementary, just as assets are complementary to liabilities and equities. When executed together, the two entries produce a zero result: Zero tests failed.

学习 TDD 的程序员被教导一次输入每一个行为——一次作为失败的测试，然后再次作为通过测试的生产代码。这使他们能够快速捕获错误。他们被教导要避免编写大量生产代码然后添加一批测试，因为这样很难发现错误。

Programmers who learn TDD are taught to enter every behavior one at a time—once as a failing test, and then again as production code that passes the test. This allows them to catch errors quickly. They are taught to avoid writing a lot of production code and then adding a batch of tests, since errors would then be hard to find.

复式簿记和 TDD 这两个学科是等价的。它们都具有相同的功能：防止在每个符号都必须正确的极其重要的文档中出现错误。尽管编程对我们的社会来说已经变得多么重要，但我们还没有赋予 TDD 以法律效力。但考虑到生命和财富已经因编写糟糕的软件的变幻莫测而丧失，那么这条法律还会远吗？

These two disciplines, double-entry bookkeeping and TDD, are equivalent. They both serve the same function: to prevent errors in critically important documents where every symbol must be correct. Despite how essential programming has become to our society, we have not yet imbued TDD with the force of law. But given that lives and fortunes have already been lost to the vagaries of poorly written software, can that law be far away?

TDD 的三个规则

The Three Rules of TDD

TDD 可以用三个简单的规则来描述。

TDD can be described with three simple rules.

  • 在您第一次编写由于缺少该代码而失败的测试之前，不要编写任何生产代码。

  • Do not write any production code until you have first written a test that fails due to the lack of that code.

  • 不要编写超过足以导致失败的测试——编译失败算作失败。

  • Do not write more of a test than is sufficient to fail—and failing to compile counts as a failure.

  • 不要编写超过足以通过当前失败测试的生产代码。

  • Do not write more production code than is sufficient to pass the currently failing test.

具有几个月以上经验的程序员可能会认为这些规则即使不是彻头彻尾的愚蠢也很古怪。它们意味着一个大概五秒长的编程周期。程序员首先为尚不存在的生产代码编写一些测试代码。该测试几乎无法立即编译，因为它提到了尚未编写的生产代码元素。程序员必须停止编写测试并开始编写生产代码。但是仅仅敲了几次键之后，编译失败的测试现在可以正确编译了。这迫使程序员返回测试并继续添加到它。

A programmer with more than a few months’ experience will likely consider these rules to be outlandish, if not downright stupid. They imply a cycle of programming that is perhaps five seconds long. The programmer begins by writing some test code for production code that does not yet exist. This test fails to compile almost immediately because it mentions elements of the production code that have not yet been written. The programmer must stop writing the test and start writing production code. But after only a few keystrokes, the test that failed to compile now compiles properly. This forces the programmer to return to the test and continue to add to it.

测试代码和生产代码之间的这种振荡只有几秒钟的时间，程序员就被困在这个循环中。程序员将再也无法编写完整的函数，甚至是简单的if语句或while循环，而无需通过编写免费测试代码来打断自己。

This oscillation between the test and the production code is just a few seconds long, and the programmers are trapped within this cycle. The programmers will never again be able to write an entire function, or even a simple if statement or while loop, without interrupting themselves by writing the complimentary test code.

大多数程序员最初将此视为他们思维过程的中断。三个规则强加的这种持续中断使他们无法正确思考他们正在编写的代码。他们常常觉得三项规则造成了无法忍受的分心。

Most programmers initially view this as a disruption of their thought processes. This continual interruption imposed by the Three Rules prevents them from properly thinking through the code they are writing. They often feel that the Three Rules create an intolerable distraction.

然而，想象一下一群遵循这三个规则的程序员。随时选择您喜欢的任何一位程序员。程序员所做的一切都在不到一个时间内执行并通过了所有测试一分钟前。无论您选择谁或何时选择他们，一切都在不到一分钟前能正常运行。

However, imagine a group of programmers following these Three Rules. Choose any one of those programmers you like, at any time. Everything that programmer was working on executed and passed all its tests less than a minute ago. It doesn’t matter whom you choose or when you choose them—everything worked less than a minute ago.

调试

Debugging

如果一切都在一分钟前正常工作会怎样？您需要进行多少调试？如果一分钟前一切正常，那么您遇到的几乎所有故障都不会发生在一分钟之内。调试在最后一分钟添加的故障通常是微不足道的。事实上，使用调试器来查找问题可能有点矫枉过正。

What would it be like if everything always worked a minute ago? How much debugging would you have to do? If everything worked a minute ago, then almost any failure you encounter will be less than a minute old. Debugging a failure that was added in the last minute is often trivial. Indeed, using a debugger to find the problem is probably overkill.

您是否熟练操作调试器？您是否记住了调试器的热键？您的肌肉记忆会自动知道如何敲击这些键来设置断点、单步执行、单步执行和单步执行吗？当你调试的时候，你觉得自己在你的元素中吗？这不是一项需要的技能。

Are you skilled at operating the debugger? Do you have the debugger’s hot keys memorized? Does your muscle memory automatically know how to hit those keys to set breakpoints, single-step, step-into, and step-over? When you are debugging, do you feel like you are in your element? This is not a skill to be desired.

要想熟练使用调试器，唯一的方法就是花大量时间进行调试。花很多时间调试意味着总是有很多错误。测试驱动开发人员不擅长操作调试器，因为他们根本不经常使用调试器；当他们这样做时，通常会持续很短的时间。

The only way you get good at using a debugger is by spending a lot of time debugging. Spending a lot of time debugging implies that there are always a lot of bugs. Test-Driven Developers are not skilled at operating the debugger because they simply don’t use a debugger that often; and when they do, it is typically for a very brief amount of time.

现在我不想造成错误的印象。即使是最好的测试驱动开发人员仍然会遇到棘手的错误。这仍然是软件；仍然很难。但是，通过实践这三个规则，错误的发生率和严重性会大大降低。

Now I don’t want to create a false impression. Even the best Test-Driven Developer still encounters difficult bugs. This is still software; it’s still hard. But the incidence and severity of bugs is vastly reduced by practicing the Three Rules.

文档

Documentation

你有没有集成过第三方包？它可能来自一个 zip 文件，其中包含一些源代码、DLL、JAR 文件等。该存档中的文件之一可能是包含集成说明的 PDF。在 PDF 的末尾，可能有一个丑陋的附录，其中包含所有代码示例。

Have you ever integrated a third-party package? It likely came in a zip file that contained some source code, DLLs, JAR files, etc. One of the files in that archive was likely a PDF that contained the instructions for integration. At the end of the PDF, there was probably an ugly appendix with all the code examples.

你在该文件中读到的第一件事是什么？如果你是一名程序员，你会直接跳到后面阅读代码示例，因为代码会告诉你真相。

What was the first thing you read in that document? If you are a programmer, you skipped right to the back and read the code examples because the code will tell you the truth.

当您遵循三个规则时，您最终编写的测试将成为整个系统的代码示例。如果你想知道如何调用一个 API 函数，有一些测试可以调用该函数的每一种方式，捕获它可以抛出的每一个异常。如果您想知道如何创建一个对象，可以通过各种测试来创建该对象。

When you follow the Three Rules, the tests you end up writing become the code examples for the whole system. If you want to know how to call an API function, there are tests that call that function every way it can be called, catching every exception it can throw. If you want to know how to create an object, there are tests that create that object every way it can be created.

测试是描述被测系统的一种文档形式。本文档是用程序员熟悉的语言编写的。它完全明确，执行起来非常正式，并且不会与应用程序代码脱节。测试是程序员的完美文档：代码。

The tests are a form of documentation that describe the system being tested. This documentation is written in a language that the programmers know fluently. It is utterly unambiguous, it is so formal it executes, and it cannot get out of sync with the application code. The tests are the perfect kind of documentation for programmers: code.

更重要的是，测试本身并没有形成一个系统。测试彼此不了解。测试之间没有依赖关系。每个测试都是一个小而独立的代码单元，用于描述系统一小部分的行为方式。

What’s more, the tests do not form a system in and of themselves. The tests don’t know about each other. There are no dependencies between the tests. Each test is a small and independent unit of code that describes the way one small part of the system behaves.

乐趣

Fun

如果您曾经在事后编写过测试，您就会知道这并不是一件很有趣的事情。这并不好玩，因为您已经知道代码可以工作。你已经手动测试过了。您编写这些测试很可能是因为有人告诉您您必须这样做。感觉工作很忙。这很无聊。

If you have ever written tests after the fact, you know that it’s not a lot of fun. It’s not fun because you already know the code works. You’ve tested it manually. You are likely writing those tests because someone told you that you had to. It feels like busy work. It’s boring.

当您首先根据三个规则编写测试时，这很有趣。每一个新的测试都是一个挑战。每次通过测试，都是小成功。当您遵循三项规则时，您的工作就是这些小挑战和成功的链条。感觉不像是忙碌的工作——感觉像是让事情运转起来。

When you write the tests first according to the Three Rules, it’s fun. Every new test is a challenge. Every time you make a test pass, it’s a small success. Your work, as you follow the Three Rules, is a chain of those small challenges and successes. It doesn’t feel like busy work—it feels like getting stuff working.

完整性

Completeness

现在让我们回到事后测试。即使您已经手动测试了系统并且您已经知道它可以工作，但您还是觉得有义务编写这些测试。您从一个测试进行到另一个测试，对测试通过这一事实并不感到惊讶。

Now let’s return to after-the-fact tests. You somehow feel obligated to write these tests even though you’ve tested the system manually, and you already know it works. You proceed from test to test being unsurprised by the fact that the tests pass.

不可避免地，你会遇到一个很难写的测试。很难编写，因为当您编写代码时，您没有考虑可测试性，也没有将其设计为可测试。要为此代码编写测试，您将不得不通过打破一些耦合、添加一些抽象和/或重新路由一些函数调用和参数来更改结构。这感觉需要付出很多努力，尤其是因为您已经知道代码可以工作。

Inevitably, you will come to a test that’s hard to write. It’s hard to write because when you wrote the code you weren’t thinking about testability, and you did not design it to be testable. To write a test for this code, you are going to have to change the structure by breaking some couplings, adding some abstractions, and/or rerouting some function calls and arguments. This feels like a lot of effort, especially because you already know the code works.

日程安排很紧，您知道自己有更紧迫的事情要做。所以，你搁置了那个测试。你说服自己，要么它是不必要的，要么你稍后回去写。因此，您在测试套件中留下了一个漏洞。

The schedule is tight, and you know you have more pressing things to do. So, you set that test aside. You convince yourself either that it is unnecessary or that you’ll go back and write it later. Thus, you leave a hole in the test suite.

并且由于您在测试套件中留下了漏洞，您怀疑其他人也有。当您执行测试套件并看到它通过时，您会大笑、假笑或轻蔑地挥手，因为您知道套件通过并不意味着系统正常工作。

And since you have left holes in the test suite, you suspect everyone else has, too. When you execute the test suite and see it pass, you laugh, smirk, or derisively wave your hand because you know that the passing of the suite doesn’t mean that the system works.

当这样的测试套件通过时，您无法做出任何决定。通过测试给你的唯一信息是没有任何测试被破坏。测试套件的不完整性让您别无选择。然而，如果你遵循三个规则，那么每一行生产代码都是为了通过测试而编写的。因此，测试套件非常完整。当它通过时，你可以做出决定。该决定是部署。

When such a test suite passes, there is no decision you can make. The only information that the passing tests give you is that nothing tested is broken. The incompleteness of the test suite leaves you with no options. However, if you follow the Three Rules, then every line of production code was written in order to make a test pass. Therefore, the test suite is very complete. When it passes, you can make a decision. That decision is to deploy.

这就是目标。我们想创建一套自动化测试，告诉我们部署系统是安全的。

That’s the goal. We want to create a suite of automated tests that tells us that it is safe to deploy the system.

再说一遍，我不想画假图。遵循三个规则会给你一个非常完整的测试套件，但它可能不是 100% 完整的。这是因为在某些情况下，遵循三项规则是不切实际的。这些情况超出了本书的范围，只是说它们是有限的，并且有缓解它们的解决方案。结果是，即使是三项规则最勤奋的拥护者也不太可能生成 100% 完整的测试套件。

Now again, I don’t want to paint a false picture. Following the Three Rules will give you a very complete test suite, but it is probably not 100% complete. This is because there are situations in which following the Three Rules is not practical. These situations are outside the scope of this book except to say that they are limited, and there are solutions that mitigate them. The result is that even the most diligent adherents to the Three Rules are not likely to produce a test suite that is 100% complete.

但部署决策不需要 100% 的完整性。覆盖 90% 可能就足够了——而且这种完整性是非常容易实现的。

But 100% completeness is not necessary for the deployment decision. Coverage in the high 90s is likely all that is required—and that kind of completeness is eminently achievable.

我已经创建了非常完整的测试套件，它们允许做出部署决策。我也看到很多其他人也这样做。在每一种情况下，完整性都低于 100%，但足以做出部署决策。

I have created test suites that are so complete that they allow the deployment decision to be made. I have seen many others do so as well. In each of those cases, the completeness was less than 100%, but it was high enough to make the deployment decision.

警告

Warning

测试覆盖率是团队指标，而不是管理指标。管理人员不太可能知道该指标的实际含义。管理人员不应将此指标用作目标或指标。团队应该只使用它来通知他们的测试策略。

Test coverage is a team metric, not a management metric. Managers are unlikely to know what the metric actually means. Managers should not use this metric as a goal or a target. The team should use it solely to inform their testing strategy.

双重警告

Double Warning

不要因为覆盖率不足而导致构建失败。如果你这样做，那么程序员将被迫从他们的测试中删除足够多的断言，以获得足够高的覆盖率。代码覆盖率是一个复杂的主题，只有在深入了解代码和测试的情况下才能理解。不要让它成为管理指标。

Do not fail the build based on insuffi cient coverage. If you do this, then the programmers will be forced to remove enough assertions from their tests in order to get the coverage numbers high enough. Code coverage is a complex topic that can only be understood in the context of a deep knowledge of the code and tests. Don’t let it become a management metric.

设计

Design

还记得事后难以测试的功能吗？它可能很难测试，因为它与您不想在测试中执行的行为相关联。例如，它可能会打开 X 光机或从数据库中删除行。该功能很难测试，因为您没有将其设计为易于测试。您首先编写了代码，现在您正在事后编写测试。当您编写代码时，为可测试性而设计是您考虑最远的事情。

Remember that function that’s hard to test after the fact? It may be hard to test because it is coupled to behaviors that you’d rather not execute in the test. For example, it might turn on the x-ray machine or delete rows out of the database. The function is hard to test because you did not design it to be easy to test. You wrote the code first, and you are now writing the tests as an afterthought. Designing for testability was the furthest thing from your mind when you wrote the code.

现在您面临着重新设计代码以对其进行测试。您看了看手表，发现整个测试过程已经花费了太长时间。因为您已经手动测试过它，并且知道它有效，所以您走开了，在测试套件中留下了另一个漏洞。

Now you are faced with redesigning the code in order to test it. You look at your watch and realize that this whole testing thing has taken too long already. Since you’ve already tested it manually, and you know it works, you walk away, leaving yet another hole in the test suite.

但是，当您首先编写测试时，会发生一些非常不同的事情。您不能编写难以测试的函数。既然是先写测试，自然会把要测试的功能设计得容易测试。您如何使功能易于测试？你解耦它们。事实上，可测试性只是解耦的同义词。

However, when you write the test first, something very different happens. You cannot write a function that is hard to test. Since you are writing the test first, you will naturally design the function you are testing to be easy to test. How do you keep functions easy to test? You decouple them. Indeed, testability is just a synonym for decoupling.

通过首先编写测试，您将以以前从未想过的方式解耦系统。整个系统将是可测试的；因此，整个系统将被解耦。

By writing the tests first, you will decouple the system in ways that you had never thought about before. The whole system will be testable; therefore, the whole system will be decoupled.

正是出于这个原因，TDD 通常被称为设计技术。三个规则迫使你进入更高程度的解耦。

It is for this reason that TDD is often called a design technique. The Three Rules force you into a much higher degree of decoupling.

勇气

Courage

到目前为止，我们已经看到遵循三个规则提供了许多强大的好处：更少的调试、良好的低级文档、乐趣、完整性和解耦。但这些只是附带的好处；这些都不是实践 TDD 的驱动原因。真正的原因是勇气。

So far, we’ve seen that following the Three Rules provides a number of powerful benefits: less debugging, good low-level documentation, fun, completeness, and decoupling. But these are just ancillary benefits; none of these is the driving reason for practicing TDD. The real reason is courage.

我在本书开头告诉过您以下故事，但值得在这里重复。

I told you the following story at the beginning of the book, but it bears repeating here.

想象一下，您正在屏幕上查看一些旧代码，而且一团糟。你心里想，“我应该把它清理干净。” 但你的下一个想法是，“我才不会碰它！” 因为你知道如果你触摸它，你会打破它；如果你打破它，它就会成为你的。所以你远离代码，任由烂摊子腐烂。

Imagine that you are looking at some old code on your screen, and it’s a mess. You think to yourself, “I should clean this up.” But your next thought is, “I’m not touching it!” Because you know if you touch it, you will break it; and if you break it, it becomes yours. So you back away from the code, leaving the mess to fester and rot.

这是一种恐惧反应。你害怕代码。你害怕触摸它。你害怕如果你打破它会发生什么。所以，你没有做一件可以改进代码的事情——你没有清理它。

This is a fear reaction. You fear the code. You fear touching it. You fear what will happen to you if you break it. So, you fail to do the one thing that could improve the code—you fail to clean it.

如果团队中的每个人都这样做，那么代码肯定会烂掉。没有人会清理它。没有人会改进它。添加的每个功能都将以最小化对程序员的直接风险的方式添加。耦合和重复将被添加，因为它们最小化了直接风险，即使它们破坏了代码的设计和完整性。

If everyone on the team behaves this way, then the code must rot. No one will clean it. No one will improve it. Every feature added will be added in such a way as to minimize the immediate risk to the programmers. Couplings and duplications will be added because they minimize the immediate risk, even though they corrupt the design and integrity of the code.

最终，代码将变成一团可怕的无法维护的意大利面条，以至于几乎无法取得任何进展。估计会成倍增长。管理者会变得绝望。将雇用越来越多的程序员以期提高生产力，但这种提高不会实现。

Eventually the code will become such a horrible mass of unmaintainable spaghetti that little to no progress can be made with it. Estimates will grow exponentially. Managers will become desperate. More and more programmers will be hired in the hopes of increasing productivity, but that increase will not be realized.

最后，在万般无奈之下，经理们只好同意程序员的要求，将整个系统从头开始重写，循环又开始了。

Finally, in utter desperation, the managers will agree to the programmers’ demands that the whole system should be rewritten from scratch, and the cycle will begin again.

想象一个不同的场景。回到那个乱七八糟的代码的屏幕。你的第一个想法是清理它。如果你有一个非常完整的测试套件，当它通过时你信任它会怎么样？如果该测试套件运行得很快怎么办？你的下一个想法是什么？它会是这样的：

Imagine a different scenario. Go back to that screen with the messy code. Your first thought was to clean it. What if you had a test suite that was so complete that you trusted it when it passed? What if that test suite ran quickly? What would your next thought be? It would be something like this:

天哪，我想我会更改该变量的名称。啊，测试仍然通过。好的，现在我将那个大函数拆分成两个较小的函数……很好，测试仍然通过……。好的，现在我想我可以将其中一个新功能移到另一个类中。哎呀！测试失败了。放回去……啊，我明白了，我也需要移动那个变量。是的，测试仍然通过……

Gosh, I think I’ll change the name of that variable. Ah, the tests still pass. OK, now I’ll split that big function into two smaller functions… Good, the tests still pass…. OK, now I think I can move one of those new functions over into a different class. Whoops! The tests failed. Put it back… Ah, I see, I needed to move that variable as well. Yes, the tests still pass…

当您拥有完整的测试套件时，您将不再害怕更改代码。你不再害怕清理代码。因此，您将清理代码。您将使系统保持整洁有序。您将保持系统设计的完整性。你不会创造出大量溃烂的意大利面条，将团队拖入低生产率和最终失败的低迷状态。

When you have a complete test suite, you lose your fear of changing the code. You lose your fear of cleaning the code. So, you will clean the code. You will keep the system neat and orderly. You will keep the design of the system intact. You will not create the festering mass of spaghetti that would drag the team into the doldrums of low productivity and eventual failure.

这就是我们实践 TDD 的原因。我们实践它是因为它给了我们保持代码整洁有序的勇气。它给了我们像专业人士一样行事的勇气。

That is why we practice TDD. We practice it because it gives us the courage to keep the code clean and orderly. It gives us the courage to act like professionals.

重构

Refactoring

重构是那些需要一本书来描述的主题之一。幸运的是，Martin Fowler 就这样一本书做了出色的工作。3在本章中，我将简单地讨论纪律，而不是具体的技术。同样，本章不包含任何代码。

Refactoring is another one of those topics that requires a book to describe. Fortunately, Martin Fowler has done a superb job with just such a book.3 In this chapter I’ll simply discuss the discipline, not the specific techniques. Again, this chapter contains no code.

3 . Fowler, M. 2019。重构：改进现有代码的设计，第 2 版。马萨诸塞州波士顿：Addison-Wesley。

3. Fowler, M. 2019. Refactoring: Improving the Design of Existing Code, 2nd ed. Boston, MA: Addison-Wesley.

重构是在不改变测试定义的行为的情况下改进代码结构的做法。换句话说，我们在不破坏任何测试的情况下更改名称、类、函数和表达式。我们改进系统的结构，而不影响行为。

Refactoring is the practice of improving the structure of the code without altering the behavior, as defined by the tests. In other words, we make changes to the names, the classes, the functions, and the expressions without breaking any of the tests. We improve the structure of the system, without affecting the behavior.

当然，这种做法与 TDD 密切相关。为了无所畏惧地重构代码，我们需要一个测试套件，让我们非常有信心我们没有破坏任何东西。

Of course, this practice couples strongly with TDD. To fearlessly refactor the code, we need a test suite that gives us very high confidence that we aren’t breaking anything.

重构期间所做的更改种类繁多，从微不足道的修饰到深度重构。更改可能是简单的名称更改或 switch 语句到多态调度的复杂重组。大函数将被拆分成更小、更好命名的函数。参数列表将更改为对象。有很多方法的类会被拆分成很多较小的班级。函数将从一个类移动到另一个类。类将被提取到子类或内部类中。依赖关系将被倒转，模块将跨架构边界移动。

The kinds of changes made during refactoring range from trivial cosmetics to deep restructurings. The changes might be simple name changes or complex reshufflings of switch statements to polymorphic dispatches. Large functions will be split into smaller, better-named, functions. Argument lists will be changed into objects. Classes with many methods will be split into many smaller classes. Functions will be moved from one class to another. Classes will be extracted into subclasses or inner classes. Dependencies will be inverted, and modules will be moved across architectural boundaries.

在所有这一切发生的同时，我们让测试不断通过。

And while all this is taking place, we keep the tests continuously passing.

红/绿/重构

Red/Green/Refactor

重构过程本质上融入了 TDD 的三个规则，即所谓的红/绿/重构循环（图 5.1）。

The process of refactoring is woven intrinsically into the Three Rules of TDD in what is known as the Red/Green/Refactor cycle (Figure 5.1).

  1. 首先，我们创建一个失败的测试。

  2. First, we create a test that fails.

  3. 然后我们让测试通过。

  4. Then we make the test pass.

  5. 然后我们清理代码。

  6. Then we clean up the code.

  7. 返回步骤 1。

  8. Return to step 1.

这里的想法是编写有效的代码和编写干净的代码是编程的两个不同维度。试图同时控制两个维度充其量是困难的，因此我们将两个维度分成两个不同的活动。

The idea here is that writing code that works and writing code that is clean are two separate dimensions of programming. Attempting to control both dimensions at the same time is difficult at best, so we separate the two dimensions into two different activities.

换句话说，让代码正常工作已经够难了，更不用说让代码干净了。因此，我们首先专注于通过我们贫乏的头脑中出现的任何混乱方法来使代码正常工作。然后，一旦工作，测试通过，我们就会清理我们造成的混乱。

To say this differently, it is hard enough to get code working, let alone getting the code to be clean. So we first focus on getting the code working by whatever messy means occur to our meager minds. Then, once working, with tests passing, we clean up the mess we made.

这清楚地表明重构是一个连续的过程，而不是按计划执行的过程。我们不会连续几天把事情弄得一团糟，然后再尝试清理。相反，我们会在一两分钟的时间里弄得一团糟，然后我们清理那个小烂摊子。

This makes it clear that refactoring is a continuous process, and not one that is performed on a scheduled basis. We don’t make a huge mess for days and days, and then try to clean it up. Rather, we make a very small mess, over a period of a minute or two, and then we clean up that small mess.

重构这个词永远不应该出现在日程表上。重构不是出现在计划中的那种活动。我们不会为重构预留时间。重构只是我们按分钟、按小时编写软件的方法的一部分。

The word Refactoring should never appear on a schedule. Refactoring is not the kind of activity that appears on a plan. We do not reserve time for refactoring. Refactoring is simply part of our minute-by-minute, hour-by-hour approach to writing software.

更大的重构

Bigger Refactorings

有时需求的变化会让您意识到系统的当前设计和体系结构不是最优的，您需要对系统结构进行重大更改。此类更改是在红/绿/重构周期内进行的。我们不会专门创建一个项目来更改设计。我们不会在时间表中为此类大型重构预留时间。相反，我们一次一小步地迁移代码，同时在正常的敏捷周期中继续添加新功能。

Sometimes the requirements change in such a way that you realize the current design and architecture of the system is suboptimal, and you need to make a significant change to the structure of the system. Such changes are made within the Red/Green/Refactor cycle. We do not create a project specifically to change the design. We do not reserve time in the schedule for such large refactorings. Instead, we migrate the code one small step at a time, while continuing to add new features during the normal Agile cycle.

这样的设计更改可能需要几天、几周甚至几个月的时间。在此期间，系统将继续通过所有测试并可能部署到生产环境中，即使设计转换仅部分完成。

Such a change to the design may take place over several days, weeks, or even months. During that time, the system continues to pass all its tests and may be deployed to production, even though the design transition is only partially complete.

简单的设计

Simple Design

简单设计的实践是重构的目标之一。简单设计是一种只编写所需代码的做法，其结构保持最简单、最小和最具表现力。

The practice of Simple Design is one of the goals of Refactoring. Simple Design is the practice of writing only the code that is required with a structure that keeps it simplest, smallest, and most expressive.

Kent Beck 的简单设计规则如下：

Kent Beck’s rules of Simple Design are as follows:

  1. 通过所有测试。

  2. Pass all the tests.

  3. 透露意图。

  4. Reveal the intent.

  5. 删除重复项。

  6. Remove duplication.

  7. 减少元素。

  8. Decrease elements.

这些数字既是它们的执行顺序，也是它们被赋予的优先级。

The numbers are both the order in which these are executed and the priority they are given.

第1点是不言而喻的。代码必须通过所有测试。代码必须有效。

Point 1 is self-evident. The code must pass all the tests. The code must work.

第 2 点说，在使代码工作之后，就应该使其具有表现力。它应该揭示程序员的意图。它应该易于阅读和自我描述。这是我们应用许多更简单和更美观的重构的地方。我们还将大函数拆分为更小、更好命名的函数。

Point 2 says that after the code is made to work, it should then be made expressive. It should reveal the intention of the programmer. It should be easy to read and self-descriptive. This is where we apply many of the simpler and more cosmetic refactorings. We also split large functions into smaller, better-named functions.

第 3 点说，在我们使代码尽可能具有描述性和表达性之后，我们会寻找并删除该代码中的任何重复项。我们不希望代码重复说同样的话。在此活动期间，重构通常更加复杂。有时删除重复就像将重复代码移动到一个函数中并从许多地方调用它一样简单。其他时候它需要更有趣的解决方案，例如设计模式：4 Template Method、Strategy、Decorator或Visitor。

Point 3 says that after we have made the code as descriptive and expressive as possible, we hunt for and remove any duplication within that code. We don’t want the code to say the same thing more than once. During this activity, the refactorings are usually more complicated. Sometimes removing duplication is as simple as moving the duplicate code into a function and calling it from many places. Other times it requires more interesting solutions, such as the Design Patterns:4 Template Method, Strategy, Decorator, or Visitor.

4 . 设计模式超出了本书的范围。参见 Gamma, E.、R. Helm、R. Johnson 和 J. Vlissides。1995.设计模式：可重用面向对象软件的要素。马萨诸塞州雷丁：Addison-Wesley。

4. Design Patterns are beyond the scope of this book. See Gamma, E., R. Helm, R. Johnson, and J. Vlissides. 1995. Design Patterns: Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software. Reading, MA: Addison-Wesley.

第 4 点说，一旦我们删除了所有重复项，我们应该努力减少结构元素的数量，例如类、函数、变量等。

Point 4 says that once we have removed all the duplication, we should strive to decrease the number of structural elements, such as classes, functions, variables, etc.

简单设计的目标是使代码的设计重量尽可能小。

The goal of Simple Design is to keep the design weight of the code as small as practicable.

设计重量

Design Weight

软件系统的设计范围从非常简单到异常复杂。设计越复杂，程序员的认知负担就越大。这种认知负荷就是设计重量。该设计的权重越大，程序员理解和操作系统所需的时间和精力就越多。

The designs of a software system range from quite simple to extraordinarily complex. The more complex the design, the greater the cognitive load placed on the programmers. That cognitive load is Design Weight. The greater the weight of that design, the more time and effort are required for the programmers to understand and manipulate the system.

同样，需求的复杂度也从很小到很大。需求越复杂，理解和操作系统所需的时间和精力就越多。

Similarly, the complexity of the requirements also ranges from very small to very great. The greater the complexity of the requirements, the more time and effort are required to understand and manipulate the system.

但是，这两个因素不是相加的。复杂的需求可以通过采用更复杂的设计来简化。通常这种权衡是有利的。通过为现有的一组功能选择合适的设计，可以降低系统的整体复杂性。

However, the two factors are not additive. Complex requirements can be simplified by employing a more complex design. Often the trade-off is favorable. The overall complexity of the system can be reduced by choosing the appropriate design for an existing set of features.

实现设计和功能复杂性的平衡是简单设计的目标。使用这种做法，程序员不断重构系统的设计，使其与需求保持平衡，从而保持生产力最大化。

Achieving this balance of design and feature complexity is the goal of Simple Design. Using this practice, programmers continuously refactor the design of the system to keep it in balance with the requirements and, therefore, keep productivity maximized.

结对编程

Pair Programming

多年来，结对编程的做法一直存在大量争议和虚假信息。许多人对两个（或更多）人可以在同一个问题上高效合作的想法持否定态度。

The practice of Pair Programming has enjoyed a substantial amount of controversy and disinformation over the years. Many folks react negatively to the idea that two (or more) people can work productively together on the same problem.

首先，配对是可选的。不应强迫任何人配对。其次，配对是间歇性的。不时独自编码有很多充分的理由。一个团队应该参与的配对数量是 50% 左右。这个数字并不重要。它可能低至 30% 或高达 80%。在大多数情况下，这是个人和团队的选择。

First of all, pairing is optional. No one should be forced to pair. Secondly, pairing is intermittent. There are many good reasons to code alone from time to time. The amount of pairing a team should engage in is 50% or so. That number is not critical. It could be as low as 30% or as much as 80%. For the most part, this is an individual and team choice.

什么是配对？

What Is Pairing?

结对是两个人一起解决一个编程问题的行为。两人可以在同一个工作站一起工作，共享屏幕、键盘和鼠标。或者他们可以在两个相连的工作站上工作，只要他们看到和操作相同的代码即可。后一个选项与流行的屏幕共享软件配合得很好。该软件还允许合作伙伴彼此远离，只要他们有良好的数据和语音连接。

Pairing is the act of two people working together on a single programming problem. The pair may work together at the same workstation, sharing the screen, keyboard, and mouse. Or they may work on two connected workstations so long as they see and manipulate the same code. The latter option works nicely with popular screen-sharing software. That software also allows the partners to be remote from each other, so long as they have a good data and voice link.

配对程序员有时扮演不同的角色。一个可能是司机，另一个是导航员。驱动程序有键盘和鼠标；导航器会放眼长远并提出建议。另一个角色选择是一个程序员编写测试，另一个使它通过并为第一个通过的程序员编写下一个测试。这有时称为乒乓球。

Pairing programmers sometimes adopt different roles. One may be the driver and the other the navigator. The driver has the keyboard and mouse; the navigator takes a longer view and makes recommendations. Another role option is for one programmer to write a test, and the other to make it pass and write the next test for the first programmer to pass. This is sometimes called Ping-Pong.

然而，大多数情况下根本没有角色。程序员只是平等的作者，以合作的方式共享鼠标和键盘。

Most often, however, there are no roles at all. The programmers are simply co-equal authors sharing the mouse and keyboard in a cooperative manner.

对没有安排。它们根据程序员的喜好形成和分解。管理者不应尝试创建配对时间表或配对矩阵。

Pairs are not scheduled. They form and break up according to the programmers’ preference. Managers should not try to create pairing schedules or pairing matrices.

对通常是短暂的。配对会话可以持续长达一天，但通常不会超过一两个小时。即使配对时间短至 15 到 30 分钟也是有益的。

Pairs are generally short-lived. A pairing session can last as long as a day, but more often they last no more than an hour or two. Even pairings as short as 15 to 30 minutes can be beneficial.

故事不分配给对。独立的程序员，而不是结对的，负责完成故事。一个故事的持续时间通常比单个配对长得多。

Stories are not assigned to pairs. Individual programmers, and not pairs, are responsible for completing stories. The duration of a story is generally much longer than a single pairing.

在一周的时间里，每个程序员将​​把大约一半的结对时间花在他们自己的任务上，并寻求其他几个人的帮助。他们配对时间的另一半将用于帮助他人完成任务。

Over the course of a week, each programmer will spend about half of their pairing time on their own tasks, recruiting the help of several others. The other half of their pairing time will be spent helping others with their tasks.

与其他年长者结对相比，年长者应该更频繁地与年长者结对。与请求其他晚辈的帮助相比，晚辈应该更多地请求晚辈的帮助。有专长的程序员应该花大量的配对时间与他们专业以外的程序员一起工作。目标是传播和交流知识，而不是集中知识。

Seniors should take care to pair with juniors more often than they pair with other seniors. Juniors should request the help of seniors more often than they request the help of other juniors. Programmers with specialties should spend significant amounts of their pairing time working with programmers outside of their specialty. The goal is to spread and exchange knowledge, not concentrate it.

为什么配对？

Why Pair?

我们配对以便我们表现得像一个团队。团队成员并不是彼此孤立地工作。相反，他们以秒为单位进行协作。当一个团队的成员倒下时，其他团队成员会填补该成员留下的洞并继续朝着目标前进。

We pair so that we behave like a team. The members of a team do not work in isolation from each other. Instead, they collaborate on a second-by-second basis. When a member of a team goes down, the other team members cover the hole left by that member and keep making progress towards the goal.

结对是迄今为止在团队成员之间共享知识并防止形成知识孤岛的最佳方式。这是确保团队中没有人不可或缺的最佳方法。

Pairing is the best way, by far, to share knowledge between team members and prevent knowledge silos from forming. It is the best way to make sure that nobody on the team is indispensable.

许多团队报告说配对可以减少错误并提高设计质量。在大多数情况下，这可能是正确的。对于任何给定的问题，通常最好有不止一组眼睛。事实上，许多团队已经用结对取代了代码审查。

Many teams have reported that pairing reduces errors and improves design quality. This is likely true in most cases. It is generally better to have more than one set of eyes on any given problem. Indeed, many teams have replaced code reviews with pairing.

结对作为代码审查

Pairing as Code Review

配对是代码审查的一种形式，但具有显着的优势。结对程序员在结对期间是共同作者。他们看到旧代码并对其进行审查是理所当然的，但目的是编写新代码。因此，审查不仅仅是静态检查，以确保应用团队的编码标准。相反，它是对代码当前状态的动态审查，着眼于代码在不久的将来需要处于的位置。

Pairing is a form of code review, but with a significant advantage. The pairing programmers are co-authors during the time they are pairing. They see older code and review it as a matter of course, but with the intention of authoring new code. Thus, the review is not simply a static check to ensure that the team’s coding standards are applied. Rather, it is a dynamic review of the current state of the code with an eye to where the code needs to be in the near future.

成本如何？

What about the Cost?

配对的成本很难衡量。最直接的成本是有两个人在处理一个问题。很明显，这并没有加倍解决问题的努力；但是，它确实可能要花一些钱。各种研究表明，直接成本可能约为 15%。换句话说，需要 115 名结对的程序员来完成 100 个人的相同工作（没有代码审查）。

It is hard to measure the cost of pairing. The most direct cost is that there are two people working on a single problem. It should be obvious that this does not double the effort to solve the problem; however, it does likely cost something. Various studies have indicated that the direct cost might be about 15%. In other words, it would require 115 pairing programmers to do the same work of 100 individuals (without code reviews).

天真的计算表明，一个团队在 50% 的时间里结对，其生产力下降不到 8%。另一方面，如果结对实践取代了代码审查，那么生产力可能根本不会降低。

A naive calculation would suggest that a team that pairs 50% of the time would suffer something less than 8% in productivity. On the other hand, if the practice of pairing replaces code reviews, then there is likely no reduction in productivity at all.

然后我们必须考虑交叉培训知识交流和密切协作的好处。这些好处不容易量化，但也可能很重要。

Then we must consider the benefits of the cross-training knowledge exchange and intense collaboration. These benefits are not easily quantifiable, but they are also likely significant.

我的经验和许多其他人的经验是，如果结对是非正式的并由程序员自行决定，则对整个团队都非常有益。

My experience and the experience of many others is that pairing, when done informally and at the programmers’ discretion, is quite beneficial to the whole team.

只有两个？

Just Two?

“配对”一词意味着只有两个程序员参与配对会话。虽然这通常是正确的，但这不是规则。有时，三个、四个或更多人会决定一起解决一个给定的问题。（同样，这是由程序员自行决定的。）这有时被称为“暴民编程”。5、6 _ _

The word “pair” implies that there are just two programmers involved in a pairing session. While this is typically true, it is not a rule. Sometimes three, four, or more will decide to work together on a given problem. (Again, this is at the programmers’ discretion.) This is sometimes known as “mob programming.”5,6

5 . https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mob_programming

5. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mob_programming

6 . https://mobprogramming.org/mob-programming-basics/

6. https://mobprogramming.org/mob-programming-basics/

管理

Management

程序员经常担心经理会不赞成结对，甚至可能会要求结对并停止浪费时间。我从没见过这个发生。在我编写代码的半个世纪里，我从未见过经理在如此低的级别上进行干预。一般来说，根据我的经验，经理们很高兴看到程序员一起协作和工作。它给人的印象是工作正在完成。

Programmers often fear that managers will frown upon pairing and might even demand that pairs break up and stop wasting time. I’ve never seen this happen. In the half-century that I’ve been writing code, I’ve never seen a manager interfere at such a low level. Generally, in my experience, managers are pleased to see programmers collaborating and working together. It creates the impression that work is being done.

但是，如果您是一名经理，并且因为担心结对效率低下而想要干预结对，那么请将您的恐惧搁置一旁，让程序员解决这个问题。毕竟，他们是专家。如果你是一名程序员，其经理告诉你停止结对，提醒经理你是专家，因此你，而不是经理，必须负责你的工作方式。

If, however, you are a manager who is tempted to interfere with pairing because you fear it is inefficient, then set your fears aside and let the programmers figure this out. They are, after all, the experts. And if you are a programmer whose manager has told you to stop pairing, remind that manager that you are the expert, and that therefore you, and not the manager, must be in charge of the way you work.

最后，永远、永远、永远不要请求配对许可。或测试。或者重构。或者……你是专家。你决定。

Finally, never, ever, ever, ask for permission to pair. Or test. Or refactor. Or… You are the expert. You decide.

结论

Conclusion

敏捷的技术实践是任何敏捷工作中最重要的组成部分。任何在没有技术实践的情况下采用敏捷实践的尝试都注定要失败。原因很简单，敏捷是一种在匆忙中制造大混乱的有效机制。如果没有保持高技术质量的技术实践，团队的生产力将迅速下降并开始无情的死亡螺旋。

The technical practices of Agile are the most essential ingredient of any Agile effort. Any attempt to employ Agile practices without the technical practices is doomed to fail. The reason for this is simply that Agile is an efficient mechanism for making a big mess in a big hurry. Without the technical practices to keep the technical quality high, the productivity of the team will quickly falter and begin an inexorable death spiral.

6.变得敏捷

6. Becoming Agile

当我第一次了解 XP 时，我想，“还有什么比这更容易的呢？只需遵循一些简单的纪律和实践。没什么。”

When I first learned about XP, I thought, “What could be easier? Just follow a few simple disciplines and practices. Nothing to it.”

然而，根据尝试并失败的组织的数量，要变得敏捷，变得敏捷一定非常非常困难。也许所有失败的原因是太多的组织认为敏捷不是什么东西。

However, based upon the number of organizations that try—and fail—to become Agile, becoming Agile must be very, very difficult. Perhaps the reason for all that failure is that so many organizations think Agile is something that it’s not.

敏捷价值观

Agile Values

很久以前，Kent Beck 就提出了敏捷的四个价值观。它们是勇气、沟通、反馈和简单。

Kent Beck named the four values of Agile long ago. They are courage, communication, feedback, and simplicity.

勇气

Courage

第一个价值是勇气——或者换句话说，是合理程度的冒险精神。敏捷团队的成员不会过于关注政治安全而牺牲质量和机会。他们意识到，长期管理软件项目的最佳方式是采取一定程度的进取心。

The first value is courage—or, in other words, a reasonable degree of risk-taking. The members of an Agile team are not so focused upon political safety that they sacrifice quality and opportunity. They realize that the best way to manage a software project over the long term is with a certain degree of aggression.

勇敢和鲁莽之间是有区别的。部署最小功能集需要勇气。保持高代码质量和保持高质量的纪律也需要勇气。但是，部署您不高度信任或具有不可持续设计的代码是鲁莽的。通过牺牲质量来遵守时间表是鲁莽的。

There is a difference between courage and recklessness. It requires courage to deploy a minimum feature set. It also requires courage to maintain high code quality and maintain high-quality disciplines. However, it is reckless to deploy code that you are not highly confident in or that has an unsustainable design. It is reckless to conform to a schedule by sacrificing quality.

坚信质量和纪律能提高速度是一种勇敢，因为它会不断受到有影响力但天真的匆忙者的挑战。

The belief that quality and discipline increase speed is a courageous belief because it will constantly be challenged by powerful but naive folks who are in a hurry.

沟通

Communication

我们重视跨渠道的直接和频繁的沟通。敏捷团队成员希望彼此交谈。程序员，客户，测试人员和管理人员希望彼此坐在一起并经常互动，而不仅仅是在会议中。不仅仅是通过电子邮件、聊天和备忘录。相反，他们重视面对面、非正式的人际对话。

We value direct and frequent communication that crosses channels. Agile team members want to talk with one another. The programmers, customers, testers, and managers want to sit near each other and interact with each other frequently, and not just in the context of meetings. Not just through emails, chat, and memos. Rather, they value face-to-face, informal, interpersonal conversation.

这就是团队凝聚的方式。正是在频繁互动的快速、混乱、非正式的风暴中，灯泡熄灭，洞察力获得。一个坐在一起并经常交流的团队可以创造奇迹。

This is how teams gel. It is within the rapid, chaotic, informal firestorm of frequent interaction that light bulbs go off and insight is gained. A team that sits together and communicates frequently can work miracles.

回馈

Feedback

我们研究过的敏捷学科实际上都旨在为做出重要决策的人提供快速反馈。计划游戏、重构、测试驱动开发、持续集成、小版本、集体所有权、整个团队等最大限度地提高反馈的频率和数量。它们使我们能够尽早确定何时出现问题并予以纠正。他们提供有关早期决策后果的大量教育。敏捷团队在反馈中茁壮成长。反馈是使团队如此有效地工作以及推动项目取得有益成果的原因。

The Agile disciplines we have studied are virtually all geared toward providing rapid feedback to the folks who make important decisions. Planning Game, Refactoring, Test Driven Development, Continuous Integration, Small Releases, Collective Ownership, Whole Team, etc. maximize the frequency and quantity of feedback. They allow us to determine when things are going wrong early enough to correct them. They provide massive education about the consequences of earlier decisions. Agile teams thrive on feedback. Feedback is what makes the team work so effectively and what drives a project to a beneficial outcome.

简单

Simplicity

敏捷的下一个价值是简单——换句话说，直接。人们常说，软件中的每个问题都可以通过添加另一层间接来解决。但勇气、沟通和反馈的价值在于确保将问题的数量减少到最低限度。因此，可以将间接性保持在最低限度。解决方案可以很简单。

The next Agile value is simplicity—in other words,being direct. It has often been said that every problem in software can be solved by adding another layer of indirection. But the values of courage, communication, and feedback are there to ensure that the number of problems is reduced to a minimum. Therefore, indirection can be kept to a minimum. Solutions can be simple.

这适用于软件，也适用于团队。被动攻击是间接的。当你意识到一个问题但默默地允许它传递给其他人时，你就是在间接参与。当你在明知后果很严重的情况下同意经理或客户的要求时，你就是间接的。

This applies to the software, but it also applies to the team. Passive aggression is indirection. When you recognize a problem but silently allow it to pass to someone else, you are engaging in indirection. When you accede to the demands of a manager or customer knowing that the consequences will be dire, you are being indirect.

简单就是直接——代码的直接，沟通和行为的直接。在代码中，一定量的间接是必要的。间接是我们减少相互依赖的复杂性的机制。在团队中，需要的间接性要少得多。大多数时候，您想尽可能直接。

Simplicity is directness—directness in the code, and directness in communication and behavior. In the code, a certain amount of indirection is necessary. Indirection is the mechanism by which we reduce the complexity of interdependence. On the team, far less indirection is necessary. Most of the time, you want to be as direct as possible.

保持代码简单。让团队更简单。

Keep the code simple. Keep the team simpler.

动物园

The Menagerie

大量的敏捷方法很容易让你感到困惑。我对你的建议是忽略动物园。最后，无论您选择哪种方法，您最终都会调整和调整流程以满足您自己的需要。因此，无论您是从 XP、Scrum 还是其他 5328 种敏捷方法中的任何一种开始，您都将在同一个地方结束。

It is easy to become confused by the vast numbers of Agile methods out there. My advice to you is to ignore the menagerie. In the end, regardless of which method you choose, you will wind up tuning and tweaking the process to fit your own needs. Thus, whether you begin with XP, Scrum, or any of the 5328 other Agile methods out there, you are going to wind up in the same place.

然而，我能给你的最强烈建议是采用完整的生命周期，包括，尤其是技术实践。太多的团队采用了外部业务环，并发现自己陷入了 Martin Fowler 标记为“松弛的 Scrum”的陷阱。1这种疾病的症状是随着项目的进行，从项目初期的高生产率缓慢下降到非常低的生产率。这种生产力损失的原因是代码本身的损坏和退化。

The strongest advice I can give you, however, is to adopt the full Circle of Life, including, and most especially, the technical practices. Far too many teams have adopted the outer business ring and have found themselves in the trap that Martin Fowler has labeled “Flaccid Scrum.”1 The symptoms of this disease are a slow decline from high productivity in the early days of a project to very low productivity as the project wears on. The reason for this loss of productivity is the corruption and degradation of the code itself.

1 . https://martinfowler.com/bliki/FlaccidScrum.html

1. https://martinfowler.com/bliki/FlaccidScrum.html

事实证明，敏捷的业务实践是制造非常大的混乱的高效方法。此外，如果您不注意正在构建的结构的清洁度，那么混乱会减慢您的速度。

It turns out that the business practices of Agile are a highly efficient way to make a very large mess. Furthermore, if you don’t take care of the cleanliness of the structure you are building, then the mess will slow you way down.

因此，选择其中一种方法或不选择任何方法。确保您处理生命周期中的所有学科。让团队同意。然后，开始。记住勇气、沟通、反馈和简单，并定期调整纪律和行为。不要征求许可。不要强调“做对了”。解决出现的问题，并继续推动您的项目取得最佳结果。

So, pick one of the methods or none of the methods. Ensure that you address all the disciplines in the Circle of Life. Get the team to agree. Then, begin. Remember courage, communication, feedback, and simplicity and regularly adjust the disciplines and behaviors. Don’t ask for permission. Don’t stress about “doing it right.” Just work through the issues as they arise and continue to drive your projects to the best possible outcome.

转型

Transformation

从非敏捷到敏捷的转变是价值观的转变。敏捷开发的价值包括人们之间无视障碍和命令结构的冒险精神、快速反馈、密集、高带宽的沟通。他们还专注于直线移动，而不是规划和协商景观。这些价值观与大型组织的价值观截然相反，后者在重视安全性、一致性、命令和控制以及计划执行的中层管理结构方面投入了大量资金。

The transition from non-Agile to Agile is a transition in values. The values of Agile development include risk-taking, rapid-feedback, intense, high-bandwidth communication between people that ignores barriers and command structures. They also focus on moving in straight and direct lines rather than mapping out and negotiating the landscape. These values are diametrically opposed to the values of large organizations who have invested heavily in middle-management structures that value safety, consistency, command-and-control, and plan execution.

是否有可能将这样的组织转变为敏捷？坦率地说，这不是我取得很大成功的事情，我也没有看到其他人取得多大成功。我已经看到付出了大量的努力和金钱，但我还没有看到很多组织真正实现了转型。价值结构差异太大，中层管理层无法接受。

Is it possible to transform such an organization to Agile? Frankly, this is not something I have had a lot of success with, nor have I seen much success from others. I have seen plenty of effort and money expended, but I have not seen many organizations that truly make the transition. The value structures are just too different for the middle-management layer to accept.

我所看到的是团队和个人的转变，因为团队和个人通常受到与敏捷一致的价值观的指导。

What I have seen is the transition of teams and individuals, because teams and individuals are often directed by values that are aligned with Agile.

具有讽刺意味的是，高管们也经常被敏捷的冒险、直接和交流价值观所驱动。这是他们尝试转变组织的原因之一。

Ironically, executives are also often driven by the risk-taking, direct, communicative values of Agile. This is one of the reasons they try to transition their organizations.

障碍是中间的管理层。雇用这些人是为了不冒险，避免直接，以最少的沟通来遵循和执行指挥链。这就是组织困境。组织的高层和底层重视敏捷思维，但中层反对它。我不知道我是否见过中间层进行更改。的确，他们怎么可能？他们的工作是反对这样的改变。

The barrier is the management layer in the middle. These folks were hired to not take risks, to avoid directness, to follow and enforce the chain of command with a minimum of communication. This is the organizational dilemma. The tops and bottoms of the organization value the Agile mindset, but the middle layer opposes it. I don’t know that I have ever seen that middle layer make the change. Indeed, how could they? Their job is to oppose such a change.

为了深入了解这一点，让我告诉你几个故事。

To drive this point home, let me tell you a few stories.

诡计

The Subterfuge

在我 2000 年参与的一次敏捷转型中，我们得到了高管和程序员的支持。有很多充满希望的热情。问题出在技术主管和架构师身上。这些人错误地推测他们的角色正在被削弱。

In one Agile transformation in which I participated back in 2000, we had the support of the executives and the programmers. There was a lot of hopeful enthusiasm. The problem was the technical leads and architects. These folks incorrectly surmised that their roles were being diminished.

架构师、技术主管、项目经理和许多其他人在敏捷团队中的角色是不同的，但他们并没有减少。不幸的是，这些人看不到这一点，这可能是我们的错。也许我们没有传达他们的角色对团队的价值，或者他们可能只是不愿意学习他们需要的新技能。

The roles of architects, technical leads, project managers, and many others are different in an Agile team, but they are not diminished. Unfortunately, these folks could not see this, and that may have been our fault. Perhaps we did not communicate how valuable their roles were to the team, or perhaps they were just uncomfortable learning the new skills they’d need.

无论如何，他们秘密会面并制定了破坏敏捷转型的计划。我不会详细介绍该计划。我只是说他们被抓住了，他们立即被解雇了。

In any event, they met in secret and devised plans to sabotage the Agile transition. I won’t go into the details of that plan. I’ll just say that they were caught at it, and they were immediately fired.

我想报告一下，敏捷转型随后进展迅速并取得了巨大成功。但我不能。

I’d like to report that the Agile Transition then proceeded apace and achieved great success. But I can’t.

小狮子

The Lion Cubs

我们在转型一家大得多的公司的一个部门方面取得了巨大成功。他们采用了 XP，多年来做出了如此出色的工作，以至于他们被写在了Computerworld中。事实上，所有这些成功导致了领导该过渡的工程副总裁的晋升。

We had great success transitioning one division of a much larger company. They adopted XP and did such great work over the years that they were written up in Computerworld. In fact, all that success led to the promotion of the VP of engineering who led that transition.

然后新的副总裁接任。就像一头新的雄狮接管了狮群，他开始杀死前任副总裁的所有后代。这包括敏捷。他停止了它，并让团队恢复到他们旧的、远不成功的过程。

Then the new VP took over. And like a new male lion taking over the pride, he proceeded to kill all the offspring of the previous VP. And that included Agile. He stopped it cold and reverted the team to their old, far less successful process.

这导致团队中的许多人到别处寻找工作——我相信这是新副总裁的意图。

This led many folks on the team to seek employment elsewhere—which, I believe, was the new VP’s intent.

哭泣

Weeping

最后一个故事是二手的。我不是来见证关键时刻的。当时我的员工向我报告了这件事。

This last story is second hand. I wasn’t there to witness the critical moment. It was reported to me by my employees at the time.

2003 年，我的公司参加了一家知名股票经纪公司的敏捷转型。一切进展顺利。我们培训了高管、中层管理人员和开发人员。他们一起做饭。一切都很顺利。

In 2003, my company participated in an Agile Transition at a well-known stock brokerage firm. All was proceeding well. We trained the executives, the middle managers, and the developers. They were cooking along. Everything was going great.

然后是最后的评估。高管、中层管理人员和开发人员都聚集在一个大礼堂里。他们的目标是评估敏捷转型的进展和成功。高管们问了一个问题，“最近怎么样？”

Then came the final assessment. The executives, middle managers, and developers all met in a big auditorium. Their goal was to assess the progress and success of the Agile Transition. The executives asked the question, “How’s it going?”

来自各方参与者的回答是：“进行得很好。”

The answer came from the various participants: “It’s going very well.”

房间里静了片刻，突然被房间后面有人哭泣的声音打断了。就在那时，情感支持崩溃了，房间里的积极情绪也崩溃了。“这太难了。” 人们听到说。“我们不能再这样下去了。”

Then there was a moment of silence in the room, which was suddenly punctuated by the sound of someone in the back of the room, weeping. And that’s when the emotional supports crumbled, and the positive mood in the room collapsed. “This is just too hard.” People were heard to say. “We just can’t keep this up.”

因此，高管们扼杀了转型。

And so, the executives killed the transition.

道德

Moral

我想所有这些故事的寓意是“期待一些奇怪的事情发生。”

I suppose the moral of all these stories is “Expect something weird to happen.”

作假

Faking It

敏捷团队可以存在于一个拥有强大的中层管理层反对敏捷的组织中吗？我曾见过这种情况。一些软件开发团队悄悄地使用敏捷价值观来推动他们的开发，同时也遵守由中层管理人员。只要中层管理人员对他们的程序和标准得到遵守感到满意，他们就可以让开发团队自行其是。

Can Agile teams exist in an organization with a strong middle-management layer that opposes Agile? I have seen this happen upon occasion. Some software development teams quietly use Agile values to drive their development, while also conforming to the rigors imposed upon them by middle management. So long as middle management is satisfied that their procedures and standards are being followed, they may leave the development teams to their own devices.

这就是 Booch 和 Parnas 所说的“假装”。2团队在幕后进行敏捷，同时提供满足中层管理层的一切。这些团队没有与中层管理人员进行徒劳的战斗，而是在敏捷之上加了一层，使敏捷看起来安全且符合中层管理人员的要求。

This is what Booch and Parnas called “faking it.”2 The team does Agile under the covers, while providing everything that satisfies the middle-management layer. Rather than fighting a futile battle with the middle managers, these teams put a layer on top of Agile that makes Agile look safe and conformant to the middle managers.

2 . Booch, G. 1994。面向对象的分析和设计与应用程序，第 2 版。马萨诸塞州雷丁：Addison-Wesley，p. 233-34。

2. Booch, G. 1994. Object-Oriented Analysis and Design with Applications, 2nd ed. Reading, MA: Addison-Wesley, p. 233–34.

例如，中层管理人员可能希望在项目的早期阶段生成一份分析文档。敏捷团队通过使用所有正常的敏捷规程编写系统的大部分早期代码来提供此文档，然后通过安排一系列文档故事来生成分析文档。

For example, the middle managers may want an analysis document produced in the early phases of the project. The Agile team provides this document by writing much of the early code of the system using all the normal Agile disciplines, and then produces the analysis document by scheduling a sequence of documentation stories.

这是有道理的，因为前几次编码迭代主要集中在需求分析上。事实上，这种分析是通过实际编写代码来完成的，这并不是中层管理人员需要知道的。他们也不应该关心。

This makes sense because the first few coding iterations are heavily focused on requirements analysis. The fact that this analysis is being done by actually writing code is not something that the middle managers need to know. Nor should they care.

不幸的是，我见过功能失调的组织，当中层管理人员闻到团队在“伪装”时，他们会采取诡计并迅速采取行动消除敏捷纪律。这是一个深深的耻辱，因为这些团队实际上正在为中层管理人员提供他们需要的东西。

Unfortunately, I have seen organizations who are so dysfunctional that when middle managers smell that a team is “faking it,” they assume subterfuge and quickly move to expunge the Agile disciplines. This is a deep shame because those teams were actually giving the middle managers what they needed.

在较小的组织中取得成功

Success in Smaller Organizations

我见过一些中型组织采用敏捷。他们的中层管理人员很薄，由层层晋升的人组成，但仍然保持着直接、敢于冒险的心态。

I have seen some medium-sized organizations adopt Agile. They had thin middle-management layers composed of folks who came up through the ranks and still retained the direct, risk-taking mindset.

小型组织完全过渡到敏捷的情况并不少见。他们没有中层管理人员，高管和开发人员的价值观高度一致。

It is not uncommon to see small organizations transition completely to Agile. They have no middle management, and the values of the executives and developers are strongly aligned.

个人成功与迁移

Individual Success and Migration

最后，有时只有组织内的某些人采用敏捷价值观。进行这种转变的个人在没有这种转变的组织或团队中表现不佳。价值观的差异通常会导致某种分离。在最好的情况下，进行过渡的个人将加入新的敏捷团队，设法躲避中层管理人员。如果那不可能，他们可能会在与他们价值观相同的公司寻求（并找到）工作。

Finally, sometimes only certain individuals within an organization adopt the Agile values. Individuals who make this transition do not fare well within organizations or teams who do not. The difference in values generally leads to a separation of some kind. In the best case, the individuals who make the transition will join to form new Agile teams that manage to hide from middle management. If that’s not possible, they will likely seek (and find) employment at a company that shares their values.

事实上，在过去的二十年中，我们已经看到该行业正在发生这种价值观的转变。拥抱敏捷价值观的新公司已经成立，希望以敏捷方式工作的程序员涌向这些公司。

Indeed, over the last twenty years, we have seen this migration of values taking place in the industry. New companies that embrace the Agile values have been formed, and programmers who desire to work in an Agile manner flock to those companies.

创建敏捷组织

Creating Agile Organizations

能否创建允许敏捷团队在其中繁荣发展的大型组织？当然！但是，请注意，这个词是创建的，而不是转换的。

Can large organizations be created that allow Agile teams to prosper within them? Certainly! However, note that the word is created not transformed.

当 IBM 决定制造 PC 时，公司的高管意识到组织的价值观不允许进行所需的快速创新和冒险。因此，他们创建了一个具有不同价值结构的组织。3个

When IBM decided to build the PC, the company’s executives realized that the values of the organization would not allow the kind of quick innovation and risk-taking that would be required. So, they created an organization with a different value structure.3

3 . IBM PC 的诞生。在https://www.ibm.com/ibm/history/exhibits/pc25/pc25_birth.html访问。

3. The birth of the IBM PC. Accessed at https://www.ibm.com/ibm/history/exhibits/pc25/pc25_birth.html.

我们在软件世界中看到过这种情况吗？较早的大型组织是否为了采用敏捷而创建了较小的软件组织？我已经看到了这方面的暗示，但我想不起任何明显的例子。我们当然已经看到许多初创公司采用敏捷。我们也看到很多敏捷咨询公司被大型非敏捷公司使用希望更快、更可靠地完成某些软件项目的公司。

Have we seen this happen in the software world? Have older, large organizations created smaller software organizations for the purpose of adopting Agile? I’ve seen hints of this, but I cannot bring to mind any overt examples. We have certainly seen many startups adopt Agile. We have also seen many Agile consulting companies being used by large non-Agile companies that want to get certain software projects done more quickly and reliably.

这是我的预测。我们最终会看到更大的公司创建使用敏捷开发软件的新部门。我们还将看到敏捷咨询公司越来越多地被无法改造其现有开发人员的大型组织所采用。

That’s my prediction. We will eventually see larger companies create new divisions that use Agile for their software development. We will also see Agile consulting companies used more and more by larger organizations that have been unable to transform their existing development staff.

辅导

Coaching

敏捷团队需要教练吗？最简洁的答案是不。” 较长的答案是“有时”。

Does an Agile team need a coach? The short answer is “No.” The longer answer is “Sometimes.”

首先，我们需要区分敏捷培训师和敏捷教练。敏捷培训师教导团队如何以敏捷方式行事。他们通常是从公司外部聘请的，或者是团队外部的内部培训师。他们的目标是灌输敏捷价值观并教授敏捷学科。他们的任期应该很短。每个由十几名开发人员组成的团队只需要接受不超过一到两周的培训。他们需要学习的所有其他内容，无论敏捷培训师说什么或做什么，他们都会自己学习。

First, we need to differentiate between Agile trainers and Agile coaches. An Agile trainer teaches a team how to conduct themselves in an Agile way. They are often hired from outside the company or are internal trainers from outside the team. Their goal is to inculcate the Agile values and teach the Agile disciplines. Their tenure should be short. Each team of a dozen or so developers should require no more than one or two weeks of training. Everything else they need to learn they’re going to learn by themselves no matter what the Agile trainer says or does.

在球队转型初期，教练员可能会临时担任教练的角色，但这是暂时的情况。该角色应尽快从团队内部填补。

Early in the transition of a team, a trainer may temporarily fill the role of the coach, but this is a temporary situation. That role should be filled from within the team as soon as possible.

一般来说，敏捷教练不是培训师。他们是团队的成员，其职责是在团队中捍卫流程。在开发的热潮中，开发人员可能会受到诱惑而放弃流程。也许他们无意中停止了配对、停止了重构，或者忽略了持续构建中的失败。看到这一点并向球队指出是教练的工作。教练作为球队的良心，时时提醒球队他们对自己的承诺，以及他们同意持有的价值观。

In general, Agile coaches are not trainers. They are members of the team whose role is to defend the process within the team. In the heat of development, developers may be tempted to go off process. Perhaps they inadvertently stop pairing, stop refactoring, or ignore failures in the continuous build. It is the coach’s job to see this and point it out to the team. The coach acts as the team’s conscience, always reminding the team of the promises they made to themselves and the values they agreed to hold.

该角色通常根据需要根据非正式时间表从一名团队成员轮换到另一名团队成员。一个成熟的团队，稳扎稳打，不需要教练。另一方面，处于某种压力下的团队——无论是日程安排、业务还是人际关系——可能会决定请某人临时填补该职位。

This role typically rotates from one team member to the next on an informal schedule and based on need. A mature team working steadily along does not require a coach. On the other hand, a team under some kind of stress—whether it be schedule, business, or interpersonal—may decide to ask someone to fill the role temporarily.

教练不是经理。教练不负责预算或日程安排。教练不指挥球队，也不向管理层代表球队的利益。教练不是客户和开发人员之间的联络人。教练的角色完全是团队内部的。经理和客户都不知道教练是谁，甚至不知道目前是否有教练。

The coach is not a manager. The coach is not responsible for budget or schedule. The coach does not direct the team nor does she represent the team’s interests to management. The coach is not the liaison between the customers and the developers. The role of the coach is strictly internal to the team. Neither the managers nor the customers know who the coach is, nor even whether there currently is a coach.

Scrum 大师

Scrum Masters

在 Scrum 中，教练被称为Scrum Master。这个术语的发明，以及随之而来的一系列事件，是敏捷社区发生的最好和最坏的事情之一。认证项目吸引了大量的项目经理。这种涌入在早期增加了敏捷的流行，但最终导致教练的角色与项目经理的角色混为一谈。

In Scrum, the coach is called a Scrum Master. The invention of this term, and the sequence of events that followed it, were among the best and worst things that happened to the Agile community. The certification programs attracted large numbers of project managers. This influx increased the popularity of Agile in the early days but eventually led to the role of the coach to be conflated with the role of the project manager.

如今，我们经常看到 Scrum Master 根本不是教练，而只是项目经理，他们在做项目经理一直做的事情。不幸的是，头衔和认证往往会给他们对敏捷团队带来不当影响。

Nowadays, it is all too frequent that we see Scrum Masters who are not coaches at all but are simply project managers doing what project managers always did. Unfortunately, the title and certification tend to give them undue influence over the Agile team.

认证

Certification

现有的敏捷认证完全是个笑话，完全是荒谬的。不要认真对待认证。伴随认证计划的培训通常是值得的；但是，培训不应针对特定角色，而应针对团队中的每个人。

The Agile certifications that exist are a complete joke and an utter absurdity. Do not take the certifications seriously. The training that accompanies the certification programs is often worthwhile; however, that training should not be focused on a particular role, it should be for everyone on the team.

例如，某人被“认证”为 Scrum Master 的事实是毫无价值的认证。除了此人支付了费用并可能参加了为期两天的课程之外，认证机构不提供任何保证。认证者特别不保证新成立的 Scrum Master 会作为教练做好工作。认证的荒谬含义是“认证 Scrum Master”有一些特别之处，这当然与教练的概念背道而驰。敏捷教练没有经过专门培训成为敏捷教练。

For example, the fact that someone is “certified” a Scrum Master is a worthless certification. The certifiers are not guaranteeing anything other than that the person paid the fee for, and possibly attended, a two-day course. The certifiers are specifically not guaranteeing that the newly minted Scrum Master will do a good job as a coach. The absurd implication of the certification is that there is something special about a “Certified Scrum Master,” which of course flies in the face of the notion of a coach. An Agile coach is not specially trained to be an Agile coach.

同样，伴随这些认证的培训计划通常没有任何问题。但是，只培养一个特殊的人是愚蠢的。敏捷团队的每个成员都需要了解敏捷的价值和技术。因此，如果培训了团队中的一名成员，则应培训团队的所有成员。

Again, there’s often nothing wrong with the training programs that go along with these certifications. However, it is foolish to train just one special person. Every member of an Agile team needs to understand the values and techniques of Agile. Therefore, if one member of the team is trained, all members of the team should be trained.

真实认证

Real Certification

真正的敏捷认证项目应该是什么样子的？这将是一个为期一个学期的课程，包括敏捷培训和小型敏捷项目的监督开发。该课程将被评分，学生们将保持高标准。认证者将保证学生理解敏捷价值观并表现出执行敏捷学科的熟练程度。

What would a real Agile certification program look like? It would be a semester-long course, complete with Agile training and the supervised development of a small Agile project. The course would be graded and the students held to a high bar. The certifier would guarantee that the students understood Agile values and showed proficiency in executing Agile disciplines.

大规模敏捷

Agile in the Large

敏捷运动始于 80 年代后期。它很快被认为是组织 4 到 12 名软件开发人员的小团队的一种方式。这些数字是软的，很少被明确表达，但每个人都明白敏捷（或我们在 2001 年之前的任何称呼）不适合拥有数千名开发人员的庞大团队。那不是我们要解决的问题。

The Agile movement began in the late ’80s. It was quickly recognized as a means for organizing a small team of between 4 and 12 software developers. Those numbers are soft and were seldom articulated, but everyone understood that Agile (or whatever we called it before 2001) was not appropriate for a massive team of thousands of developers. That was not the problem we were trying to solve.

然而，几乎是立刻，这个问题就被提出来了。大团队呢？大体上的敏捷怎么样？

Nevertheless, almost immediately, the question was raised. What about big teams? What about Agile in the large?

多年来，许多人都试图回答这个问题。早期，Scrum 的作者提出了所谓的“Scrum-of-Scrums”技术。后来，我们开始看到某些品牌方法，如 SAFe 4和 LeSS。5关于这个主题，后来写了几本书。

Over the years, many folks have tried to answer that question. Early on, the authors of Scrum proposed the so-called “Scrum-of-Scrums” technique. Later, we started to see certain branded approaches like SAFe4 and LeSS.5 Several books have since been written on the topic.

4 . https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scaled_agile_framework

4. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scaled_agile_framework

5 . https://less.works/

5. https://less.works/
