The problem here is that we are offering a solution before agreeing on the problem. People will not change the way they work if they do not see the value.

与其推动 TDD，也许我们可以开始就减少测试整个系统所需时间的价值达成一致。今天需要多长时间？两个小时？两天？两周？有多少人参与其中？如果我们可以将它减少到 20 分钟呢？2分钟？甚至会2秒？如果我们只需按一下按钮就可以随时做到这一点呢？这会给我们带来良好的投资回报吗？那会让我们的生活更轻松吗？我们能够更快地发布可靠的软件吗？

Instead of pushing TDD, maybe we could start agreeing on the value of reducing the time it takes to test our entire system. How long does it take today? Two hours? Two days? Two weeks? How many people are involved? What if we could reduce it to 20 minutes? Two minutes? Maybe even 2 seconds? And what if we could do that at any time just by pressing a button? Would that give us a good return on investment? Would that make our lives easier? Would we be able to release reliable software faster?

如果我们同意答案是肯定的，那么我们就可以开始讨论可以帮助我们实现这一目标的做法。TDD 将是这里的自然选择。对于那些不太热衷于 TDD 的人，我们应该问问他们更喜欢什么实践。他们可以建议哪些实践可以根据商定的目标带来相同或更高的价值？

If we agree that the answer is yes, then we can start talking about practices which could help us achieve that. TDD would be a natural choice here. For those who are not so keen on TDD, we should ask what practice they would prefer. What practice can they suggest that could bring the same or higher value according to the agreed-upon goals?

在讨论实践时，首先就要实现的目标达成一致至关重要。唯一不应该接受的是在没有提供更好的替代方案的情况下拒绝一种做法。

Agreeing first on the goals to be achieved is essential when discussing practices. The only thing that should not be acceptable is to reject a practice without providing a better alternative.

讨论实践

Discussing Practices

围绕实践的讨论应该在合适的级别和合适的人中进行。如果我们想采用改善业务和技术之间协作的实践，业务和技术人员应该参与讨论。如果开发人员正在讨论能够使他们以更好的方式构建系统的实践，那么就没有理由让业务人员参与进来。仅当对项目的成本或持续时间产生重大影响时，企业才应参与。

The discussion around practices should be done at the right level and with the right people. If we want to adopt practices that improve the collaboration between business and technology, people from business and technology should be involved in the discussion. If developers are discussing practices that would enable them to build systems in a better way, there is no reason to involve businesspeople. Business should only be involved when there is a significant impact in the cost or duration of the project.

将整个单体系统重新架构为微服务与进行 TDD 是有区别的。前者对项目的成本和工期有非常重大的影响；后者不会，只要开发人员对这项技术感到满意即可。开发人员是否自动化他们的测试不应该与业务相关。自动化测试是在生产代码之前还是之后编写的，应该更不相关。企业应该关心的是，从商业创意到生产软件的交付周期正在逐渐缩短。减少花在返工（错误、测试、部署和生产监控等手动流程）上的金钱和时间也是开发团队应该解决的业务问题。降低成本试验也是一个商业问题。当软件不是模块化且易于测试时，试验成本会很高。业务和开发人员应该就业务价值而不是技术实践进行对话。

There is a difference between re-architecting a whole monolith system into microservices and doing TDD. The former has a very significant impact on the cost and duration of the project; the latter doesn’t, as long as developers are comfortable with the technique. Whether or not developers automate their tests should not be relevant to the business. It should be even less relevant whether the automated tests are written before or after the production code. What business should care about is that the lead time from business ideas to software in production is gradually reduced. Reducing the amount of money and time spent on rework (bugs, manual processes like testing, deployment, and production monitoring) is also a business concern that should be addressed by the development teams. Reducing the cost of experimenting is also a business concern. Experimenting becomes very costly when the software is not modular and easily testable. Business and developers should have conversations about business value, not technical practices.

开发人员不应为编写测试请求授权。他们不应该有单独的单元测试或重构任务。他们不应该有单独的任务来准备好制作专题片。这些技术活动应该被考虑到任何功能的开发中。它们不是可选的。经理和开发人员应该只讨论将交付什么以及何时交付，而不是如何交付。每次开发人员自愿详细说明他们的工作方式时，他们都是在邀请经理对他们进行微观管理。

Developers should not ask authorization for writing tests. They should not have separate tasks for unit tests or refactoring. They should not have separate tasks for making a feature production ready. These technical activities should be factored into the development of any feature. They are not optional. Managers and developers should only discuss what is going to be delivered and when, not how. Every time developers volunteer details of how they work, they are inviting managers to micromanage them.

我们是说开发人员应该隐藏他们的工作方式吗？一点都不。开发人员应该能够向感兴趣的任何人清楚地描述他们的工作方式以及以这种方式工作的优势。开发人员不应该做的是让其他人决定他们的工作方式。开发人员和企业之间的对话应该是关于为什么、什么和何时——而不是如何。

Are we saying that developers should hide how they work? No, not at all. Developers should be able to clearly describe how they work and the advantages of working that way to whomever is interested. What developers should not do is to let other people decide how they work. Conversations between developers and business should be about why, what, and when—not how.

手艺对个人的影响

Craftsmanship Impact on Individuals

手艺对个人有着深远的影响。经常看到人们将个人生活与职业生活分开。诸如“我离开办公室后不想谈论工作”或“我对生活有不同的兴趣”这样的短语的表达方式使工作看起来像是一件苦差事、一件坏事，或者你做的事情是因为你必须，不是因为你想。将我们的生命分成多个生命的问题在于，它们总是处于冲突之中。总有一种感觉，无论我们选择哪种生活，我们都必须为了另一个生命而牺牲一个生命。

Craftsmanship has a profound impact on individuals. It is common to see people separating their personal lives from their professional lives. Phrases like “I do not want to talk about work after I leave the office,” or “I have different interests in life” are said in a way that makes work look like a chore, a bad thing, or a thing you do because you have to, not because you want to. The problem of dividing our lives into multiple lives is that they are constantly in conflict. There is always that feeling that we must sacrifice one life for the sake of the other, regardless of which life we pick.

工匠精神推动软件开发成为一种职业。有一份工作和有一份职业是有区别的。工作是我们所做的事情，但它不是我们的一部分。另一方面，职业是我们的一部分。当被问及“你是做什么的？”时，有工作的人会通常会说“我在X 公司工作”或“我是一名软件开发人员”。但是有职业的人一般会说，“我是软件开发人员”。职业是我们投资的东西。这是我们想要做得更好的东西。我们希望获得更多技能，并拥有一份持久而充实的职业。

Craftsmanship promotes software development as a profession. There is a difference between having a job and having a profession. A job is a thing we do but it is not part of who we are. A profession, on the other hand, is part of who we are. When asked, “What do you do?”, a person with a job would normally say something like “I work for company X,” or “I work as a software developer.” But a person with a profession would generally say, “I am a software developer.” A profession is something we invest in. It’s something we want to get better at. We want to gain more skills and have a long-lasting and fulfilling career.

这并不意味着我们不会花时间与家人在一起，或者我们在生活中不会有其他兴趣。相反，它意味着我们会找到一种方法来平衡我们所有的承诺和利益，这样我们就可以过上单身、平衡和幸福的生活。有时我们想要更多地关注我们的家庭、我们的职业或我们可能拥有的爱好。那完全没问题。我们在不同的时间有不同的需求。但是当我们有职业时，上班不应该是一件苦差事。这只是我们所做的另一件事，它给我们带来快乐并使我们作为个人感到满足。职业赋予我们生命意义。

That does not mean we would not spend time with our families or that we would not have other interests in life. Rather, it means that we would find a way to balance all our commitments and interests such that we can live a single, well-balanced, and happy life. There are times when we want to give more attention to our family, our profession, or a hobby we might have. And that is totally OK. We have different needs at different times. But going to work should not be a chore when we have a profession. It is just another thing we do that gives us pleasure and fulfills us as individuals. A profession gives meaning to our lives.

工艺对我们行业的影响

Craftsmanship Impact on Our Industry

自 2008 年以来，越来越多的软件工艺社区和会议在世界各地组织起来，吸引了数以万计的开发人员。敏捷社区强调软件项目的人员和过程方面，而工艺社区更关注技术方面。他们一直是向世界各地的许多开发人员和公司推广 XP 和许多其他技术实践的关键。正是通过软件工艺社区，许多开发人员正在学习 TDD、持续集成、结对编程、简单设计、SOLID 原则、清洁代码和重构。他们还在学习如何使用微服务构建系统、如何自动化部署管道以及如何将系统迁移到云端。他们正在学习不同的编程语言和范式。他们正在学习新技术和不同的方法来测试和维护他们的应用程序。Craftsmanship 社区的开发人员正在创建安全友好的空间，在那里他们可以结识志同道合的人并谈论他们的职业。

Since 2008, a growing number of Software Craftsmanship communities and conferences are being organized all over the world, attracting tens of thousands of developers. While Agile communities have an emphasis on the people and process side of software projects, the Craftsmanship communities focus more on the technical side. They have been key in promoting XP, and many other technical practices to many developers and companies around the world. It is through Software Craftsmanship communities that many developers are learning TDD, Continuous Integration, Pair Programming, Simple Design, SOLID principles, Clean Code, and Refactoring. They are also learning how to architect systems using microservices, how to automate their deployment pipelines, and how to migrate their systems to the cloud. They are learning different programming languages and paradigms. They are learning new technologies and different ways to test and maintain their applications. Developers in the Craftsmanship community are creating safe and friendly spaces where they can meet like-minded people and talk about their profession.

软件工艺社区极具包容性。从一开始，Software Craftsmanship 的主要目标之一就是将来自不同背景的软件开发人员聚集在一起，以便他们可以相互学习并提高专业软件开发的标准。工艺社区与技术无关，所有开发人员，无论其经验水平如何，都欢迎参加会议。社区致力于培养下一代专业人士，举办各种活动，让加入我们行业的人们可以学习构建精心设计的软件的基本实践。

Software Craftsmanship communities are extremely inclusive. From the very beginning, one of the main goals of Software Craftsmanship was to bring together software developers from all backgrounds so that they could learn from each other and raise the bar of professional software development. Craftsmanship communities are technology agnostic, and all developers, regardless of their level of experience, are welcome in the meetings. The community is committed to preparing the next generation of professionals, creating various events where people joining our industry can learn essential practices to build well-crafted software.

工艺对公司的影响

Craftsmanship Impact on Companies

软件工艺的采用正在增长。许多采用敏捷的公司现在都在寻找工艺来提高他们的工程能力。然而，软件工艺并没有敏捷所具有的商业吸引力。XP 仍然是许多管理人员不了解或兴奋的东西。经理们了解 Scrum、迭代、演示、回顾、协作和快速反馈循环。但是他们对与编程相关的技术并不那么感兴趣。对于他们中的大多数人来说，XP 是关于编程的，而不是关于敏捷软件开发的。

Software Craftsmanship adoption is growing. Many companies that have adopted Agile are now looking at Craftsmanship to improve their engineering capabilities. However, Software Craftsmanship does not have the same business appeal that Agile has. XP is still something that many managers do not understand or are excited about. Managers understand Scrum, iterations, demos, retrospectives, collaboration, and a fast feedback loop. But they are not so interested in programming-related techniques. For most of them, XP is about programming, not about Agile software development.

与 2000 年代初具有强大技术背景的敏捷教练不同，如今的大多数敏捷教练无法教授 XP 实践或与业务人员谈论工程。他们不能与开发人员坐下来并与他们结对编程。他们不能谈论简单设计或帮助配置持续集成管道。他们不能帮助开发人员重构他们的遗留代码。他们既不能讨论测试策略，也不能讨论如何在生产中维护多个服务。他们无法向业务人员解释某些技术实践的真正优势，更不用说创建或建议技术策略了。

Differently from Agile coaches in the early 2000s, who had a strong technical background, most Agile coaches today cannot teach XP practices or talk to businesspeople about engineering. They cannot sit down with developers and Pair Program with them. They cannot talk about Simple Design or help with the configuration of Continuous Integration pipelines. They cannot help developers to refactor their legacy code. They can discuss neither testing strategies nor how to maintain multiple services in production. They cannot explain to businesspeople the real advantages of certain technical practices, let alone create or advise on a technical strategy.

但公司需要可靠的系统——使他们能够根据业务需求快速做出反应的系统。公司还需要有积极性和能力的技术团队，他们可以出色地创建和维护他们的系统。这些都是软件工艺擅长的领域。

But companies need reliable systems—systems that enable them to react quickly according to their business needs. Companies also need motivated and capable technical teams that can do a great job creating and maintaining their systems. And those are areas where Software Craftsmanship excels.

Software Craftsmanship 思维模式启发了许多开发人员。它给了他们使命感、自豪感和做好事情的天生意愿。与一般人一样，大多数开发人员都热衷于学习和做好事情——他们只需要支持和一个可以让他们茁壮成长的环境。拥抱工艺的公司经常看到内部实践社区蓬勃发展。开发人员组织内部会议，在那里他们一起编码、实践 TDD 并提高他们的软件设计技能。他们开始对学习新技术和使他们工作的系统现代化感兴趣。他们讨论了改进代码库和消除技术欠账的更好方法。Software Craftsmanship 促进学习文化，使公司更具创新性和响应能力。

The Software Craftsmanship mindset is an inspiration for many developers. It gives them a sense of purpose, a sense of pride, and an innate willingness to do things well. Most developers, as people in general, are keen to learn and do things well—they just need support and an environment where they can thrive. Companies embracing Craftsmanship often see internal communities of practice flourish. Developers organize internal sessions where they code together, practice TDD, and improve their software design skills. They become interested in learning new technologies and modernizing the systems they work on. They discuss better ways to improve the codebase and eliminate technical debit. Software Craftsmanship promotes a culture of learning, making companies more innovative and responsive.

工艺和敏捷

Craftsmanship and Agile

一些引发软件工艺运动的触发因素与许多开发人员对敏捷所采取的方向感到沮丧有关。正因为如此，有些人认为工匠精神和敏捷是相互矛盾的。曾参与敏捷运动的工匠运动中的人们批评敏捷过度关注过程而缺乏对工程的关注。敏捷运动中的人们批评 Craftsmanship 关注范围狭窄或缺乏对实际业务和人员问题的关注。

Some of the triggers for the creation of the Software Craftsmanship movement were related to the frustration that many developers felt with the direction Agile had taken. Because of that, some people felt that Craftsmanship and Agile were at odds with each other. People in the Craftsmanship movement who had also been part of the Agile movement criticized Agile for their excessive focus on process and lack of focus on engineering. People in the Agile movement criticized Craftsmanship for its narrow focus or lack of focus on real business and people problems.

尽管双方都有一些合理的担忧，但大多数分歧更多地与部落主义有关，而不是实际的根本性意见分歧。从本质上讲，这两个运动都想实现非常相似的目标。他们都希望客户满意，他们都希望密切合作，他们都重视简短的反馈循环。两者都希望提供高质量、有价值的工作，并且都希望具有专业精神。为了实现业务敏捷性，公司不仅需要协作和迭代过程，还需要良好的工程技能。将敏捷与工艺相结合是实现这一目标的完美方式。

Although there were some valid concerns coming from both sides, most of the disagreements were more related to tribalism than actual fundamental divergence of opinions. Essentially, both movements want to achieve very similar things. They both want customer satisfaction, they both desire close collaboration, and they both value short feedback loops. Both want to deliver high-quality, valuable work, and both want professionalism. In order to achieve business agility, companies need not only collaborative and iterative processes, but also good engineering skills. Combining Agile and Craftsmanship is the perfect way to achieve that.

结论

Conclusion

在 2001 年的 Snowbird 会议上，Kent Beck 说敏捷是关于弥合开发与业务之间鸿沟的。不幸的是，随着项目经理涌入敏捷社区，最初创建敏捷社区的开发人员感到被剥夺了权利并被低估了。因此，他们离开了工匠运动。因此，古老的不信任仍在继续。

At the Snowbird meeting in 2001, Kent Beck said that Agile was about the healing of the divide between development and business. Unfortunately, as the project managers flooded into the Agile community, the developers—who had created the Agile community in the first place—felt dispossessed and undervalued. So, they left to form the Craftsmanship movement. Thus, the ancient distrust continues.

然而，敏捷的价值观和工艺的价值观是高度一致的。这两个运动不应该分开。人们希望，有一天，他们会再次聚在一起。

And yet the values of Agile and the values of Craftsmanship are strongly aligned. These two movements should not be separate. One hopes that, one day, they’ll come together again.

八、结论

8. Conclusion

就是这样了。这些是我的记忆，我的观点，以及我对敏捷的咆哮和狂言。我希望你喜欢它们，甚至可能学到一两件事。

So, that’s it. Those are my memories, my opinions, and my rantings and ravings about Agile. I hope you enjoyed them and maybe even learned a thing or two.

敏捷可能是我们所见过的关于软件过程和方法的所有革命中最重要、最持久的。这种意义和坚持证明了 2001 年 2 月前往犹他州斯诺伯德的 17 个人开始了一个从非常长的山坡上滚下的雪球。骑着那个雪球，看着它越来越大，速度越来越快，看着它撞上巨石和树木，这对我来说是一种乐趣。

Agile may be the most significant, and most persistent, of all the revolutions we have seen about software processes and methods. That significance and persistence are evidence that those 17 folks who went to Snowbird, Utah, during February 2001 started a snowball rolling down a very long hill. Riding that snowball, watching it gather size and speed, and seeing it hit boulders and trees has been a load of fun for me.

我写这本书是因为我认为是时候有人站起来大声疾呼敏捷是什么以及敏捷仍然应该是什么了。我认为是时候记住基础知识了。

I wrote this book because I thought it was time for someone to stand up and yell about what Agile was and what Agile still ought to be. I thought it was time to remember the basics.

这些基础知识过去、现在和将来都是罗恩·杰弗里斯 (Ron Jeffries) 生活圈中的纪律。这些基础知识是 Kent Beck解释的极限编程的价值观、原则和纪律。1这些基础知识是 Martin Fowler 的重构中的动机、技术和原则。2这些基础知识由 Booch、DeMarco、Yourdon、Constantine、Page-Jones 和 Lister 阐述。

Those basics were, are, and will be the disciplines in Ron Jeffries’ Circle of Life. Those basics are the values, principles, and disciplines of Kent Beck’s Extreme Programming Explained.1 Those basics are the motivations, techniques, and disciplines in Martin Fowler’s Refactoring.2 Those basics were stated by Booch, DeMarco, Yourdon, Constantine, Page-Jones, and Lister.

1 . Beck, K. 2000。极限编程解释：拥抱变化。马萨诸塞州波士顿：Addison-Wesley。

1. Beck, K. 2000. Extreme Programming Explained: Embrace Change. Boston, MA: Addison-Wesley.

2 . Fowler, M. 2019。重构：改进现有代码的设计，第 2 版。马萨诸塞州波士顿：Addison-Wesley。

2. Fowler, M. 2019. Refactoring: Improving the Design of Existing Code, 2nd ed. Boston, MA: Addison-Wesley.

他们被 Dijkstra、Dahl 和 Hoare 喊了出来。你从 Knuth、Meyer、Jacobsen 和 Rumbaugh 那里听说过他们。他们得到了 Coplien、Gamma、Helm、Vlissides 和 Johnson 的响应。如果你仔细听，你会听到 Thompson、Ritchie、Kernighan 和 Plauger 的耳语。并且——在某个地方——丘奇、冯·诺依曼和图灵在那些回声和耳语经过时都笑了。

They were shouted by Dijkstra, Dahl, and Hoare. You heard them from Knuth, Meyer, Jacobsen, and Rumbaugh. And they were echoed by Coplien, Gamma, Helm, Vlissides, and Johnson. If you listened carefully, you’d have heard them whispered by Thompson, Ritchie, Kernighan, and Plauger. And—somewhere—Church, von Neumann, and Turing all smiled as those echoes and whispers went by.

这些基础知识是古老的、久经考验的、真实的。无论在边缘添加了多少新的绒毛，这些基础知识仍然存在，仍然相关，并且仍然是敏捷软件开发的核心。

Those basics are old, tried, and true. No matter how much new fluff is added around the edges, those basics are still there, still relevant, and still the core of Agile software development.

后记

Afterword

作者：Eric Crichlow，2019 年 4 月 5 日

By Eric Crichlow, April 5, 2019

我可以很容易地回忆起我的第一份工作，他们决定过渡到敏捷。那是在 2008 年，一家被大公司收购的公司。它正在对其政策、程序和人员进行重大更改。我还记得其他一些强调敏捷实践的工作。这些仪式得到了虔诚的遵循：冲刺计划、演示、冲刺审查……在其中一个仪式上，公司的每位开发人员都接受了由经过认证的 Scrum Master 进行的为期两天的敏捷培训。作为一名移动开发人员，他们让我编写了一个用于玩 Agile Poker 的移动应用程序。

I can easily recall the first job I had where they decided to transition to Agile. That was in 2008 at a company that had been acquired by a larger corporation. It was undergoing significant changes to its policies, procedures, and personnel. I can also remember a couple of other jobs where an emphasis was placed on Agile practices. The rituals were followed religiously: sprint planning, demo, sprint review… At one of them, every developer in the company was put through two days of Agile training with a certified Scrum Master. As a mobile developer, they had me write a mobile app for playing Agile Poker.

但自从我第一次接触敏捷以来的 11 年里，我也曾在几家公司工作过，老实说，我不记得他们是否使用过敏捷实践。也许那是因为敏捷已经变得如此无处不在，以至于人们很容易认为它是理所当然的，甚至不去想它。或者可能是因为仍有大量组织尚未采用它。

But in the 11 years since my first exposure to Agile, I have also been at several companies where I honestly can’t remember whether they used Agile practices. Maybe that’s because Agile has become so ubiquitous that it’s easy to take it for granted and not even think about it. Or maybe it’s because there are still a significant number of organizations that haven’t adopted it.

在我接触敏捷的时候，我并不是特别热衷于它。Waterfall 可能有它的问题，但我在一个没有花大量时间编写设计文档的组织中。作为一名开发人员，我的生活通常包括被口头告知下一个版本中预期的一组功能，被告知下一个版本的到期日期，以及放手让奇迹发生。虽然这肯定会导致可怕的死亡行军，但它也让我可以自由地按照我想要的方式安排我的活动。这也让我摆脱了每日站立会议的频繁审查和问责，在那里我必须解释我昨天做了什么以及今天要做什么。如果我决定花一个星期重新发明轮子，

At the time I was introduced to Agile, I wasn’t particularly enthusiastic about it. Waterfall may have its problems, but I was in an organization that didn’t spend a significant amount of time writing design documents. My life as a developer generally consisted of being verbally given a set of features expected in the next release, being given a date when the next release was due, and being turned loose to make the magic happen. While this could certainly lead to the dreaded death march, it also gave me the freedom to structure my activities the way I wanted to. It also kept me free of the frequent scrutiny and accountability of a daily standup meeting where I would have to explain what I had worked on yesterday and what I would be working on today. If I decided to spend a week reinventing the wheel, I was free to do so without having that choice judged by anyone because they were blissfully unaware that I was doing it.

我曾在其手下工作的一位前开发总监曾称我们为“代码抛掷者”。我们只是喜欢在软件开发的狂野西部敲打我们的键盘。他是对的。在某种程度上，敏捷实践代表了统治我们特立独行倾向的新治安官。

A former Director of Development under whom I worked used to refer to us as “code slingers.” We just loved blasting away at our keyboards in the Wild West of software development. He was right. And to an extent, Agile practices represented the new sheriff in town that reigned in our maverick tendencies.

敏捷在赢得我的支持方面有一些工作要做。

Agile had some work to do in winning me over.

认为敏捷是软件开发公司事实上的标准或所有开发人员都将其视为积极的东西是自以为是的。相反，否认敏捷在软件开发领域的重要性是天真的。但这到底是什么意思？它的意义到底是什么？

It would be presumptuous to believe that Agile is the de-facto standard in software development houses or that all developers embrace it as something positive. Conversely, it would be naive to deny the significance of Agile in the world of software development. But what does that even mean? What, exactly, is its significance?

询问“敏捷组织”中的开发人员什么是敏捷，与询问软件开发经理级别以外的任何人相比，您可能会得到截然不同的答案。也许这就是这本书最有启发性的地方。

Ask the developers in an “Agile organization” what Agile is, and you’ll likely get a very different answer than if you ask anyone beyond the level of a software development manager. Perhaps that is where this book has been the most enlightening.

开发人员将敏捷理解为一种简化开发过程并使软件开发更可预测、更实用和更易于管理的方法。我们从这个角度来看它是合理的，因为它是最直接影响我们的角度。

Developers understand Agile to be a methodology for streamlining the development process and for making software development more predictable, more practicable, and more manageable. It’s reasonable that we look at it from this perspective because it’s the perspective that most directly affects us.

从个人经验来看，许多开发人员很幸运地没有意识到管理层对敏捷实践实施所提供的指标及其产生的数据的使用。在某些组织中，整个开发团队都会参加讨论这些指标的会议；但在许多其他情况下，开发人员甚至不知道这些讨论会发生。此外，也许在某些情况下，这些讨论实际上并没有发生。

Speaking from personal experience, many developers are blissfully unaware of management’s use of the metrics provided by the implementation of Agile practices and the data it produces. In some organizations, the entire development team participates in the meetings where these metrics are discussed; but in many others, the developers have no idea that these discussions even take place. Moreover, perhaps in some, those discussions don’t actually happen.

虽然我早就意识到敏捷的这个方面，但我仍然发现理解本书提供的这种方法的创始人的初衷和思维过程很有启发性。也很高兴看到这些创始人人性化。他们不是一群超级精英的软件架构师，不是由软件工程大师任命的，也不是由软件程序员大众选出的来传承经典的。他们是一群经验丰富的开发人员，他们对如何让他们的工作和生活更轻松、压力更小有想法。他们厌倦了在注定要失败的环境中工作，并希望营造能够成功的环境。

While I have long been aware of this aspect of Agile, I still found it enlightening to understand the original intent and thought processes of the founders of this methodology that this book provides. It was also good to see those founders humanized. They weren’t some set of ultra-elite software architects, ordained by the Software Engineering Masters or elected by the software programmer masses to hand down canon. They were a set of experienced developers with ideas about how to make their jobs, and their lives, easier and less stressful. They were tired of working in environments destined for failure and wanted to foster environments that allowed for success.

这听起来像我工作过的每家公司的大多数开发人员。

This sounds like most developers at every company where I’ve ever worked.

如果 Snowbird 会议在 15 年后举行，我可以看到是我和我个人共事过的许多开发人员召集了那次会议并将这些想法写成电子纸。但作为另一群经验丰富的开发人员，这群人很容易产生幻想，而这些幻想在现实的企业软件开发世界中可能并不适用。也许这一切都按照高端顾问的设计运作，有权提出要求并要求组织和管理层履行他们的承诺，但我们大多数人都是软件工厂机器中的咕噜声，齿轮。我们是可替代的，我们的影响力很小。因此，当涉及到像《权利法案》这样的事情时，我们明白这是一种理想，但对我们大多数人来说还没有实现。

Had the Snowbird meeting taken place 15 years later, I could see it having been a number of developers with whom I have personally worked and myself, who convened that meeting and put those ideas to digital paper. But being just another group of seasoned developers, this group was prone to flights of fancy that might not play well in the real world of corporate software development. Maybe it all works as designed in the world of highend consultants with the authority to make demands and hold organizations and management to their commitments, but most of us are grunts, cogs in the machinery of software factories. We are replaceable, and we have very little leverage. So when it comes to things like The Bill of Rights, we understand that this is an ideal, but one that is not realized for the majority of us.

借助当今的社交媒体社区，我很高兴看到许多新的开发人员超越了 CS 学位和朝九晚五的开发工作的界限，与世界各地的其他开发人员联系，以多种不同的方式学习，并将他们自己的知识和经验用于教导和启发其他初出茅庐的开发人员。我完全期待这些年轻后起之秀的数字聚会会带来方法论的下一次巨变。

With the social media communities of today, I am heartened to see many new developers extending themselves beyond the boundaries of a CS degree and 9-to-5 development job, connecting with other developers around the world, learning in any number of different ways, and putting their own knowledge and experiences out there to teach and inspire other fledgling developers. I fully expect the next sea change in methodology to emerge from a digital gathering of these young up-and-comers.

因此，在我们等待下一代将向我们展示的下一件大事的同时，让我们花点时间重新评估一下我们目前所处的位置以及我们必须处理的事情。

So while we await the Next Big Thing that the next generation will reveal to us, let’s take a minute to reassess where we are and what we have to work with at present.

既然您已经阅读了这本书，请考虑一下。考虑一下您可能知道但没有过多考虑的敏捷方面。从负责规划发布或创建产品路线图的业务分析师、项目经理或除开发经理以外的任何其他人员的角度考虑。考虑开发人员对敏捷过程的输入给他们带来了什么价值。了解您对流程的投入如何影响接下来两周的工作量，而不仅仅是您的工作量。然后回去再翻一遍这本书。如果您以这种更广阔的视角来处理它，我相信您会收集到更多有用的见解。

Now that you’ve read this book, contemplate it for a minute. Consider the aspects of Agile you may have known about but to which you hadn’t given much thought. Think about it from the perspective of the business analyst, project manager, or anything-other-than-dev manager responsible for planning releases or creating product roadmaps. Consider what value the input from developers into the Agile processes brings to them. Understand how your input into the process affects more than just your workload for the next two weeks. Then go back and skim the book again. If you approach it with this broader perspective in mind, I believe you will glean even more useful insights.

完成后，鼓励您组织中的另一位开发人员阅读它并进行同样的反省。甚至可能将这本书交给某个不是开发人员的人，等等。将其交给公司“业务”方面的人员。我几乎可以向你保证，他们从未认真考虑过《权利法案》。如果你让他们明白这些权利与他们从敏捷中提取的指标一样是敏捷不可或缺的一部分，你的生活就会变得更加愉快。

Once you’ve done that, encourage another developer in your organization to read it and undergo the same introspection. Maybe even hand the book to someone who, wait for it… isn’t a developer. Give it to someone on the “business” side of the company. I would almost guarantee you that The Bill of Rights is something they have never given much thought to. Your life stands to be much more pleasant if you get them to understand that these rights are just as integral to Agile as the metrics that they pull out of it.

您可能会说敏捷已经成为软件开发领域中一种类似于宗教的东西。我们中的许多人已经接受它作为最佳实践。为什么？对于许多人来说，这是因为他们被告知如此。这已成为传统；这就是事情的完成方式。对于新一代的企业开发人员来说，它就是这样。他们，甚至我们许多老前辈都不知道这一切从何而来，也不知道最初的目标、目的和做法是什么。说出你对宗教的看法，但最好的信奉者是那些努力理解他们信仰的人，而不仅仅是相信他们被告知的东西。与宗教一样，没有一个普遍接受的、放之四海而皆准的版本。

You might say that Agile has become something akin to a religion in the realm of software development. Many of us have accepted it as a best practice. Why? For many, it’s because they’ve been told so. It has become tradition; it’s just how things are done. For a new generation of corporate developers, it just is. They, and even many of us old-timers don’t really know where it all came from, nor what the original goals, purposes, and practices were all about. Say what you will about religion, but the best adherents to it are those who make the effort to understand what they believe, beyond just believing what they are told. And as with religion, there isn’t one universally accepted, one-size-fits-all version.

想象一下了解您的宗教起源的重要性，了解塑造您的正典的事件和思想。谈到您的职业生涯，这正是您在这里所拥有的。尽其所能地使用它，将它传播给你影响范围内的其他人，重新找回最初的目标，这个目标是你和几乎所有与你共事过的人都渴望、谈论过的，而且可能已经放弃了。使成功的软件开发成为可能。使组织目标可实现。让事情变得更好的过程。

Imagine the significance of having a view into the origins of your religion, an understanding of the events and thoughts that shaped what would become canon for you. When it comes to your professional life, that’s exactly what you have here. Use it for all it’s worth, evangelize it to the others in your sphere of influence, and reclaim the original goal, the goal you and practically everyone you’ve ever worked with have longed for, talked about, and probably given up on. Make successful software development achievable. Make organizational goals attainable. Make the process of making things better.
